an artist's attempt to project the image of mount rushmore onto the side of a chicago building, with the faces of passers-by playing the parts of the four presidents, didn't quite come off as planned friday
but some residents still gave david fitzgerald high marks for attempting his ``urban mount rushmore'' video display, though the images were much less clear than he had planned
it's a good way to start,'' said david harris, 23, of chicago, who was among a handful of people who stopped through the chicago loop on his way home to watch the show
harris and his friend, mark flower, also 23, said that even though they expected the images to be larger and easier to see, it probably was the closest they would get to mount rushmore
fitzgerald said that, overall, he wasn't disappointed by his photographic blending of the faces of passers-by with the figures of george washington, abraham lincoln, thomas jefferson and teddy roosevelt
we thought the glass would reflect better,'' said fitzgerald, 24, a graduate student at the school of the art institute of chicago. ``but the glass is reflecting so much that it's acting like a mirror.''
images of washington and lincoln, about 20 feet wide and 16 feet tall, flashed onto the windows on the side of the kluczinski federal building. but while fitzgerald said they were clearly visible to the people attending a private dinner on the sixth floor of the union league building across the street, they were harder for street-level pedestrians to recognize
fitzgerald's idea was to take snapshots of as many as 40 people walking by the union league building. powerful video equipment was set up to project the images of those photos combined with images of the figures on mount rushmore on the side of the federal building
the federal building is this city's urban mount rushmore and seemed like the obvious place that we should project them,'' said fitzgerald
the project was designed to give urban dwellers the chance to see the historic granite carvings at almost actual size _ a sight usually reserved for tourists who make the trek to the black hills of south dakota
the union league, a civic foundation founded while lincoln was president, decided to sponsor the event as the centerpiece of a private dinner
fitzgerald has brought images of other gigantic historic statues to the city
for the fourth of july in 1986, he used 12 projectors to recreate a lifesize image of the face of the statue of iberty on a wall of the art institute, he said
during a chicago bears game in 1985, fitzgerald projected a mammoth ``bears no. 1'' across the prudential, cna insurance and standard oil buildings
art should be for all the people all the time. i really want to bring my art to the common people,'' fitzgerald said
and along the way, i hope to make a couple of people smile.'' campaign</head> should stand for ams</note>
tennessee sen. albert gore jr., billing himself as ``entirely different'' from his democratic presidential rivals, tangled with rep. richard gephardt and gov. michael dukakis thursday night in a crackling debate that raised the curtain on a three-week campaign for southern support
dukakis and gephardt fired back, with the massachusetts governor telling gore ``you'd better be accurate'' with accusations and the missouri congressman telling him to check ``your own record first'' before making charges of campaign flip-flops
in one tart exchange, gephardt said some of gore's campaign positions were so conservative that he seemed ``more like al haig than al gore.''
shot back gore:
that line sounds more like richard nixon than richard gephardt.''
five of the six remaining democratic presidential contenders participated in the two-hour debate on the southern methodist university campus. with the iowa caucuses and new hampshire primary concluded, the debate marked the opening event in the run-up to super tuesday, the march 8 round of primaries and caucuses _ primarily in southern and border states _ in which nearly a third of the democratic national convention delegates will be picked
bruce babbitt withdrew from the race earlier thursday, and illinois sen. paul simon skipped the debate to campaign elsewhere
dukakis, winner of last tuesday's new hampshire primary, took a dig at gephardt, first-place finisher in the iowa caucuses
i think we were all a little surprised when dick last saturday stood up and said he was proud to vote for the reagan tax bill'' after telling iowans that he did so only as a last resort, he said
the debate resumed in the back room after the television cameras were turned off
said gore: ``i think it's fair to lay out the record and lay it on the line.''
said gephardt: ``he probably thinks i'm ahead in the south and he's got to jump-start his campaign to have a chance.''
much of the on-stage fireworks were initiated by gore in the two-hour confrontation that contained some of the most pointed language of the democratic race for the white house
i'm not going to sit here and listen to that,'' dukakis said after the tennessee senator accused him of a willingness to accept a soviet client state in nicaragua. ``if you're going to be president of the united states you better be accurate.''
gephardt sat silently when gore accused him of a long list of shifts in positions on critical campaign issues, from reaganomics to abortion, and said a president has to stand his ground against pressure, whether from soviet leader mikhail gorbachev or domestic groups
but a few moments later, the missouri congressman acidly replied that he had listened to gore's ``lecture on consistency,'' adding, ``maybe you ought to start looking at your own record first.''
at another point, gephardt slapped down gore's decision to skip the iowa caucus and minimize his efforts in new hampshire's primary. ``i don't think people vote for political strategies,'' said the missouri congressman
there were moments of humor during the two hours, such as when gore declared that dukakis was a good governor, ``and i think you ought to keep right on being governor.''
but there was plenty of political thrust and parry, as well
gary hart said he didn't question gephardt's motives in supporting a tough trade bill, but added, ``we all know the road to hell is paved with ... good intentions.''
i think if dick's bill ever went into effect it would be a catastrophe, and the first casualty in any trade war would be american workers and farmers.''
jesse jackson, like gore looking to appeal to a natural constituency, drew one of the loudest rounds of applause when he said the united states is making products that consumers don't want to buy
how many of you own an mx missile? not one,'' he said in a now-familiar refrain
gore sought to set himself apart as he noted that democrats have lost four of the last five presidential elections
i'm saying something in this campaign that is entirely different from what these other candidates are saying. this is the time for a democratic nominee who is in support not only of economic growth and social justice but also a strong america.''
gore also was the aggressor from the opening bell
i listen to mike (dukakis) talk and it sounds a litle different from what he said in iowa a week ago ... when he implied it would be all right to have a soviet client state in central america,'' gore said. ``if the president of the united states said that in office it could have catastrophic consequences.''
dukakis shot back: ``i never ever said that _ please get your facts straight.''
as for gephardt, gore said the missouri congressman's tough trade bill would deal with only a small portion of the nation's trade problem
he said the leading cause of the nation's trade deficit was reaganomics ``which gephardt supported when it was put in.'' with gephardt's trade bill, he said, ``we will never be able to get the kind of trade surpluses in the next decade that we need.''
dukakis also addressed the trade issue, saying, ``we've got to make made in america the international symbol for quality and value and durability once again.''
the debate was provided to public broadcasting stations and moderated by roger mudd
the republican candidates were scheduled to meet in a similar debate friday night, but sen. bob dole and former television evangelist pat robertson announced thursday afternoon that they would not participate. there was no word from the two remaining gop contenders, vice president george bush and rep. jack kemp
a passenger bus trying to pass on a curve in the eastern state of veracruz on thursday slammed into a gasoline truck, killing 17 people and injuring 14 others, authorities said
the impact caused the gasoline truck to explode near tierra blanca, 22 miles west of the port of veracruz on the gulf of mexico
the accident occurred at 6:32 a.m
luis edmundo perez garcia, a spokesman for the mexican red cross, said it appeared the accident happened when the driver of the bus tried to pass another vehicle on a curve
he said most of the bus passengers were laborers traveling to their jobs on an oil exploration rig in the town of cotlaxta. say</head>
president reagan's modest proposals for education and social spending next year drew a relatively warm reception on capitol hill, but two committee chairmen said his budget requests still aren't high enough
rep. augustus hawkins, chairman of the house education and labor committee, said the extra spending authority sought for education programs will not enable more children to participate in head start or chapter 1, the federal tutoring program for academically disadvantaged children
we intend to press for funding over and above the president's request'' to meet and surpass inflation, hawkins, d-calif., said in a statement following the unveiling thursday of reagan's $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 spending blueprint
sen. edward kennedy, chairman of the senate labor and human resources committee, said ``crucial domestic programs'' are shortchanged in the reagan budget despite its education increases
i am concerned that overall spending for social programs will not even keep up with inflation,'' said kennedy, d-mass
reagan just last year asked for cuts of nearly $5 billion in the education budget. this year he is seeking an 8 percent or $1.5 billion increase for a total of $20.3 billion in expected spending during fiscal 1989
about a third of the money would be added to the pell grant program for needy college and trade school students. grants would rise from $2,200 to $2,300 a year for total pell grant spending of nearly $5 billion
another third would be spent on chapter 1, bringing that spending total to nearly $4.4 billion. the program serves 5.6 million students at academic risk
the rest would fund modest expansions of a number of programs, including magnet schools, drug education, adult literacy and handicapped education. the administration also is proposing a college savings bond program under which interest on bonds used for tuition would be tax-free
the administration requested modest increases in several social programs, including rental vouchers for low-income families, drug abuse prevention, foster care and adoption assistance, and prenatal care for pregnant women
but some programs for the needy would suffer cuts under the proposal, including a $400 million, 25 percent drop in help for the poor to pay heating and cooling bills. head start would be frozen at $1.2 billion, and other social programs would be left with no increases or small ones lagging behind inflation
the areas still targeted for critical cuts, such as emergency food and shelter for the homeless, child abuse, discretionary grants and schooling for migrants, show that the administration still wants to save money at the expense of the most vulnerable americans,'' said marian wright edelman, president of the children's defense fund
the national council on senior citizens condemned the cuts in heating and cooling bill subsidies and in housing programs for low-income elderly and rural residents. they constitute ``a grim reminder that the reagan administration does not now, nor has it ever had, compassion for the neediest citizens in our society,'' the group said
many reacted with amusement and skepticism to the administration's reversal on education, pointing out that the only other time the president asked for an education budget increase was in 1984
we shouldn't be surprised. this is an election year,'' said mary hatwood futrell, president of the national education association. ``in election years, the reagan administration `supports' education.''
education secretary william bennett said the turnaround came because ``the president has decided to make education a priority'' and because the administration realized after several rebuffs that it was a waste of time to present cuts to congress
he added: ``it's not politically dumb, that's for certain.''
the reagan administration, concerned about threats to u.s rights to overseas military bases, is proposing a $150 million increase in aid to three strategic allies _ greece, turkey and portugal
the administration also is seeking a slight increase in relief funds, enough to settle 68,500 refugees in the united states next year. but officials expressed concern that it won't be enough to cope with an expected new influx of vietnamese boat people and others
deputy secretary of state john c. whitehead outlined thursday what he termed a ``bare bones'' request for $18.1 billion in spending authority for foreign aid and state department operations in the fiscal year starting next oct. 1
the total includes $14.3 billion in overseas economic and military aid commitments and $3.8 billion for the state department, the u.s. information agency and other foreign affairs operations, including embassies and consulates
the figures would not represent actual outlays, because some of the money will be spent on projects extending over several years. the outlay figure for foreign aid is expected to be several billion dollars less than the $14.3 billion request
the budget had few surprises, but some of the requests reflected new u.s. concerns about conditions abroad
the plan calls for a combined commitment of $1.12 billion in assistance to turkey, greece and portugal, an increase of $150 million over the current allocation
all three countries provide bases for u.s. forces, and have said their willingness to play host depends on how well washington assists them
portugal and the united states are reviewing an agreement that permits american use of lajes air base in the azores through 1991. that country would get a $163 million commitment next year, compared with $117 million this year
turkey would get $623.5 million, up from $525.3 million, and greece would get $351.1 million, compared with $344.1 million this year
negotiations with greece for renewal of base rights that expire next year are about to begin. turkey and the united states recently signed a base rights agreement, but the turkish government has frozen ratification proceedings partly to protest u.s. aid levels
congress traditionally has ignored state department aid requests for greece and turkey and recalculated assistance to comply with an unwritten practice of giving greece $7 for every $10 given to its bigger and poorer rival, turkey
reagan's budget plan calls for $340 million in refugee assistance to allow 68,500 displaced people to enter the united states. that is about the same number resettled in the current year
it is not as large an increase as we need, in view of our estimates of refugee flows,'' whitehead said, adding that there will be more vietnamese boat people and an higher level of soviet jews and armenians
we're not really sure just where the money will come from to cope with the refugees that will be coming out,'' whitehead said
as usual, israel and egypt would be the major beneficiaries of u.s. foreign aid next year, with combined commitments of $5.3 billion in economic and military assistance
the more than 40 aid recipients in sub-saharan africa, the world's poorest region, would share $733 million in economic assistance commitments
military aid to eight latin-american nations that were cut out of the 1988 program would be reinstated. latin america as a whole would get $90 million more in projected economic assistance and $55 million more in military aid than current levels
the administration proposed to eliminate aid to ireland, which received $35 million in commitments this year. whitehead said the decision was based on a perception that the united states ``does not receive a real return'' on its investment there
a woman who poured gasoline into her washing machine to remove oil from dirty clothes was burned thursday when the dryer ignited the fumes, a fire department spokesman said
the unidentified woman had added about a gallon of gasoline to the soap and water, said the spokesman, russell brown
she was treated at a hospital for second- and third-degree burns on her arms and face brown and was released, fire officials said
firefighters found the woman's frightened young son hiding under a table, said brown. the child was unhurt
the fire quickly extinguished itself and the house sustained little damage except to the washing machine and windows blown out by the explosion, said brown
anthony m. kennedy is quickly getting down to cases after taking his place as the newest member of the supreme court with a pledge to uphold a constitution that he said makes the united states unique
the constitution of the united states is the single idea, the single fact, the single reality, the single moral principle that sets the united states apart from other nations, now and throughout history,'' kennedy said during a white house swearing-in ceremony. ``i shall honor that constitution.''
kennedy, 51, on thursday became the 104th supreme court justice in u.s. history, restoring the court to full strength for the first time in eight months and inheriting a pivotal vote on key issues
today he meets in a private conference with the other eight justices to discuss pending cases and prepare for the court's return monday from a four-week recess
kennedy, who has been reading legal briefs in preparation for his new duties, appeared relaxed as he posed for cameras outside the court building
i've been working. i'm ready for monday,'' he said
one of the first cases in which kennedy will hear arguments next week focuses on whether private clubs may exclude women and racial minorities as members
the case has attracted considerable attention and kennedy's participation will be watched closely. he was criticized during his senate confirmation hearings for his past membership in such exclusive clubs
kennedy took part in two oath-taking ceremonies thursday
at the first in the ornate courtroom where the justices meet to hear arguments, he said, ``i do solemnly swear that i will administer justice without respect to persons and do equal right to the poor and to the rich.''
he then took his seat at one end of the high court bench reserved for the supreme court's newest member
later, kennedy went to the white house to a take a second oath of office in the presence of president reagan
justice kennedy has shown a consistency and a courageous dedication to preserving ours as a government of laws, and that's why i nominated him,'' the president said
he won the respect of his colleagues and of the entire legal community,'' reagan said. ``lawyers and judges of all persuasions characterize him as fair, open-minded and scholarly.''
kennedy gave a thumbs-up salute with both hands after the audience in the east room of the white house applauded him
kennedy was reagan's third choice to succeed justice lewis. f. powell, who retired june 26
reagan's first choice, robert h. bork, was rejected in a bitter senate battle and the next appointee, douglas h. ginsburg, withdrew after admitting he had smoked marijuana occasionally while a law professor
reagan did not attend the courtroom swearing-in ceremony. also absent were justice thurgood marshall, who was attending a meeting in hawaii, and the three former court members still living: powell, warren e. burger and arthur goldberg
chief justice william h. rehnquist welcomed kennedy by wishing him ``a long and happy career in our common calling.''
unanimously confirmed by the senate, kennedy is viewed as a moderate conservative with an open-minded approach to issues involving civil rights and individual liberties
but little is known about his specific views on abortion regulation, affirmative action, church-state relations or the other politically sensitive issues on which the high court is closely divided
he is the third reagan appointee to join the court, following justices sandra day o'connor and antonin scalia
reagan also promoted rehnquist to chief justice when burger retired in 1986
secretary of state george shultz will be in a hurry to pack for the middle east after two days of talks in moscow next week, but he will go out of his way to stop in brussels to brief the nato alliance
then he'll jump aboard his air force jet and rush home having about 24 hours to shift gears, pack fresh laundry and head for the middle east to push a plan for arab-israeli negotiations that neither side is excited about
shultz will pause patiently at nato headquarters on tuesday to give the west europeans a blow-by-blow account of his talks with general secretary mikhail gorbachev and foreign minister eduard shevardnadze
he considers these briefings critical to the cohesion of the west european alliance. it's also shultz' way of making sure moscow knows that the united states is on guard against any attempt to divide the allies
the north atlantic treaty organization will get a bigger and more publicized boost on march 2
president reagan will hold a summit meeting with the 15 nato west european and canadian leaders. the aim is to reinforce the idea that the trans-atlantic alliance formed after world war ii remains the centerpiece of u.s. foreign policy
hundreds of reporters, photographers and television cameras will make sure the point is not lost on american and west european audiences
and yet, high-powered diplomacy and public relations aside, maintaining american unity with western europe in a nuclear-nervous era is not always easy
the dutch and the belgians did not want u.s. intermediate-range nuclear weapons on their soil. the danes opposed having the rockets anywhere in western europe. norway and spain are self-declared nuclear-free zones. france, with its own nuclear force, does not take part in various nato deliberations
west germany in 1979 readily accepted the pershing 2 and cruise missiles that now will be withdrawn over three years. but significant segments of the west german electorate and political spectrum wanted the united states to move on to negotiations to cut back battlefield nuclear weapons
nato decided in 1983 to scrap 1,400 of the oldest nuclear arms in western europe. but many of the american weapons that remain and are below the 315-mile intermediate range will be replaced with newer ones
no alliance allows its forces to defend itself ... with weapons from yesteryear,'' assistant secretary of state rozanne ridgway said wednesday. ``modernization is an ongoing process. we are not prepared to defend europe with weapons from the 1890s.''
large numbers of the new arms would be deployed in west germany
she said the west german government supported the program and was not pushing for negotiations to reduce the current tactical arsenals
there is no move for the removal of the tactical nuclear weapons from europe,'' the u.s. official said
actually, the west germans would have preferred giving top priority to negotiating a reduction in tactical nuclear weapons now that the united states and the soviet union have signed a treaty to scrap 2,700 intermediate-range rockets
but shultz and the 15 western foreign ministers resolved at a nato meeting last year in reykjavik, iceland, to place three other items on the top of the agenda: a strategic nuclear weapons cutback, a ban on chemical weapons and eliminating the warsaw pact's edge in ground forces
now that the west germans have backed off, the reagan administration can concentrate on still another problem: the future of u.s. bases in western europe
while prime minister andreas papandreou has dropped all discussion of pulling greece out of nato, he has not withdrawn his threats to close u.s. military bases on greek soil. portuguese prime minister anibal cavaco silva has threatened to scrap a treaty that allows american use of a base in the azores islands. and the united states is still looking for a home for the 72 f16 fighter-bombers spain is ordering out of the torrejon base near madrid
barry schweid is head of the ap's state department staff
gop presidential hopefuls sen. bob dole and pat robertson said they won't participate in a debate here tonight. their campaigns charged the event would be packed with supporters of vice president george bush
the withdrawals leave only bush and new york rep. jack kemp scheduled to attend. bush was saying thursday that he still planned to participate
we had one of those (bush) pep rallies in houston. i don't see why we have to have two of them in one candidate's home state,'' dole told reporters after a rally in the rotunda of the georgia capitol
richie martin, robertson's state campaign director, said he also thought the event was ``stacked for bush.''
dole complained that organizers of the debate at southern methodist university _ sponsored by the dallas morning news, kera-tv and texas monthly magazine _ had given his campaign only 60 of 2,600 tickets for the debate audience
but burl osborne, president and editor of the dallas morning news, said all the campaigns received 60 tickets each
it is preposterous to try to blame their decision to withdraw on the morning news as dole's representatives have tried to do,'' osborne said in a statement
he complains that he received only 60 tickets. that is the same number of tickets allotted to each candidate _ no more, no less,'' the statement said
osborne said 304 tickets went to smu for distribution on campus
debate organizers received on-again, off-again reports that dole would withdraw and that dole was trying to persuade robertson to pull out too, osborne said
we hope that sen. dole and mr. robertson do not write off texas and merely go away. we will have chairs for them at the debate and we hope they use them,'' he said
the democratic presidential candidates, except for sen. paul simon, debated thursday night under the sponsorship of the same organizations
restraint is the note struck by president reagan's 1989 budget proposal, but the administration still found room in the $1.1 trillion spending plan for new projects and hefty increases in old programs
much of the budget, the last of reagan's presidency, has been pre-ordained by a deficit-cutting deal he cut with congress in negotiations spurred by the october stock market crash
it offers few new ways to spend money and retreats from the administration's favorite use of tax dollars: the military. the pentagon would get only a $9 billion boost to $294 billion. it's the smallest ever proposed by reagan and doesn't even keep up with inflation
however there were some winners, including the agency that regulates the stock market. the securities and exchange commission would get a 19 percent budget increase and 153 new employees
science and space programs are among the biggest beneficiaries. while domestic programs overall will increase by only 2 percent, spending on science will increase 20 percent to $13.1 billion
leading the list is a huge new atomic research facility to study the building blocks of matter. the energy department would get $363 million next year to start construction of the superconducting super collider at a site yet to be chosen
national aeronautics and space administration administrator james fletcher says the president's budget establishes, for the first time, the goal of putting astronauts on other planets. it provides start-up money for the pathfinder project, a research program designed to put an american astronaut on mars early in the next century
it also earmarks nearly $1 billion for a permanent manned space station to orbit the earth by the mid-1990s and more than $1 billion in added funds to help get the space shuttle off the ground
the budget devotes $1.3 billion to research into preventing and treating acquired immune deficiency syndrome, a 38 percent boost
another new element in the reagan budget is its treatment of education. last year the president proposed a $5 billion cut. this year he calls for a $1.5 billion increase to $20.3 billion
and, the president proposes a new program to help low- and middle-income parents save for their children's education. purchasers of u.s. savings bonds wouldn't have to pay taxes on the interest if they're cashed to pay for college tuition
on the revenue side of the budget, reagan reprises many of his ``privatization'' proposals of the past: sale of government loans; sale of amtrak, the government-owned passenger rail service; and sale of military housing. one new proposal is a private plan to mediate disputes that now choke the u.s. tax court
among other highlights of the budget, released thursday, were:
_$3.9 billion, a 13 percent boost, for drug law enforcement and treatment
_$2.5 billion over five years to fight acid rain
_$1.6 billion, a 44 percent increase, to improve the air traffic control system
_nearly $1 billion for the new worker readjustment program (wrap)
wrap will provide counseling, job search assistance, education and training aimed at helping displaced workers move into new careers. it replaces two other federal programs: one which provides unemployment benefits after unemployment insurance runs out and a second that pays states to help dislocated workers
the federal government has until the end of today to appeal a court decision that paves the way for a merger between two of the nation's largest manufacturers of glass containers
on thursday, u.s. district judge joyce hens green rejected the federal trade commission's request for a preliminary injunction to block the merger between toledo, ohio-based owens-illinois inc. and brockway inc. of jacksonville, fla., ruling that the ftc had not proven the deal would hurt competition
the ftc had sought to stop the merger while it conducts administrative proceedings on its complaint that the combination of the nation's second- and third-largest glass-container makers threatened to violate antitrust laws by reducing competition
but the judge rejected the agency's claims, saying: ``the ftc has not shown the possibility of harm to competition that would occur between the denial of the preliminary injunction and final adjudication.''
green accepted the argument advanced by the two manufacturers that competition from the plastics and metal-packaging industry will keep down prices
the trend in packaging is definitely toward a greater variety of container alternatives rather than fewer,'' the judge said. ``counterbalancing the potential for direct impact on glass prices through price discrimination, the other relevant effect on price and supply would be efficiencies to be gained from the merger.''
last month, the judge concluded four days of hearings on the ftc's motion to block the merger. she had issued a temporary restraining order stopping the deal, but it expires today
last september, owens-illinois proposed to buy brockway for $750 million, or $60 per share
the merger would make the combined company the largest manufacturer in the industry. the nation's top manufacturer is anchor glass container corp., which controls 23.7 percent of the market
owens-illinois has a 22.7 percent share of the market, while brockway controls 15 percent of sales
the ftc has said the merger might violate federal antitrust laws by substantially reducing competition in the glass container industry and creating conditions for price discrimination
but attorneys for owens-illinois said the purpose of the merger is to achieve cost savings and efficiencies that will enable the combined companies to vigorously compete against the producers of plastics, metal and other types of packaging materials
fbi officials will report publicly to senators next week on the conduct of agents who spied on and infiltrated an organization opposed to president reagan's policies in central america
the senate intelligence committee asked for an internal probe after publicly released documents showed the bureau conducted a broad investigation of the committee in solidarity with the people of el salvador
the group, known as cispes, contends that the fbi's motives were political and that it was targeted because it opposes reagan's policies. cispes pointed out the march 1983-june 1985 investigation was closed down without any charges filed
fbi director william s. sessions was asked by the committee in closed session feb. 2 to conduct an internal probe of the bureau operation. although top fbi officials will present their interim findings tuesday, sessions will not appear until a later session, the committee said
committee chairman david boren, d-okla. and vice chairman william cohen, r-maine, said in a joint statement that ``while we will not draw any conclusions prematurely,'' they viewed ``violations of the civil rights of individual americans as an extremely serious matter.''
the hearing also will focus on the fbi's justification for conducting the investigation under broad guidelines that are supposed to be used when acts of international terrorism are carried out or planned
use of those guidelines gave the fbi more leeway to investigate cispes; the bureau has other guidelines for conducting domestic investigations which would have placed far more restrictions on agents' activities
the fbi has said it conducted a legitimate investigation into allegations that certain leaders and key members of cispes were covertly giving money and materials to a foreign terrorist organization. the fbi identified the group as the fmln, which is fighting the u.s.-backed government of el salvador
thursday, the fbi gave the committee more than 3,000 pages of still-classified documents on the investigation
another 2,000 documents have been released under the freedom of information act, and they show the fbi was concerned that some of its field offices were investigating protected political acts
representing the fbi tuesday will be executive assistant director oliver b. revell; bill gavin, assistant director in charge of the inspection division; bob ricks, deputy assistant director, criminal investigation division; and steve pomerantz, chief of the terrorism section of the criminal investigative division
the effectiveness of the national park service is threatened by political interference, a problem that is getting worse and can only be solved by making the agency independent, according to the nation's principal park advocacy organization
the popularity of the national parks inspires political appointees to curb the national park service's independence and limit its clout,'' said the national parks and conservation association in a set of recommendations released thursday
there is an urgent need to make the national park service an independent agency, responsible directly to the congress and the president'' because of ``increasing politicization,'' the association said
the recommendations ranged over a wide field, calling for, among other things, establishment of 75 new park units in the 340-unit system and expansion of 200 existing units
the report also urged the service to end the physical and administrative isolation of researchers; to install a systematic, understandable recruitment and hiring procedure; and to provide the chance for employees to move back and forth between general positions like ranger and specialist jobs like historian
conservationists have continually criticized the three interior secretaries of the reagan administration for their tight control over the service and their reluctance to seek funds for land acquisition. but paul pritchard, president of the association, said at the news conference introducing the report: ``it's not just this administration. the process doesn't work.''
defenders of the present system say the cabinet-rank interior secretary carries clout for the service in the white house. the association says it doesn't work that way:
more often, the service has taken its concern to the public and the congress, either publicly or privately, to overcome obstacles placed before it by political appointees of the department.''
if independent, ``the service would still have to compete against all other federal agencies for funding, (but) it would be able to compete without the filters and constraints of interior secretaries, who historically have reduced national park service funding requests to fit their own priorities.''
the service was founded in 1916 in the interior department to take care of the parks, the first of which was established in 1872. the service now has 340 national parks, monuments, battlefields, recreation areas, seashores and other units
many were added in the 1960s and 1970s by a congress delighted to discover a new political currency that won favor with constituents. only four units have been added under the reagan administration
all directors have been professional park managers with one exception: ron walker, a former campaign aide for president nixon. the current director, william penn mott, began his career with the service in the 1930s and served as state parks director in california under then-gov. ronald reagan before being appointed to his current job by interior secretary donald p. hodel
i don't think he's free to advocate,'' said rep. bruce vento, d-minn., chairman of the parks subcommittee of the house interior committee, at the news conference
vento said he was introducing a bill to transfer all the secretary's legal responsibilities for the parks to the director and to make the directorship a five-year presidential appointment. the director would have to be a professional parks manager confirmed by the senate and subject to removal only for cause. the bill also would establish a three-member board to advise congress on the parks
complaints about political direction are common in the government, but until recently have been rare in the park service. interior secretaries have tended to keep the directors they inherit, but there have been reports that some have not been above making it clear they'd like to see an early retirement
current employees say they are under tighter political rein than ever
vento's bill would not actually take the service out of the interior department, but he said it would accomplish the objectives the association seeks and ``be more acceptable by my colleagues.''
he said the association report ``sets forth a damning case against the politicization of one of the finest professional organizations in government.''
mott, said spokesman george berklacy, ``does not support the removal of the service from interior. he does not believe there is anything advantageous to that. he feels very strongly that the director of the national park service should be a professional park manager. a five-year presidential appointment is ok with him.''
the defense department issued some wordy marching orders this week for reporters preparing stories on its $299.5 billion budget request for next year
the aim was to prevent publication of budget details until noon thursday
in official washington, copies of complicated documents are routinely made available to journalists in advance of publication to give them time to absorb the complexities and write informed stories
the agency that issues the document sets the day and hour when the information can be released. in journalistic parlance, that's called an embargo
but the pentagon's budget embargo warning was more emphatic _ and a lot wordier _ than most
its budget embargo was to be a ``total embargo,'' no ifs, ands or buts
until release, none of this material may be paraphrased, hinted at or alluded to in any way,'' the pentagon declared
this material must not be discussed with or provided to others who have not accepted the package on an embargoed basis.''
the pentagon also laid out the rules under which it would discuss the contents of the budget
in advance of release, no telephone inquiries on this material will be accepted by defense department personnel,'' the department said. ``questions from news media correspondents must be asked in person and the requester must acknowledge acceptance of this embargo.''
just to make sure the message got across, the pentagon directive _ stamped top and bottom with the words _ hold for release _ added the following:
there is a total embargo on this budget, as stated above, which includes any and all references to any material in the budget or the budget appendix.''
two rival groups that sponsor chili cook-offs have removed a simmering dispute from the back burner and taken it into the courtroom
the chili appreciation society international inc. has been judging the fiery merits of this southwestern specialty since 1967. five years ago, an unincorporated spinoff group took the same name and started its own cookoff
both groups hold an annual championship cookoff each november near the west texas ghost town of terlingua
the older group has mounted a court challenge seeking to force the newer one to change its name. u.s. district judge lucius bunton said he would decide within 20 days which group will get to keep the chili appreciation society international name
frank x. tolbert, now deceased, helped organize the first cookoff in 1967 to publicize this ghost town
one of tolbert's early partners, ray king, testified wednesday that tolbert agreed in 1980 to incorporate the group, but later backed out because ``he didn't care much for rules and organization. he liked it like it started out.''
king and others incorporated the group, and tolbert accepted the organization's honorary title of ``supreme pepper.''
but in 1983, tolbert broke from the society and started a rival cookoff across the road from the original site at the vacant chisos saloon
the older, larger group has since moved its cookoff eight miles down the road to villa de la mina, where 2,500 participated last year
bunton likened the argument to the child-custody dispute king solomon resolved by ordering the baby cut in half
that's exactly what's happened to terlingua,'' bunton said. ``the baby is split. terlingua doesn't need two cookoffs.''
reagan administration plans to overhaul the u.s. sugar support system and drastically cut rural housing and telephone programs are headed for the same chilly reception that congress gave them in past years, farm-state democrats say
they were dead on arrival and will remain dead on arrival,'' rep. leon panetta, d-calif., said after president reagan submitted his proposed fiscal 1989 farm budget on thursday
panetta, a member of the house agriculture committee, characterized reagan's spending plan as ``a no-news budget'' and ``a rehash of old proposals.''
in any case, he said, legislators are in no mood to revamp farm programs so soon after approving a full-scale overhaul in the 1985 farm law
food programs, including food stamps and school lunches, remained largely untouched under reagan's proposed budget. there were no changes in most farm commodity programs except for the sugar program, which includes protective import quotas and price supports
the agriculture department wants to reduce the sugar price support from 18 cents a pound to 12 cents to make domestic sugar more competitive with imports. it contends that high supports artificially stimulate domestic production and forces the united states to impose tighter quotas on imports
most of the major decisions embodied in the proposed budget resulted from a summit agreement between congress and the white house on $76 billion in deficit-reducing savings over two years
accordingly, the administration proposed to cut overall farm spending by 5 percent, but dropped previous proposals for new user fees, changes in forest service payments to states, alterations in food assistance programs and turning the federal crop insurance program over to private enterprise
the 5 percent cut included a proposed reduction in farmers home administration rural housing programs from more than $3.3 billion this year to less than $1.4 billion in fiscal 1989, which starts oct. 1
also, 70 percent of rural electrification administration loans to rural telephone companies and cooperatives would be transformed into guaranteed loans from private lenders at an estimated government savings of $478 million
but congress has tossed these same proposals in the wastebasket in the past, and seems likely to do the same this year
this is not the leadership required to address the need for economic recovery in the thousands of rural communities that have been bypassed by the economic recovery,'' said sen. patrick j. leahy, d-vt., the chairman of the senate agriculture committee
said rep. glenn english, d-okla., a member of the house agriculture committee: ``this is not a budget that attempts to deal with real numbers. it is a philosophical budget, an attempt to use the budget in obtaining the reagan administration's philosophical goals.''
we recognize the need for budget discipline,'' said rep. e ``kika'' de la garza, d-texas, chairman of the house panel. but he said congress ``would remind the administration and the public that over recent years, agriculture has taken more than its fair share of budget cuts.''
according to the house budget committee, agriculture spending after inflation increased 109.8 percent from fiscal 1981 until fiscal 1987. the increase was caused largely by huge subsidy programs under the 1985 law that were intended to spur exports and revitalize the depressed farm economy
net outlays for farm payments by the agriculture department's commodity credit corp. peaked in 1986 at $25.8 billion. they have been falling since then to $17.7 billion currently, and are projected at $17.1 billion next year
reagan's budget proposed no new types of price-support payments, although some lawmakers have begun to push for new subsidies for soybeans and possibly other crops. states</head>
u.s. officials have drawn up a list of suspects in their search for a ``mr. x'' inside the government who they believe helped israel direct convicted spy jonathan jay pollard to critical secret documents, the washington post reported today
the post reported that justice department officials believe israel almost certainly had another espionage agent spying against the united states in addition to pollard, who has been sentenced to life in prison
however, no evidence has been developed yet that points to the specific identity of this second person, who has been dubbed ``mr. x,'' the post said, citing unidentified sources for its information
as we have indicated previously, there are unanswered questions in the case and the investigation continues,'' justice department spokesman terry eastland said
an israeli embassy spokesman, yossi gal, said the pollard case was an aberration and that the israeli government has no more spies in the united states
pollard was a navy intelligence analyst who was working at the navy's new antiterrorism alert center during the 17 months when he spied for israel. he was sentenced in march 1987 to life imprisonment after pleading guilty to selling secrets to israel. he was arrested in november 1985 outside the israeli embassy in washington and is imprisoned in springfield, mo
pollard's wife, anne henderson-pollard, was sentenced in march 1987 to five years imprisonment after she pleaded guilty to conspiracy to receive embezzled government property and being an accessory after the fact to possession of state secrets. she has been moved to the federal medical center in rochester, minn., where she is suffering from a digestive tract disease
the post, quoting unidentified sources, said the belief that a mr. x must exist grew out of a massive debriefing and polygraphing of pollard over many months
pollard told authorities that his israeli handlers often specified by date and document control number the highly sensitive u.s. documents they wanted him to acquire, the newspaper said
the handlers once showed him a top secret u.s. document to which pollard himself did not have access, the post said, identifying the document as an index or catalog that pollard then could use to obtain other documents from u.s. intelligence agencies
investigators concluded that another american _ mr. x _ had provided that index and other specific information on u.s. secrets that pollard learned from his israeli handlers, the newspaper said
prosecutors have said pollard sold israel enough classified documents to fill a large, walk-in closet and called the spy case one of the nation's worst
the reagan administration is taking aim at a favorite budget-cutting target again this year, the dams and irrigation projects that are cherished by members of congress
the white house spending plan for fiscal 1989, sent to the capitol on thursday, calls for construction starts on only a half-dozen water projects by the army corps of engineers. and for the second consecutive year, no new projects were proposed for the bureau of reclamation
a year ago, the president's 1988 budget request included funds to begin 13 corps projects out of the scores authorized by congress under a 1986 law that required local beneficiaries to start paying a share of the costs
for decades, congress had cooperated closely with the corps and the bureau, simultaneously expanding business for both agencies and providing lawmakers with public works projects to extoll during re-election campaigns
the congressional response to reagan's request last year for only 13 new construction starts was to appropriate money to begin 21 corps projects, ranging from flood control dams to replacement of sand on eroding beaches
there was no immediate reaction among legislators thursday to the administration's proposal to start only six new flood control projects in fiscal 1989, which begins oct. 1
the battle over reagan's request probably will be fought in coming months during closed meetings of the house and senate appropriations committees
the slow-growth spending plan for water projects was termed ``a good one'' by robert dawson, associate director of the white house office of management and budget for natural resources, energy and science
it's a strong water development budget, clearly founded on the concept that the user must help pay the cost,'' he said. ``it shows that worthy projects can proceed even in times of budget austerity.''
the fiscal 1989 request for the corps totals nearly $3.3 billion. the bulk of it is earmarked to continue work on 157 projects under construction and to operate and maintain more than 650 completed projects
the total for the corps' flood control, navigation, recreation and environmental repair activities is only about $52 million more than congress appropriated for the current fiscal year
spending by the bureau of reclamation, an interior department agency operating in western states, would total $1.07 billion in fiscal 1989, just $13 million more than congress approved for fiscal 1988
the bureau's budget request calls for higher spending to solve environmental problems caused by irrigation systems, in line with a major redirection of the agency's activities last year
the bureaucratic changes, which include transferring the majority of the bureau's washington staff to denver, was tied to the reclamation reality that nearly all the major rivers in the water-short west have been dammed
the bureau's budget also includes a reshuffling of construction priorities aimed at channeling increasingly limited funds to more quickly complete major projects such as central arizona and central utah
last year, congress rejected an administration attempt to make an even more drastic reallocation of money among projects under construction
the six newly proposed corps projects are cache creek settling basin and the santa ana river mainstem in california; sheyenne river, west fargo and riverside in north dakota; the ramapo and mahwah rivers in new jersey and new york; lock haven in pennsylvania, and nonconnah creek in tennessee and mississippi
the nikkei stock average closed at 24,773.41 points, up 98.05 points, on the tokyo stock exchange friday
the defense department wants to spend $9 billion on military construction projects in fiscal 1989, including more than $1 billion for work outside the united states
of the $9 billion, more than $200 million has already been authorized, meaning that about $8.8 billion in new funds is being sought
within the united states, the biggest winners would be california, new york, texas, alaska and washington state, primarily because of work on new bases or seaports
abroad, the pentagon plans to spend the most in west germany, south korea, the philippines, england and italy, in that order
the $81.4 million request for construction work in the philippines comes at a time of instability in that country and uncertainty over whether the government of president corazon aquino will approve extension of leases for the subic naval base and clark air base beyond 1991
the pentagon has said it expects to negotiate new leases for the bases and will continue improving them in the meantime
also contained in president reagan's fiscal 1989 budget request, sent to congress on thursday, is $3 million to ``upgrade facilities'' in honduras, where u.s. forces regularly engage in maneuvers as part of a u.s. campaign to deter nicaraguan expansion
the budget plan also includes $9.9 million to improve air fields in oman near the persian gulf and $16 million for a missile range complex in the kwajalein islands in the pacific ocean for experiments on reagan's star wars missile defense system
the funds for more than 1,100 construction projects at more than 600 sites were contained in reagan's request for $299.5 billion in pentagon spending authority for the budget year starting oct. 1, compared with $291.4 billion this year
the administration initially had planned to spend more than $10.6 billion for construction next year, but was forced to trim back because of a deficit-reduction agreement with congress last november
of the $9 billion construction total, the pentagon said it would spend nearly $5.8 billion on military facilities and nearly $3.3 billion on housing. by contrast, the department plans to spend $8.7 billion this year, including $5.5 billion on new facilities and $3.2 billion on housing
nearly $600 million would be spent next year to build 3,226 new housing units and improve 16,900 existing units. the remaining $2.7 billion would be for operating and maintaining the 413,000 existing family units, the pentagon said
the military facility projects include work to support the b-1 bomber, the mx missile, the ``stealth'' bomber and new ports for ships joining the navy's fleet
among the larger individual projects are $56.3 million for a new naval submarine base at kings bay, ga.; $214 million in previouly authorized money for the new home of a light infantry division at fort drum, n.y.; $72.5 million for a major star wars test facility at falcon air station, colo., and $53 million for a new aircraft carrier base at everett, wash
including family housing funds and previously authorized projects, the pentagon said it planned to spend $666 million in california, $309.5 million in new york, $217.6 million in texas, $202.2 million in alaska and $201.2 million in washington state
besides the philippines, foreign spending would include $421.1 million in west germany, $133.6 million in south korea, $77.7 million in england and $50.4 million in italy
bruce babbitt closed the doors on his presidential race in the same way that he campaigned _ with grace and humor, and a pledge to continue to keep fighting for his vision of america
the former arizona governor stood before a roomful of supporters, tv lights and reporters on thursday to announce what had become apparent since his dismal sixth-place showing in new hampshire on tuesday: that he was ending the marathon he had officially started on march 10
but there was hopeful news for the babbitt faithful _ their champion said he wasn't bowing out of the political arena completely
indeed, staffers at his new hampshire campaign office were answering the phone on thursday with the words, ``babbitt in '92.''
babbitt said he's making no plans for 1992, and hopes to be supporting an incumbent democratic president. nonetheless, he stated:
i want to be a positive part of this process. i'm not leaving _ it's too much fun, and i am too much an optimist, and too much an american who believes in the process to walk away from it or to say anything negative about the candidates.''
with an endorsement of the campaign process, if not of any rival candidate, babbitt said he intends to continue speaking out and ``chiding'' the other candidates because ``there's room for improvement'' in the field
babbitt's departure was relaxed, upbeat and laughter-filled, with no trace of bitterness that his long quest had ended so early in the 1988 primary season
the tall, lanky 49-year-old, flanked by his wife hattie and two young sons, cracked jokes, often as not poking fun at himself and the campaign that never caught fire. it was a babbitt typical of the man reporters covering him had grown to expect
babbitt seemed to have general affection for the press corps, which had bolstered his cash-poor campaign with a spate of positive articles highlighting his frankness, his willingness to take unpopular stands such as his call for a national sales tax, and his quotable and colorful remarks
at one point, the favorable publicity before the iowa caucuses , which never quite coincided with babbitt's low poll standings, came to be known as the ``babbitt boomlet.''
on thursday, babbitt kiddingly accused the media of a conspiracy to discredit him with the public by ``making me into kind of a house pet.''
as he left the podium, babbitt closed his news conference by saying, ``thank you very much, it's been an honor and a privilege.''
campaign manager fred duval said one supporter remarked to him afterward, ``that wasn't a press conference. that was an encounter group.''
in contrast to the rancorous withdrawals by past candidates who blamed press scrutiny for their troubles, duval said that one line that had been suggested to babbitt to use as he exited the race was, ``after this you won't have bruce babbitt to puff any more.''
the line was a parody of richard nixon's 1962 remark that he was leaving politics and the press wouldn't have him to ``kick around'' any more
babbitt seemed genuinely reluctant to leave the final press conference of his campaign, modestly stating that he had monopolized a half hour of reporters' time but would take a couple more questions, and then, ``i'll stay around for a while. ... as vicious and unprincipled as you've been, i hate to let loose,'' he joked
later at a farewell luncheon for his staff, the mood was teary and affectionate as loyalists recounted what the campaign had meant to them
there's been tears ... equal doses of disappointment and affection,'' said duval. ``everybody feels as if they've just tasted an extraordinary experience.''
even on the night of the new hampshire debacle, babbitt and his supporters partied as if they were at a victory celebration, the candidate and his wife dancing the twist until 1:30 a.m
they cheered every percentage point as a victory of sorts _ this collection of salesmen, students, writers, politicians and lawyers turned envelope stuffers, telephone operators and chauffeurs. and they left convinced they had done the right thing
babbitt compared traveling the debate circuit with his democratic rivals to going to summer camp ``when all of a sudden you're living in the same cabin with a bunch of guys that you never knew before.''
but he said he would be happy to back any one of the democrats who gets the nomination
one of them, sen. paul simon, on thursday, said, ``seeing bruce leave the campaign trail is like seeing an army buddy ship out to go home. he has contributed much to this campaign.''
the biggest merger in new york legal history was announced by one of the nation's oldest law firms, lord, day &amp; lord, which plans to join with a slightly smaller new york city firm
the merger announced thursday with barrett smith simon &amp; armstrong will create a firm of 170 to 180 lawyers that will be among the nation's 75 largest firms
lord, day &amp; lord, suffering from the recent defections of top partners, will change its name for the first time since its founding 140 years ago. it will be known starting march 31 as lord day &amp; lord, barrett smith
the new york times said friday that the deal was prompted in part by pressure from clients to match huge firms that offer larger staffs capable of handling bigger deals, more complex lawsuits and more diverse services
both firms serve a number of prestigious clients in business and the arts but have been hurt recently by the loss of top lawyers who took leading clients with them, the times said. a.m. est</note>
seeking to break an impasse in peace talks, cardinal miguel obando y bravo urged contra rebels to accept a 30-day truce in exchange for four major concessions from nicaragua's sandinista government
the contras said they accepted ``in principle'' the proposal forwarded thursday night. the leftist sandinistas called it ``interesting and constructive,'' but said it needed clarification
obando y bravo, leader of nicaragua's roman catholics, is mediating the talks, whihc were to resume today
the concessions requested of the sandinistas are:
_a ``full, general'' amnesty for the several thousand political prisoners in nicaraguan jails, including all members of the national guard of former dictator gen. anastasio somoza, whom the sandinistas overthrew in 1979
_full freedom of the press, which now is granted only to a few communications outlets, including the opposition newspaper la prensa and radio catolica, the voice of the catholic church
_a promise to ``reconsider'' a mandatory military draft law, which has sparked violent disturbances in several nicaraguan cities by young men and the mothers of draft-age youths. the most recent disturbance was in masaya only a week ago
_renewal of a dialogue with the sandinistas' internal political opposition, which is calling along with the contras for 17 changes in nicaragua's constitution. the talks broke off last year
victor hugo tinoco, nicaragua's deputy foreign minister, said the cease-fire proposed by the cardinal was ``vague and ill-defined'' and would have to be clarified before the government could respond to the plan
the four requirements for the nicaraguan government are very clear and very well defined,'' tinoco said. ``the requirement for the contras is not quite clear.''
tinoco said the cardinal did not define ``when the cease-fire is going to happen, how long it is going to be, where it is going to be'' or how it would be verified. ``we have to clarify what the contras are going to give in exchange,'' he said
obando y bravo said he offered the plan after the two sides were unable to agree on the philosophy underlying a cease-fire
the contras had argued that any truce must be preceded by democratic reforms, while the sandinistas contended hostilities must end before real change can begin
we argued a long time,'' the cardinal said. ``we could not come to agreement on the definitions.''
the concessions requested by obando y bravo of the government were among many the contras have been demanding for some time
the rebels have also been seeking tri-partite talks among the sandinistas, their internal opposition and the contras. the cardinal did not forward that demand
nor did the requested concessions specifically address other contra concerns, including constitutional changes that would prevent a nicaraguan president from succeeding himself, separate the army from the sandinista political party and establish a tribunal to guarantee constitutional rights
obando y bravo said the inability of both sides to ``define a cease-fire'' led to ``an impasse'' after just two hours of talks thursday, the opening day of their second round of face-to-face peace negotiations
the first direct talks took place in san jose, costa rica, in late january, only a week before the u.s. house of representatives rejected president reagan's request for $36.2 million in additional contra aid
the two sides presented their basic bargaining positions in the san jose talks, which all participants characterized as cordial but lacking in progress
the sandinistas and the contras came to guatemala city clearly stating that they were still far apart on the question of which should come first, a cease-fire or democratic reforms in nicaragua
rock diva madonna has a date on broadway in her new play, ``speed-the-plow,'' even though the curtain has yet to go up on the production at a small lincoln center theater
speed-the-plow'' begins preview performances march 29 at lincoln center's 299-seat mitzi newhouse theater and will run through april 24. an official opening date has not been announced
it will reopen april 26 at the 1,058-seat royale theater on broadway
ticket requests have been so overwhelming that the computerized ticket agency telecharge has installed a special number for the broadway version, said show spokesman merle debuskey
the david mamet play, also starring joe mantegna and ron silver, is about two hollywood producers and their office ``temp.''
lauren bacall says humphrey bogart did not give their marriage much chance after they wed when she was 20 years old
but the union produced a son and daughter and did not end until bogart's death 12 years after the marriage. that's longevity by hollywood standards. and miss bacall credits it to bogart's determination not to allow work to separate them
i never went on location to shoot a film,'' she said in an interview in the current issue of us magazine
the agreement before we got married was that i would not take off and leave him behind. when he went on location i went with him,'' the sultry-voiced actress said
bogart, who was a quarter-century older than miss bacall when they were married in 1945, once said he had ``figured i would leave him in five years, because i didn't know anything about life and the world at that point,'' said miss bacall
director john boorman says his movie ``hope and glory,'' which received five academy award nominations, almost was not finished because of financial problems
hope and glory'' won best picture and best director from the los angeles film critics and 13 nominations feb. 9 from the british academy of film and television arts. its oscar nominations announced wednesday included best picture, direction and script
boorman, 55, recalled the day in june 1986 when he found himself $3 million short of the $9 million needed to finance the movie
i was going down to the set on a friday morning at 7 o'clock to give the men all their notices to stop the picture,'' he said in a telephone interview from his paris apartment
but both the money and a studio, columbia, were eventually found. the critics and word of mouth did the rest
