the afl-cio has accused united press international of attempting to ``bust'' the union representing the news service's writers, editors and photographers
the labor federation, in a statement issued by its executive council on thursday, condemned upi's ``callous treatment of its employees'' in declaring an impasse last october in negotiations on a new contract and unilaterally imposing ``harsh new work rules.''
members of the newspaper guild ... are fighting to save their union and their jobs from efforts by upi's owner to bust the union and shut down many of the news service's operations,'' the 36-member council of union presidents said
afl-cio secretary-treasurer thomas r. donahue called the dispute between the guild's wire service local 222 and upi ``the latest struggle in a decade of employee sacrifice to keep the financially troubled news service afloat.''
the labor federation said upi employees have agreed to major concessions including pay, pension and benefit cuts since 1978, and stayed on the job despite bounced paychecks when the company sought bankruptcy protection in 1985
newspaper guild president charles dale said the company's last contract proposal would ``eliminate job security and allow upi to subcontract all bargaining unit work to itself for the sole purpose of cutting wages again and the destruction of the union.''
dale said upi has fired 112 employees and put no money into its employee pension plan since nov. 12
chris smith, a upi spokesman at its headquarters in washington, said the company's last offer and imposed work rules include a 16 percent pay raise over the next two years for top-scale editorial workers
smith said 181 employees have left the company's payroll since oct. 1 but that 70 of them have been replaced
upi has ``never made an expression to use its subcontracting power to replace existing full-time news staff,'' smith said. ``it hasn't happened and we don't anticipate it happening.'' 4th graf pvs bgng, ``there's absolutely ...</note>
