the dollar closed at 130.53 yen, up 0.53 yen from thursday's close of 130.00 yen. it had opened at 130.33 yen and traded in a narrow range of 130.30-130.55 yen
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, a 245.41-point winner thursday, added another 98.05 points to close the week's trading at 24,773.41
there's absolutely nothing to move the market, no market-motivating news, and the dollar is dead,'' said a trader with a major commercial bank
the dealer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said currency trading was also dampened by a holiday in hong kong and the slow start-up of trading in singapore after a holiday
japanese housing and retail shares posted gains along with high-technology issues and those of importers
these sectors are moving the market as the country seems determined to address the trade imbalance problem and expand domestic demand,'' said yoshio ogawa of nikko securities
tobacco is still a titan in many of the 14 southern and border states that will hold presidential primaries march 8. but some say it's no longer political suicide in the tobacco belt to talk about health risks of smoking or to voice opposition to government subsidies of the industry
testing that theory in recent weeks, two southerners hoping for strong presidential showings in the region _ republican pat robertson and democrat albert gore jr. _ have raised eyebrows with statements about tobacco that might have doomed them in past campaigns
in an article in conservative digest, robertson proposed a 10-year phaseout of the domestic tobacco industry, which employs 710,000 people and generates $14.1 billion per year in wages and benefits
robertson called for federal assistance to cushion the blow for farmers and cigarette manufacturers
gore's statements were less provocative. during a mid-january debate in iowa, he said he opposed federal subsidies of tobacco and supported federal anti-smoking programs targeted at young people
rep. charles rose, a north carolina democrat who is chairman of the house subcommittee on tobacco and peanuts, says the industry still wields enormous clout
it's a very silent but powerful force in southern politics,'' rose said
but jim van hecke, north carolina democratic chairman, said growers were more outspoken in past decades because there was less scientific evidence of the dangers of smoking. also, the growth of southern cities and the arrival of workers and industries from other areas have made the region's economy more diverse
it has become routine for presidential candidates venturing into north carolina, south carolina, virginia, kentucky, tennessee and georgia to face questions about their stands on the federal tobacco program and the government's war on smoking. few had openly defied the tobacco industry until this year
robertson's industry-phaseout plan was widely condemned in tobacco circles
ludicrous and asinine,'' said joe king, a grower and president of the 300-member south carolina tobacco association
however, earl black, political science professor at the university of south carolina, said, ``robertson's getting some criticism but he's also getting some praise for having the courage to take on an issue like this.''
in robertson's home state of virginia, the impact has been hard to gauge, said steve haner, executive director of the state's republican legislative caucus
you go down to southside virginia where they grow the stuff and it's fatal to talk like that,'' haner said. but he also said robertson had ``a committed cadre of followers'' who would not desert him because of his stand on tobacco
robertson himself sounded unconcerned. ``i'm not about to lose any votes on this,'' the former television evangelist said in columbia, s.c. ``i'm on the side of the angels on this one.''
gore, a u.s. senator from tennessee, said he opposed subsidies ``in spite of the fact that there are 100,000 tobacco farmers in my home state.'' the federal tobacco program is financed through fees paid by the growers, not direct government payments
many of this year's presidential hopefuls have tried to please the tobacco industry as well as increasingly assertive non-smokers by separating the health and economic issues
you can be against smoking cigarettes without being against family farmers who grow tobacco,'' jesse jackson said recently
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis told an audience in wilson, n.c., that he had ``no problem'' with the existing tobacco program, but he urged farmers to grow other crops as well
rep. richard gephardt of missouri is an enthusiastic supporter of the tobacco program. ``it encourages an orderly market for tobacco. we're going to have tobacco and tobacco products in america and it's just a matter of where it's grown.''
on the republican side, rep. jack kemp said he would continue support programs for tobacco and other commodities where necessary but preferred the free-market system
prime minister margaret thatcher said britain must retain nuclear weapons because without them soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev could threaten western europe
soviet superiority in conventional and chemical weapons would guarantee gorbachev ``would get what he wanted,'' mrs. thatcher said on commercial television's ``news at ten'' thursday night
three hours earlier on another commercial television newscast, soviet foreign ministry spokesman gennadi gerasimov said he did not accept mrs. thatcher's view that british nuclear weapons were vital to western security
i don't accept this because we want to see the world nuclear-free and we cannot see it nuclear-free if britain is going to keep her nuclear forces,'' he said
gerasimov said although the united states and the soviet union want to get rid of nuclear weapons, the british did not
we are believers, you are non-believers. you do not believe in a nuclear-free world. so our task is to convert you to our faith,'' he said
asked about this later, mrs. thatcher responded: ``i want a war-free europe. a nuclear-free europe i do not believe would be a war-free europe.''
she added, ``the nuclear weapon has kept the peace in western europe for 40 years
of course mr. gorbachev wants to get rid of nuclear weapons out of western europe because he knows that if he does, the enormous superiority he has got in men, in tanks, in aircraft, in all conventional weapons, and the colossal superiority in chemical weapons, would mean that if he got the nuclear weapon out of europe, we would never be able to deter an aggressor.''
mrs thatcher said: ``he could almost threaten, and he would get what he wanted. it's my job, as head of government, to see that no one who wants to threaten western europe has any chance of succeeding
the only way to do that is to see that we have a sure defense.''
she concluded: ``you are not sure because of your own virtue. you are sure because the men, the materials, the weapons, including the nuclear, are there
and if you make a mistake now it may not affect our generation, but it may affect future generations because one mistake will take 10 or 12 years to recover.'' throughout with teen-ager turning up at school with head shaved, telling friends he was having trouble with parents, family van found and car stolen. no pickup.</note>
a couple and two of their children were slain in their nightclothes with a hatchet thursday, and the couple's 16-year-old son was being sought for questioning, authorities said
the bodies of bernard brom, his wife, paullette, and children diane, 14, and rick, 9 were found thursday night at their home in suburban cascade township, said olmsted county sheriff charles von wald
a bloody ax 2 to 3 feet long was found in the basement, von wald said
the sheriff said a nationwide bulletin was issued for the broms' 16-year-old son and the family van. the boy was at lourdes high school on thursday morning but did not attend classes, the sheriff said
friends at the school said the boy had dyed his hair black, shaved the sides of his head and spiked the hair in back, von wald said. the youth also bought a wig and makeup
he indicated he was having some trouble with his parents,'' von wald said. ``one student said he was having trouble with his dad because of a tape he had bought and he didn't want him listening to it
bernard and rick brom's bodies were found in their upstairs bedrooms, and paullette and diane brom's bodies were in an upstairs hallway, the sheriff said. he said they were slain early in the morning
the house is among four on a road in a quiet, well-to-do area of cascade township
von wald said the sheriff's department received a call at about 5:30 p.m. from an unidentified school official about a possible problem at the house
the family van had been missing but was found late thursday, von wald said. a car and another car's license plates were reported stolen from the vicinity of the high school
president reagan's 1989 budget would boost america's space and science spending by 20 percent and proposes new funds to put astronauts on mars, probe particles smaller than the atom and listen for voices from distant galaxies
the $13.1 billion general science request is an increase of $2.2 billion over this year and includes start-up funds for the superconducting super collider in the department of energy and the space station in the national aeronautics and space administration
nasa also would get start-up money for a new machine to search for radio signals from unknown sources in outer space _ an effort to answer the ageless question of whether there is intelligent life elsewhere in the universe
the spending plan, part of reagan's $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget proposal delivered to congress on thursday, calls for new money for a national science foundation program to develop scientists and engineers for america's future and to continue fundamental research at colleges and universities
our faith in science and technology has served us very well in the past,'' said william r. graham, the presidential science adviser. ``we see this as the dawn (of this concept) and not the end of it.''
the budget calls for $400 million to start construction of the super collider. the experimental device would be the world's most powerful proton collider, capable of conducting research into fundamental subatomic particles
several states are competing for the $4 billion super collider, but a final location has not been determined
the department of energy's science budget authority for 1989 would total $1.2 billion, a 49 percent increase over the 1988 level. most of the increase would go to the collider
james fletcher, the nasa administrator, told reporters that reagan's budget follows a policy that ``clearly commits the united states to space leadership as a fundamental objective.''
for the first time, he said, it also funds a national goal of putting astronauts on other planets. about $100 million is planned for the pathfinder project, an effort to develop the technologies needed to send astronauts to mars in the next century
the budget asks nearly $1 billion to start construction of the space station, a permanent orbital base that nasa plans to have in operation in the mid-1990s. nasa officials had hoped for a presidential commitment of about $1.8 billion, but even the reduced amount may run into resistance in congress
i am not prepared to sacrifice important science projects, including environmental earth studies, to build a space hotel,'' said rep. bill green, r-n.y., the ranking republican on the house subcommittee for independent agencies
nasa's total budget outlay would increase by about 20 percent, from $9.11 billion in 1988 to $10.97 billion in 1989
the funding would include the final expenses in recovering from the challenger accident and returning the space shuttle fleet to orbit. seven missions are planned for the shuttle in fiscal year 1989, with the resumption of flights planned for next august
tucked into the budget is a modest $9 million to start building an instrument that would be able to listen to thousands of different radio frequencies at once. fletcher said the instrument, which is planned for operation by 1992, is part of a continuing search for civilizations that may be sending signals from planets far beyond the solar system
there also are funds for nasa's share of a joint project with the air force to develop the spaceplane, a transport capable of carrying cargo and passengers around the earth at hypersonic speeds by cruising in and out of space
the national science foundation, which endured heavy cuts in congress in its 1988 budget, would increase its 1989 outlay from $1.65 billion to $1.80 billion, a boost of about 9 percent
erich bloch, the nsf director, said the president's budget would include a program to establish 10 to 15 basic science research centers over the next five years
bloch said the nsf would put a much heavier emphasis than in the past on programs to boost science and math education on the ``pre-college'' level, an effort to boost the number of students attracted to the science and technical fields
here are some highlights of president reagan's budget message to congress
by reordering priorities so that we spend more on national security and less on wasteful or unnecessary federal programs, we have made freedom more secure around the world and have been able to negotiate with our adversaries from a position of strength
by pursuing market-oriented economic policies, we have uncorked the genie of american enterprise and created new businesses, more jobs, improved production, and widespread prosperity
and we have done all this without neglecting the poor, the elderly, the infirm, and the unfortunate among us
this budget does not fully reflect my priorities, nor, presumably, those of any particular member of congress
but the goal of deficit reduction through spending reduction must be paramount
abandoning the deficit reduction compromise would threaten our economic progress and burden future generations
i propose an increase of $656 million ... for discretionary programs of the department of education. although state and local governments fund most educational activity, federal programs provide crucial aid for the poor, the handicapped, and the educationally disadvantaged
i have proposed reform of our overcentralized welfare system through state experimentation with innovative alternatives...
ineffective programs to assist dislocated workers would be replaced by an expanded $1 billion worker readjustment program (wrap) carefully designed to help those displaced from their jobs move quickly into new careers
i propose a continued increase in federally supported basic research aimed at longer-term improvements in the nation's productivity and global competitiveness...
i would provide $11.5 billion for space programs...
i also recommend $363 million in 1989 to initiate construction of the superconducting super collider (ssc), including $283 million for construction and $60 million for supporting research and development...
i continue to urge enactment of an affordable self-financing insurance program through medicare to protect families from economic devastation caused by catastrophic illness
to attack the scourge of aids, i propose $2 billion for additional research, education, and treatment in 1989 _ a 38 percent increase over the 1988 level...
building upon the nation's pre-eminence in basic biomedical research, i seek a 5.1 percent increase for non-aids research at the national institutes of health
for expanded law enforcement ... i propose $4.5 billion _ an increase of 6 percent over 1988
for drug law enforcement, prevention, and treatment programs, i propose $3.9 billion in 1989, a 13 percent increase over the 1988 level
to relieve prison overcrowding and adequately house a growing inmate population, i would provide $437 million _ more than double the $202 million devoted to federal prison construction in 1988
for the federal aviation administration to continue its multiyear program to modernize the nation's air traffic control systems, i would provide $1.6 billion _ a 44 percent increase over the level of 1988
to carry out the joint recommendations of the u.s. and canadian special envoys on acid rain, i recommend total funding of $2.5 billion for innovative clean coal technology demonstration projects over the period 1988 through 1992
i also recommend an expansion of hazardous waste cleanup efforts, with an increase in superfund outlays of some $430 million in 1989
to continue filling the strategic petroleum reserve (spr) at the current rate of 50,000 barrels per day, i would provide $334 million in 1989. contingent upon the enactment of legislation authorizing the sale of the naval petroleum reserves (npr), i would provide an additional $477 million to bring the fill rate up to 100,000 barrels per day...
to improve the speed and accuracy of tax processing and expand information services provided to taxpayers, i would provide a $241 million increase for the internal revenue service...
the proposals for national security contained in this budget represent an essential minimum program for keeping america safe and honoring our commitments to our friends and allies...
...my budget requests defense funding of $299.5 billion in budget authority and $294 billion in outlays for 1989. it also provides for about 2 percent real growth in these programs in future years...
...i plan to continue pushing for the elimination of artificially high (farm) price supports, thereby reducing the need for export subsidies
the budget proposes certain reforms in the medicare program ... to limit payments for certain overpriced physician procedures, limit payments for durable medical equipment and supplies, and eliminate a loophole in the payment process for kidney dialysis. in total, these reforms would reduce spending for medicare by $1.2 billion from the level that would occur if current law were continued
the government often continues programs at the federal level that are no longer needed. this is the case with rural housing programs, the economic development administration, urban mass transit discretionary grants, urban development action grants, sewage treatment, small business administration direct loans, housing development action grants, the housing rehabilitation loan program, and economic development programs of the tennessee valley authority...
...my budget proposes termination of the interstate commerce commission, contingent upon enactment of legislation that completes deregulation of the motor carrier industry
...i am proposing the sale not only of the naval petroleum reserves, but also of the alaska power administration, the federal government's helium program, excess real property and a further $12 billion in loan portfolios. in addition, i have proposed legislation to authorize a study of possible divestiture of the southeastern power administration, and plan to study possible privatization of our uranium enrichment facilities, as well as ways of making the u.s. postal service more efficient through greater reliance on the private sector
i am proposing the development of a private mediating institution to reduce the backlog of cases before the u.s. tax court.... i also encourage the complete privatization of wastewater treatment plants, certain mass transit projects, the department of agriculture's national finance center and the rural telephone bank
...our administration plans to initiate privatization and commercialization efforts involving federal prison industries, relying on a private space facility for micro-gravity research opportunities in the early 1990s, commercial cargo inspection, military commissaries, coast guard buoy maintenance and the management of undeveloped federal land. moreover, my budget proposes that the work associated with certain federal employment positions be reviewed for the feasibility of contracting their responsibilities...
...i propose in this budget a new approach to paying federal employees who increase their productivity. i ask the congress to modify the current system of virtually automatic ``within-grade'' pay increases for the roughly 40 percent of employees eligible each year to one that is based on employee performance
...a constitutional amendment to balance the federal budget _ and a provision requiring a super-majority vote in the congress to increase taxes _ would impose some much-needed discipline on the congressional budget process
i will shortly transmit legislation that will require any future legislation creating new federal programs to be deficit-neutral...requiring the concurrent enactment of equal amounts of program reductions or revenue increases...
it had all the trappings of a campaign rally. the only thing missing was a presidential candidate
on thursday night _ hours after delaware's former governor announced he was dropping out of the race for the republican presidential nomination _ du pont was greeting supporters at a high school, thanking them for their help in fueling his longshot campaign
the du pont partisans, who had made nearly 400,000 telephone calls for their candidate, who had sent out more than a million pieces of mail, crowded around, cheering, sporting ``pete 1992'' buttons
in america nobody promises you you're gonna win,'' du pont said as he announced his withdrawal. ``america only promises you're gonna get your chance to try. she gave us our chance. we took it. we used it. we did well with it. and of that i am enormously proud.''
at the rally, du pont, never letting go of wife elise's hand, tried to greet everyone, to shake every hand on his way to the stage
ironically, the campaign folded in part because of money. it's ironic because the du pont name is synonymous with big bucks
he is the great-grandson of the founder of the du pont co.; his wife is a descendant of benjamin franklin and an heiress to a dairy fortune
du pont and top aides decided there was not enough time to raise the millions needed for a respectable campaign leading up to super tuesday on march 8. the campaign ended, however, with no debt and $350,000 on hand
the couple's daughter elise was there for thursday night's farewell, as were sons pierre and benjamin franklin. eleuthere, known as ``there,'' was ``back at college doing what he ought to be doing _ getting his college degree,'' du pont said
du pont, who was heading to iowa and then new hampshire next week to thank supporters, first wanted to thank those who have supported him through a stint in the state legislature, three terms as delaware's lone congressman, and the maximum two terms as governor
the 53-year-old du pont announced his candidacy sept. 16, 1986 _ 17 months before the new hampshire primary. he was the first republican in the field. he said then if he did not do well in iowa and new hampshire, he would pull out of the race
he was fifth in a field of six gop candidates in the iowa caucuses. he was fourth out of five in the new hampshire primary
the two contests marked the first electoral losses in his political career
the harvard law school graduate is convinced, however, that his campaign made a difference
in those 17 months we contributed something here. we changed the agenda. we put forward a set of proposals that made a difference,'' he said
du pont garnered attention, if not widespread support, with his provocative approach to certain issues such as mandatory drug testing in high schools, a workfare program to replace welfare, and a private alternative to social security
he talked about what might have been
according to du pont, tracking polls showed he was solidly ahead of jack kemp the friday before tuesday's primary
if that election had been held on friday we'd be in south carolina tonight,'' he said to the cheering crowd
du pont talked about the future, particularly the republican national convention this summer in new orleans
we didn't get quite as many votes as we needed, but we did what was right for the country. and now our job is to keep talking for those things that are right for the country and make sure that those other candidates adopt our ideas. make sure they get into the republican platform,'' he said
du pont affectionately scolded his supporters, telling them not to be unhappy about the end of his candidacy
some of you are sad and you're not allowed to be sad because this is not a sad occasion. this is a celebration of a campaign for the presidency of the united states,'' he said. ``it was run the way campaigns ought to be run. on principles, on issues.''
you're not allowed to be sad but you're allowed to say we fought the good fight. we nearly won it,'' he said
you were part of a little moment in history,'' he told them, ``that will live in my heart for a long while.'' strategy</head>
vice president george bush won a presidential straw poll of nevada republicans, but his tally was nearly equaled by undecided votes _ many of which were believed to have been cast by supporters of pat robertson in a bid to control later balloting
with only a tiny fraction of returns still unreported from caucuses around the state thursday night, bush had 1,341 votes in the non-binding straw poll, and undecided votes totaled 1,146
steve wark, robertson coordinator in nevada, said many robertson voters cast undecided ballots as part of a strategy to win in later voting for delegates to the upcoming county conventions
they did that to protect their (convention) delegates,'' said state gop chairwoman sally vitkus-mckinney. ``that's politics.''
we knew that the dole and bush people would get together to try and squash us if we came out strong in the straw poll,'' wark said. even so, robertson, a former television evangelist, had 733 votes outright
kansas sen. bob dole had 1,130 votes, officially finishing ahead of robertson but lagging behind the undecided tally. rep. jack kemp had 644 votes
former delaware gov. pete du pont, who dropped out of the gop race on thursday, got 39 votes and former secretary of state alexander haig, who called it quits last week, got six votes
the caucuses were open only to registered nevada republicans, and the straw poll was conducted by secret ballot
the caucuses drew several thousand of the more than 120,000 republicans registered to vote in nevada. the registration total has gone up several thousand since jan. 1, but exact numbers weren't available
ms. vitkus-mckinney said the increase was due both to state gop registration efforts and to separate efforts by the robertson camp
whether the robertson strategy in the straw poll worked remains to be seen. the makeup of the delegations to the county conventions won't be known for several more days and even then delegates won't have to publicly declare their presidential preferences
the straw poll was developed last summer, before former nevada sen. paul laxalt announced in september that he wouldn't seek the gop presidential nomination. he would have been the probable nevada poll winner had he stayed in the running, ms. vitkus-mckinney said
a television station that pre-empted two minutes of ``jeopardy'' to report on a plane crash later broadcast the missing game-show footage during its news programs after viewers complained, station officials said
viewers missed less than two minutes of `jeopardy.' but those were the final minutes, and so we replayed them,'' said wxfl-tv general manager jim saunders
two people were killed tuesday when a twin-engine plane slammed into a house in dunedin
on wednesday, wxfl broadcast the end of ``jeopardy'' twice, once during the station's noon and 6 p.m. news shows
saunders said he did not know how many complaint calls were received tuesday, but a source at the station told the tampa tribune the number was ``well over 300.''
most americans don't know the recommended blood cholesterol levels, but do have a general knowledge of what cholesterol is, according to a louis harris poll sponsored by the maker of a cholesterol-lowering drug
seventy-nine percent of those asked didn't know the recommended cholesterol levels, according to the survey sponsored by bristol laboratories, makers of the cholesterol-lowering drug questran
however, most had general knowledge of cholesterol, the survey showed. eighty-three percent identified it as a fatty substance, and 96 percent said they knew that eating fatty foods can elevate cholesterol levels
cholesterol has been linked to heart disease
the survey was based on telephone interviews with 1,438 americans over age 18 conducted between dec. 22, 1987 and jan. 14, 1988
stock prices rallied for the seventh consecutive day in active trading in tokyo today, while the u.s. dollar climbed slightly
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected shares, a 245.41-point winner thursday, added another 98.05 points or 0.4 percent and closed the week's trading at 24,773.41
share prices rose almost across the board. we expect the stock average to top the 25,000-level pretty soon,'' said hiromi yoneyama of wako securities
he said institutional investors were especially active in areas such as steel and shipbuilding. volume of the first-section trade reached the 1 billion-share mark for the first time in six weeks, up from 750 million shares thursday
electrical issues scored strong gains, while automobiles and steel also rose
on the tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed the week's trading at 130.53 yen, up 0.53 yen from thursday's close of 130.00. it had opened at 130.33 yen and traded in a narrow range of 130.30-130.55 yen
ken iio of the bank of tokyo said trading was quiet ahead of the weekend with no major news affecting dealing today
the influential hong kong and singapore markets, which were closed part of this week due to the chinese new year's holiday, also made the dealing sluggish, he said. the volume of trade was a moderate $2.296 billion
stroke victims confined to wheelchairs for many years after their attacks can be taught to walk or climb stairs again, according to a new study by researchers who say therapists shouldn't give up
some patients who took part in a rehabilitation program were able to make improvements 40 years after their strokes, a doctor said
this is a group that generally doesn't get rehabilitated,'' said dr. paul bach-y-rita. ``they are almost totally forgotten. and we show they can make significant recovery with the right program.''
bach-y-rita, a physician at the university of wisconsin in madison, presented his findings on about 200 patients thursday at an american heart association meeting on strokes
in a separate report, dr. james n. davis of duke university said drugs may help speed up recovery in the days immediately after a stroke
strokes occur when the flow of the blood to the brain is disrupted. often an artery is clogged by a blood clot, starving some of the brain of oxygen carried by blood. other strokes occur when a blood vessel bursts, flooding the brain with blood
about 500,000 americans suffered strokes in 1985, the last year for which statistics are available, and 152,700 of them died
more than a third of all stroke victims die within a month of their attacks. about a third of the survivors need help caring for themselves, often because one side of their bodies is partially paralyzed
the latest research is part of a growing interest among specialists in helping the brain shift important functions, such as control of movement, from the damaged part of the brain to undamaged regions
these experts have found that over time, even injured brain cells can sprout new branches and connections that help repair damage
the program developed by bach-y-rita and a colleague, dr. richard balliet, sets small goals for longtime stroke victims, such as learning to move a finger or twist a wrist through exercise
as a patient recovers even small amounts initially and knows that recovery is possible, that patient will work very hard, even without a therapist there, to get to the next grade of recovery,'' he said. ``over a period of time, it adds up to significant functional improvement.''
patients visit the rehabilitation clinic for a week at a time every two or three months, he said. the rest of the time they work at home, usually with relatives' help
bach-y-rita said some patients who were confined to wheelchairs for many years learned to walk and climb stairs again. others have become able to employ a useless hand or arm for such chores as eating and supporting themselves
you dangle in front of us who deal with people with stroke the exciting possiblity that something can be done to treat these people to restore their independence,'' said dr. fletcher h. mcdowell of cornell medical college. ``if you are right at all, we all ought to be doing it.''
bach-y-rita said, ``pick out a few of your patients who are five or 10 years post-stroke and convince yourself how you can obtain function. if you pick realistic goals in a few patients, i think you are going to get so excited, you won't stop.''
he cautioned, however, that patients must have good mental function and a will to work and improve
davis said he has preliminary evidence that amphetamines, given soon after a stroke, appear to speed some people's recovery significantly
i'm not trying to argue that it will work in all patients,'' he said. ``but there are some patients in whom you can facilitate rehabilitation with drugs.'' late-morning event in oklahoma city</note>
vice president george bush is proposing a program of spending restraint that would balance the budget by 1993, while claiming that sen. bob dole's plan ``sounds easy, but it isn't decisive.''
on the same day that president reagan sent a $1.1 trillion budget to congress, bush also claimed that dole's fiscal policy would ``cut into social security and colas and reduce the checks for our senior citizens.''
bush elaborated on his budget proposal while predicting he would score the most impressive victories in the super tuesday series of republican party primaries and caucuses in the south and border states
he also said he will honor his commitment to take part in tonight's gop candidate debate here, despite dole's withdrawal, because ``we're committed.''
during a heavy day of campaigning here and in missouri, bush also said he didn't want to get into ``name-calling'' battles with dole, his closest competitor for the party's presidential nomination
bush, in fact, did not name dole when he told an audience in joplin, mo. that ``one candidate'' is supporting a budget freeze proposal that would provide only a 2 percent window of flexibility on additional spending
it sounds easy, but it isn't decisive,'' bush said. ``it's ducking decisions about where you cut and where you add.'' he said dole's ``across-the-board'' freeze would ``freeze in some outrageous waste'' in spending programs
the vice president said he is best suited to carry on reagan's economic and foreign policy legacy, and asked voters help him follow up the new hampshire victory with a strong showing on march 8
while bush continued his grass-roots style of campaigning, making an unscheduled stop at a truck stop in rural missouri, his chief spokesman, pete teeley, said the vice president's campaign aides feel bush is well positioned to make a strong showing in the next series of primaries
bush sought to capitalize on reagan's relative popularity in the south and border states, saying ``the president and i'' have brought economic prosperity to the country. bush did say, however, that some areas of the country missed out on the benefits of the recovery from the 1981-82 recession, and said he planned to do something about that if elected
on his bitter battle with dole, bush said he did not want to get into any direct confrontations with the kansas republican
i don't respond to bob dole. i'm trying to stay on the issues.''
asked in a local television interview whether he would continue to run negative commercials against dole, bush replied, ``he (dole) called them comparative ads when they were all about me.''
asked if he would support dole if the kansan won the nomination, bush said,``i'd vote for him over any democrat and i expect he'd vote for me over any democrat.''
bush said ``the next focused event, with the entire nation's focus, will be south carolina'' which holds its presidential primary on tuesday. and teeley said that bush will not try to compete in minnesota, which also holds its presidential contest next week
addressing a large crowd in the atrium of the loews anatole hotel here, bush said ``there is no way you can become president of the united states by not doing well, if not winning, on super tuesday. i intend to win.''
bush would seek to bring about a balanced budget by fiscal 1993 by limiting the growth in expenditures to a growth in u.s. treasury receipts ranging from 5 percent to 8 percent, and a 4 percent annual rate of inflation
the question is, who is best qualified to get this deficit down,'' he said
democrat albert gore jr., hoping to set himself apart from his rivals, accused richard gephart of flip-flopping on issues and michael dukakis of foreign policy inexperience in a combative debate gore said signals the ``beginning of the main event'' in their presidential race
gephardt and dukakis, who are battling the tennessee senator in the delegate-rich primaries across the south less than three weeks away, came under attack almost immediately thursday night and countered in a series of testy exchanges
it's quite natural he would launch an attack,'' gephardt, the missouri congressman, said afterward. ``he probably thinks i'm ahead in the south and he's got to jump start his campaign to have a chance.''
with jesse jackson and gary hart included, the five candidates debated for two hours in a televised session with a heavy focus on the south _ the major battleground of both parties' nomination fights before the march 8 super tuesday primaries. one candidate, paul simon, bypassed the event to concentrate on minnesota and south dakota, which have earlier contests
a similar debate was scheduled tonight for the four remaining republican candidates
but it was placed in jeopardy when bob dole withdrew thursday saying he feared it would become a pep rally for vice president george bush, and pat robertson followed suit. that left only jack kemp to debate bush, and sponsors said they hoped it would still go on _ with empty chairs on the stage for the absent contenders
the democratic debate contained what were some of the most pointed exchanges among the candidates, most of whom have met each other in more than 20 debates over the past year
gore came out swinging immediately, using the first question to charge that dukakis, the massachusetts governor, was without foreign policy experience and had said in a recent televised interview that he was willing to tolerate a ``soviet client state'' in nicaragua
i'm not going to sit here and listen to that,'' dukakis shot back, denying he said or believed such a statement. ``if you're going to be president of the united states you better be accurate.''
gore turned to gephardt moments later, saying his calls for tough trade policies would invite a trade war and cost american jobs. but it was his accusations that the missouri congressman had shifted positions on a range of issues from reaganomics to abortion that drew a sharp rebuttal
when you make a lecture on consistency, maybe you better take a look at your own record first,'' gephardt said
in a reference to the recently withdrawn gop candidate, he added, ``lately you've been sounding more like al haig than al gore.'' gore responded: ``that line sounds more like richard nixon than richard gephardt.''
gore clearly came into the debate eager to use it as an opportunity to battle the two contenders he views as his chief opponents, while leaving hart and jackson relatively untouched
gore defended his strategy in talking with reporters later, saying consistency ``is a legitimate issue'' and the race had now moved into his territory
dukakis and gephardt are the two winners so far in the 1988 democratic nomination race, dukakis winning in new hampshire earlier this week and gephardt winning iowa's caucuses the week before
turning to gephardt, gore served warning, saying, ``i'm going to lay it on the line now dick,'' and then accused him of voting in congress against increases in the minimum wage, against a department of education and for tuition tax credits. in each case, he said, gephardt has taken different positions now
you voted for reaganomics; now you say, well, where are you this week on reaganomics?'' gore said
gephardt has acknowledged changing positions on some key issues, saying time and circumstances have changed. meeting with reporters after the debate, he said: ``all of us in public life should try to re-examine issues. that's what i've tried to do.''
dukakis and gephardt tangled amongst themselves some too. dukakis said the democratic rivals were surprised gephardt had said in new hampshire he was proud to have voted for president reagan's tax-cut bill ``when he'd said all over iowa he was against it and only voted for it as a last resort.''
the sharp exchanges left hart and jackson out of the spotlight much of the time. hart at one point said he was not withdrawing from the presidential race despite critics who said he should
hart said that with bruce babbitt's withdrawal from the race, hart was the only candidate left who had laid out his plans for a federal budget. ``men, when are you going to produce your budgets?'' he asked
jackson, who has a strong following among black voters in the south and leads in polls of some southern states, drew one of the loudest rounds of applause when he said the united states is making products that consumers don't want
at another point, stressing the need for government to help poor children and welfare mothers, jackson said he was ``a graduate'' of the nation's underclass
americans will spend nearly $13 billion this year treating and caring for victims of strokes, the nation's third-leading cause of death, according to new statistics
stroke remains an extremely expensive disease, even though the stroke death rate has fallen sharply in recent years
stroke victims are often left paralyzed or disabled. the american heart association, which released the latest figures thursday, noted that about a third of all stroke survivors need help caring for themselves
strokes are exceeded only by heart disease and cancer as a cause of death in the united states
in 1985, the last year for which statistics are available, about 500,000 americas suffered strokes, and 152,700 of them died
however, notes dr. philip a. wolf of boston university medical school, ``the death rate is falling very dramatically.''
for the past four decades, the death rate from stroke has been dropping by about 1 percent a year. but since 1973, that decline has averaged 5.7 percent a year
no one knows precisely why stroke deaths are becoming less common. however, the risk of heart attacks is also going down, and many experts believe the same factors are involved in curbing both diseases
a lot of people think the control of blood pressure, changes in lifestyles, changes in diet, more exercise and more health consciousness are affecting vascular (blood vessel) disease in general,'' said dr. louis r. caplan of tufts medical school in boston, who is chairman of the heart association's stroke council
wolf, who also is an epidemiologist at the long-running framingham heart study, said that control of blood pressure appears to be the single most important of these factors
he said that when even mildly elevated blood pressure is brought down through drugs and behavior changes, the risk of stroke is cut in half
this year, the heart association estimates that $9.2 billion will be spent on hospital and nursing home care alone for stroke victims, who often are left partially paralyzed. when doctor and nurse bills, medicine and lost productivity are added, the total annual cost of strokes in 1988 will be an estimated $12.9 billion
a stroke occurs when the blood supply in the brain is disrupted. often a blood clot chokes off an artery, starving brain cells of oxygen. strokes also occur when blood vessels burst and flood brain tissue with blood
traditionally, doctors have been able to do little for patients except send them to hospitals, where they are taught to live with their disabilities. however, caplan said, that is beginning to change
a lot of us are hoping that new technology, used in patients who are diagnosed correctly, may do a lot to help patients get better,'' he said in an interview
caplan said new diagnostic machines are becoming available that can help doctors pinpoint precisely where inside the head the blood vessels are in danger of clogging or breaking. then strokes may be prevented with surgery or treatment
doctors also are experimenting with drugs that may minimize the damage of strokes once they occur
most people have treated stroke casually,'' said caplan. ``they say there's nothing you can do but rehabilitate the patient. the excitement is that we are starting to have the technology and ability to do something.''
amtrack said delays were likely on its passenger trains running from new york to richmond, va., and other points south until crews could clear tracks of derailed cars from a 78-car freight train
twelve cars from the train jumped the tracks thursday evening, forcing the evacuation of two office buildings and five homes but causing no injuries, authorities said. amtrak uses the same track
lt. michael reilly of the fairfax county fire department said the richmond, fredericksburg &amp; potomac train, traveling from richmond to alexandria, derailed around 7:10 p.m. some of the cars careened into seven empty freight cars parked on adjacent tracks
ten of the cars contained industrial equipment, while two tank cars were carrying soybean oil, reilly said
two office buildings located about a mile from the crash scene and five nearby homes were evacuated as a safety precaution, reilly said
the 19 people forced from homes and offices were allowed to return around 9 p.m., after officials confirmed the derailed cars contained no hazardous materials
passengers planning to travel on amtrak between richmond and new york were to be bused between richmond and washington, d.c., where they could continue north on amtrak, said marci larson, operations manager for amtrak. in addition, larson said, trains traveling from new york to florida and georgia would be rerouted to southern railway tracks between washington and richmond. 02-19 0382</first>
here, at a glance, is an overview of the proposed budget for fiscal year 1989 that president reagan submitted to congress:
_spending is projected at $1.09 trillion, up from $1.05 trillion in 1988
_receipts are estimated at $964.7 billion, $55.5 billion more than in 1988. income taxes provide 55 percent of receipts, followed by 36.8 percent from social insurance taxes
_the budget would reduce the federal deficit from an estimated $146.7 billion in 1988 to $129.5 billion in the fiscal year that begins next oct. 1. that's below the target of $136 billion called for in the gramm-rudman deficit-reduction law
_military spending would be $294 billion, up from $285.4 billion in 1988, but the smallest military spending increase reagan has ever sent to congress. the 3 percent increase is less than needed to keep pace with inflation, projected at 4.3 percent this year
_the plan calls for nearly $2 billion in spending authority to combat acquired immune deficiency syndrome, a 38 percent increase over 1988 levels
_education spending would rise 8 percent, or $1.5 billion. the biggest gain would be in the pell grant program for needy college students
_about $10.9 billion is included for space programs, with almost $1 billion of that going to the start of construction of a manned space station and another $1 billion for the space shuttle
_about $363 million for the start of construction of the superconducting super collider, a machine designed to study the nature of matter
_about $1.6 billion is earmarked for upgrading the nation's air traffic control system
_included is a request for $437 million, more than double last year's budget, for federal prison construction to relieve overcrowding
_the plan renews a number of previous administration proposals for reducing government programs, including abolition of the interstate commerce commission, the economic development administration, small business administration direct loans, urban development action grants and public subsidies for amtrak rail passenger service and mass transit systems
_the budget suggsts ``possible privatization'' of some postal service operations and the government's uranium enrichment facilities
_dropped were some of the more politically controversial proposals of past reagan budgets, including abolition of the legal services corp
the american cancer society has broken ground for a new headquarters next to emory university and across the street from the headquarters of the federal centers for disease control
i'm hopeful that this headquarters will be successful,'' gov. joe frank harris said at groundbreaking ceremonies thursday
harris said he would like to see the new building ``phased out of existence (someday) ... because a total cure for cancer has been found and announced here.''
the cancer society has had its headquarters in new york city the last 75 years. it hopes to move next january to the $12 million, six-floor building. the society estimated that 125 or more of its 300-person staff will make the move south
we are now moving at top speed into the future, toward advancements that would have seemed like science-fiction fantasies a few years ago,'' said dr. harmon j. eyre, a salt lake city oncologist and president of the cancer society. ``amazing and wonderful things will happen at this place.''
the cancer society, the world's largest volunteer health agency, said it wanted to escape high operating costs in new york
emory sold the four-acre site to the society for $1 million. the college had purchased the tract, worth $2.5 million, with assistance from a foundation, and wanted to add the society's headquarters to a growing cluster of health and science centers near its campus
douglas edwards, walter cronkite's predecessor and the nation's first nightly television news anchor, is retiring april 1 after 46 years with cbs
edwards, who covered world war ii on radio with the legendary edward r. murrow, says he's ``a little sad, but exhilirated'' about retirement
i've had a daily tv news report without a break since april 15, 1948, which is a record, almost 40 years now,'' edwards said thursday. he laughed and added: ``that and a dollar will get you a ride on the subway.''
he's been solid and accurate and straightforward and reliable through the years,'' said mike wallace, who worked with edwards on radio nearly 50 years ago, before the two met again at cbs. ``he has not been flashy, and he has not been sensational, he's been solid.''
in 1948, then-cbs president frank stanton tapped edwards to anchor ``doug edwards and the news.'' after 14 years in the job, he was succeeded by cronkite on the ``cbs evening news.''
edwards, 70, still does the network newsbreaks and a weekly show, ``for our times,'' as well as regular radio broadcasts
doug edwards has been a friend and a mentor since before i joined cbs news,'' said dan rather, only the third tv news anchor in the network's history. ``he's a giant in our craft, and all of us in television and radio news are indebted to him.''
his name has been synonymous with cbs news since the dawn of television,'' said cbs news president howard stringer. ``doug will be sorely missed, his accomplishments long treasured.''
edwards already had 10 years of broadcast experience when he joined cbs radio in 1942 at age 25. he joined murrow's staff in london in the final months of world war ii. afterwards, he became paris bureau chief. a interview on the local new york cbs station about his foreign coverage impressed cbs executives
they seemed to like the way i conducted myself in front of the camera, and they asked me afterwards if i'd like to do some television news,'' edwards said. he started by doing the thursday and saturday news shows
he was tapped for the news show after his participation with murrow and quincy howe in cbs' acclaimed radio coverage of the 1948 presidential conventions
we did very well, the three of us on those conventions,'' edwards recalled. ``afterward, cbs asked me to go into television, and i did it with some fear and trepidation and trembling, not because i was nervous about being on television, i had done quite a bit of it, but radio was the power, and i was pretty young at the time.''
in the beginning, the cbs network consisted of a half-dozen eastern cities. ``almost every other night, i'd welcome a new tv station that got hooked up,'' edwards said. ``until one night, in 1951 or 1952, i said, `good evening, everybody, coast to coast.'''
nbc had ``camel news caravan'' with john cameron swayze in 1949. abc launched a nightly news show in 1951 anchored by john daly, a former cbs correspondent
edwards began his broadcasting career at the tender age of 15 on a radio station in troy, ala
after high school, he landed a job with radio station wxyz in detroit, home of such popular radio serials as ``the lone ranger'' and ``the green hornet.'' he worked with another up-and-coming newsman, mike wallace
we were both cunningham news aces back in 1940-41,'' wallace recalled in a telephone interview from atlanta, where he was working on a segment for cbs' ``60 minutes.'' ``then he left to go to wsb in atlanta, where i am at this moment
cunningham was a drug chain, and they used to sponsor newscasts, and they used to have the sound of a p-38 (fighter plane) or whatever zooming and, `the cunningham news aces are on the air!' _ doug and me.''
edwards said he and his wife, may, plan to move to sarasota, fla., where he will continue lecturing on broadcast journalism and begin work on an autobiography
a federal judge is considering whether to issue an injunction blocking proposed regulations that would prohibit some 4,000 federally funded family planning clinics nationwide from offering abortion counseling services
if i were to grant an injunction, why should i not enjoin (health and human services secretary otis r. bowen) from enforcing these regulations anywhere in this country?'' u.s. district judge walter skinner said at the end of a two-hour hearing thursday
the hhs regulations, which take effect march 3, are being contested in u.s. district courts in colorado, new york and massachusetts
a federal judge in denver this week granted a preliminary injunction in the suit filed there, but the ruling apparently will only temporarily block the regulations from affecting clinics in colorado and utah
skinner, however, told attorneys thursday that he believed a single federal district court could hold ``national jurisdiction'' and issue one broad opinion that could end ``this business of raising the same issue in 92 districts.''
the judge gave no indication when he would release his decision on the injunction sought by the state of massachusetts, the national family planning and reproductive health association and 13 other local and national family planning groups
but attorneys speculated skinner would rule soon since an injunction request was scheduled to be argued late today in new york
unlike the denver judge, who partially based her ruling on the regulations' impact on physicians' relationships to their patients, skinner said, ``medical ethics is not my problem.''
he said the issue was whether the regulations were constitutional
congressional intent in establishing the family planning program under title x of the public health service act in 1970 was at the heart of thursday's arguments
skinner said, ``nothing is clear when it comes to congressional intent.''
thomas millet, a justice department attorney representing the health and human services agency, contended that the law bans the use of federal funds in ``programs where abortion is a method of family planning.''
assistant massachusetts attorney general paul glickman and james feldesman, attorney for the family planning association, argued that congress was fully aware abortion counseling was being provided through title x programs through eight budgetary reauthorizations over the years
administrative agencies can't change (law) by fiat,'' glickman argued, contending hhs did that when it proposed the regulations after reagan administration attempts to change title x through congressional action failed
while federal law already prohibits spending federal funds on abortion, the new rules say federally funded family planning programs may not provide abortion counseling, may not refer women to abortion providers and may not engage in lobbying or legal action to increase availability of abortion
in addition, the new guidelines would require any clinics now providing those abortion services to separate them entirely from their federally supported operations by april
the title x budget for fiscal 1988 is $137 million, down from $142 million in fiscal 1987. an estimated 5 million poor women receive services from the program
representatives of five republican presidential contenders have filed petitions for national convention delegates and alternates who will be chosen on ohio's may 3 primary ballot
marvin bush, the 31-year-old son of vice president george bush, filed his father's documents on thursday, shortly before representatives of bob dole gave the kansas senator's petitions to secretary of state sherrod brown
steven fought, brown's communications director, said petitions were filed later on behalf of former television evangelist pat robertson, former gov. pete du pont of delaware, and new york rep. jack kemp. the filing deadline was 4 p.m. thursday
du pont withdrew from presidential race on thursday
kansas republicans gather at five sites saturday to elect 15 delegates to the party's national convention and recommend five more for ratification at the state convention in topeka on march 5
all 20 people elected saturday will be committed to sen. bob dole in his bid for the gop presidential nomination, which will be decided at the national convention in new orleans in august
dole's supporters overwhelmingly control all five congressional district conventions and the state convention, thanks to his near-sweep of local delegates elected at county caucuses feb. 1-7
only pat robertson claimed any delegates among the other gop contenders in the county caucuses, and he won just six out of 1,249 elected at the local level. nobody else can vote at the district and state conventions
minnesota's republican presidential forum scheduled for sunday has been canceled because organizers could not get national front-runners george bush and bob dole to confirm they would attend
project chairman john r. finnegan, senior vice president and assistant publisher of the st. paul pioneer press dispatch, said thursday that despite epeated efforts, organizers had been unable to obtain confirmation from the vice president or the kansas senator
rep. jack kemp of new york, former television evangelist pat robertson and former minnesota gov. harold stassen had agreed to attend, as had former delaware gov. pete du pont. du pont, however, withdrew from the presidential race thursday
former democratic gov. harvey wollman is endorsing presidential hopeful richard gephardt, saying the missouri congressman is ``one candidate running who can add and subtract.''
wollman told about 100 people at the bergeland center for seniors on thursday that ``that's more than you can say for ronald reagan. he just knows how to add things up.''
wednesday, sen. tom daschle, d-s.d., endorsed gephardt
wollman said he supports gephardt because the congressman is from rural america and has the common sense and knowledge to straighten out problems in the united states. wollman served as governor in 1978, lieutenant governor from 1974-1978 and now farms near huron
ted thoms, co-chairman of bruce babbitt's campaign, said thursday he was transferring his allegiance to gephardt now that babbitt has left the presidential race
democratic presidential candidate jesse jackson's campaign expects endorsements sunday from the city's two most prominent politicians: rep. william h. gray iii and mayor w. wilson goode
philadelphia councilman lucien blackwell, jackson's pennsylvania campaign chairman, said thursday that jackson also will be endorsed at a fund-raising luncheon in philadelphia by mayor melvin r. ``randy'' primas jr. of camden, n.j
gray, goode and primas _ like jackson _ are black, and blackwell said it is important for jackson to get the support of black politicians while also seeking the support of other leaders
i think it's important because if you can't get support at home, i don't think you can solicit support abroad,'' blackwell said. ``it's important to have all support, but most importantly, people who are close to him.''
the federal trade commission has been asked to investigate its staff's review of a proposed takeover of federated department stores inc. and report back to a congressional panel next week
testimony by the ftc before the house energy and commerce transportation subcommittee on thursday was cut short after the commissioners said they were not familiar with the details of the review
subcommittee chairman rep. thomas luken, d-ohio, dismissed the commissioners after several unsuccessful attempts to question them on why the agency decided not to pursue a further, more extensive investigation into potential anticompetitive effects of the merger between the cincinnati-based federated and campeau corp. of canada
ftc chairman daniel oliver said the agency's bureau of competition spent 250 hours reviewing the merger and ``i have confidence in the bureau director.''
two baltimore men who oppose u.s. aid to the nicaraguan contra rebels were to be arraigned today on charges of unlawful entry after they refused to leave the capitol hill office of rep. lee hamilton, authorities said
michael bardoff, 30, and kevin hornbuckle, 25, were arrested at 7 p.m. thursday and charged with unlawful entry at the indiana democrat's office, said u.s. capitol police officer dan nichols
bardoff was detained overnight in the district of columbia jail after a bond hearing, while hornbuckle was released on his own recognizance, nichols said. both were scheduled for arraignment today in superior court
the two had entered hamilton's office at 2:30 p.m. and had vowed to remain there ``until they received assurances that contra aid would not go through the cia,'' said richard ochs, a spokesman for the baltimore emergency response network, a group that opposes contra aid
a senate sucommittee plans to hear from filmmakers steven spielberg and george lucas next month as it considers expanding the nation's copyright laws to prevent the controversial coloring of black-and-white films
the directors guild of america said thursday that spielberg and lucas, who between them have made some of the world's biggest moneymaking movies, will testify march 3 before the senate judiciary subcommittee on patents, copyrights and trademarks in favor of legislation giving directors the ``moral rights'' over changes in their completed works
spielberg, who opposes the coloring of old films, said in a statement thursday: ``moral rights are essential to protect future generations from the kind of big business greed that doesn't care about the desecration of timeless treasures.''
president reagan called to console the family of marine lt. col. william r. higgins, stung by the double blow of higgins' abduction in lebanon and the death of his father a day later
the president telephoned the colonel's wife this afternoon and offered all the support he knew how to give her ... i think it helped her tremendously,'' harold fisher, higgins' brother-in-law, said thursday
fisher, noting that eight other americans are being held in lebanon, said, ``one of the hardest parts is seeing how they are held captive, with no resolution in sight. being the ninth, you just don't know.''
the family learned of higgins' kidnapping by islamic revolutionaries wednesday when they telephoned his wife, marine maj. robin higgins, who works in the pentagon's public affairs office, with news of the elder higgins' imminent death
william f. higgins, 72, died from cardiopulmonary arrest and kidney failure thursday morning without knowing of his son's ordeal. the last time father and son saw each other was in september 1987, when higgins came home on emergency leave from the middle east
he never knew that his son had been taken captive. it was a blessing that he didn't know,'' fisher told a news conference. fisher is married to higgins' sister, mary, who did not attend the news conference
fisher said the family was doing well, considering the ordeal
it's difficult to accept the death of a father and then at the same time something that's so unknown as what's really taking place'' with the lieutenant colonel
fisher said the family was happy that higgins had chosen to serve his country as a united nations observer. ``we have confidence that our government will do what is best and necessary for our country and for his safety,'' he said
higgins, 43, was abducted as he returned from a meeting in tyre with officials of lebanese justice minister nabih berri's shiite amal militia to discuss efforts to free foreign hostages in lebanon
it could be two days, two years or never. it's a sad situation,'' fisher said of prospects for higgins' release
he said, however, that higgins ``will handle the situation better than most people because of the training he has had. he is a very strong individual.''
fisher said the military had also been in touch with the family and ``given us some telephone numbers to call for information. we are comfortable with the arrangements they have provided.''
president-elect roh tae-woo unveiled a new cabinet today in which several key posts went to hardliners and holdovers from the old government. widespread hopes for major changes were unfulfilled
roh, who takes office feb. 25, has pledged to end south korea's long tradition of authoritarian rule and restore full democracy
but cabinet security posts went to hardliners. technocrats, civil servants and academics took most other posts
the naming of the 23-member cabinet was closely watched for evidence roh would follow through on promises for sweeping reforms. many of the new ministers are politically unknown
political observers said the new cabinet was little different from the one it will replace and does not appear to contain independents or reformers
roh stressed the need for stability in making the appointments, saying the government had to ensure political and economic calm. he also underlined the need to guarantee the success of the 1988 olympic games, which are scheduled for september in seoul
i call on you new ministers to make maximum efforts to turn the nation into an advanced country by enhancing the people's capability and integrating national strength,'' roh told them
opposition parties charged that roh is determined to continue the authoritarian rule of outgoing president chun doo-hwan
despite much talk, the new cabinet falls far short of expectations,'' said an opposition statement
however, the main opposition reunification democratic party and the party for peace and democracy had rejected roh's invitation to nominate candidates for the cabinet, saying they doubted roh's ability to bring about reform
roh retained seven ministers from the chun government, including those holding the key posts of foreign affairs, home affairs and justice
home minister lee sang-hee heads the police and justice minister chung hae-chang supervised recent crackdowns on political dissidents. the foreign minister is choi kwang-soo
new defense minister oh ja-bok, a recently retired general and armed forces commander, is a hardliner who has attacked opposition parties in the past
oh is expected to be roh's link to the powerful military, which has long dominated the country. he supported chun and roh and other young generals who took power in 1980 with military backing
ahn moo-hyuk was retained as head of south korea's powerful intelligence agency, the agency for national security planning. the director works with the cabinet, but is not a member
roh had pledged to increase substantially the power of the cabinet as part of his promises to usher in full democracy. traditionally, ministers have had little power, with most decisions being made by the presidency
the appointment feb. 11 of noted moderate lee hyun-jae as prime minister had spurred hope the new cabinet would include people with new outlooks
roh said the new government would seek to end the political, regional and social divisions that have long troubled south korea
the new government should stand in the vanguard to create conditions under which the entire people would be willing to participate,'' he said
roh won the presidential elections on dec. 16 with 36.7 percent of the vote. chun had agreed to elections after huge protests for democractic government last summer
roh, saying he is determined to maintain the country's rapid economic growth and massive exports drive, held over some key economic experts, including finance minister sakong il
outgoing trade minister rha woong-bae was promoted to the joint post of deputy prime minister and economic planning minister
business and trade groups applauded the makeup of the cabinet, saying it would help to bolster economic growth while stabilizing prices and other economic factors. allegations</head>
the government asked the u.s. ambassador for the names of u.s. officials who were the sources for a newspaper report alleging links between the honduran military and colombian drug traffickers
foreign minister carlos lopez contreras said in a statement thursday that the government also wants the names of members of the honduran military who were accused of involvement in the narcotics trade and details of the illegal acts they purportedly committed
notwithstanding the seriousness of the charges formulated (against honduras), for the moment what most displeases and disturbs my government is that these are attributed to (high-level u.s. officials),'' lopez contreras said
he said that if the names were not forthcoming, ``then we await the satisfactions (consequences) that the case warrants.'' he did not elaborate
this is not the appropriate moment to get into analyzing the truthfulness or falseness of the charges provided by anonymous but identifiable sources,'' the statement said
a story in the new york times last week quoted unidentified u.s. and honduran officials as saying honduras was in danger of being overrun by colombian drug dealers
the newspaper reported the sources as saying narcotics traffickers had corrupted honduran army officers, offered money to political parties and bought businesses and land to launder drug profits
the honduran military denied the charges and demanded that the government of president jose azcona hoyo file lawsuits against newspapers that report such accounts
both azcona hoyo and u.s. ambassador everett briggs held news conferences on tuesday at which they called the reports untrue
briggs said the stories were ``very imaginative and inventive.''
i am the principal and highest official of the united states in honduras and i totally disavow this situation that has appeared in the newspapers of my country,'' briggs said
prices were mostly lower on the london stock exchange early today
the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index opened 4 points, or 0.23 percent, lower at 1,732.1
by 9:45 a.m. the index was only slightly changed at 1,732.5, down 3.6 from thursday's close
forty-five of the ft-se 100 issues were down, 10 up and the remainder unchanged in early trading today
brokers attributed the lower trend to wall street's decline thursday
about 5,000 people evacuated after a toxic chemical leak tainted the sandusky river were permitted to return to their homes today after fumes dissipated, the mayor said
a water emergency remained in effect in this northwestern ohio city of 22,000 after an estimated 100,000 gallons of flammable toluene spilled wednesday from a ruptured sun co. pipeline south of here
reserve tanks which hold about 4 million gallons of water were expected to last until late this afternoon, mayor fred singer said
at least three people were treated for injuries after an undetermined amount of the chemical flowed into the river, and as many as 5,000 residents were evacuated wednesday and thursday because of the fumes, officials said
toluene can produce irritating or poisonous gases, according to an emergency response guidebook published by the u.s. department of transportation
city and u.s. environmental protection agency officials assessed the air quality during the night
we just returned with federal epa people and have monitored the situation, and we are satisfied that it will be safe for the people to return to the evacuated areas,'' singer said early this morning
gov. richard celeste on thursday declared a state of emergency for sandusky county, which includes fremont. the declaration makes state assistance available
the toluene was detected wednesday night from a sun co. pipeline near tiffin, about 20 miles upstream from fremont
bob arnet, an environmental safety coordinator for the tulsa, okla.-based sun pipe line, said thursday that authorities had turned off the pipeline, but had not located the leak
the city stopped taking in water from the river before the spill reached fremont late thursday, officials said. they estimated a 14-mile section of the river was contaminated
under the water emergency, industries are prohibited from using water, and residents are urged to conserve
singer said city officials were considering having the national guard truck in water from clyde, about 10 miles southeast of fremont
epa officials said they believed much of the chemical would dissipate by the time it reaches lake erie
singer criticized sun officials for not notifying fremont officials of the spill until thursday, and said the city will seek reimbursement from the company for expenses incurred
it's real interesting. no one contacted us until 5 p.m., and the chemical is dangerous and highly combustible,'' singer said. ``they acted very irresponsibly.''
sun spokesman bud davis, said the company would take ``liability and responsibility for the leak'' and cleanup, which could cost as much as $1 million and take three to four months
two fremont residents on thursday filed a class-action lawsuit in u.s. district court in toledo against the sun pipe line co
joe albrechta, an attorney for lupe avalos and barry halstead, said no specific dollar amount was named in the suit, which seeks compensation for lost wages, property damage and damages for emotional stress created by the incident
the spill occurred in a swampy area in seneca county, south of fremont, and then leaked into sugar creek, a tributary of the sandusky river, said sonya elam, a spokeswoman for the ohio disaster services agency. the sandusky river flows north into lake erie
two emergency workers were treated at tiffin mercy hospital after they fell through ice and into contaminated water, and a volunteer firefighter was treated after inhaling the fumes. all were subsequently released
ohio epa spokesman allan franks said at least 100 dead fish were visible in the river. he said officials suspect there may be 1,000 dead fish under the ice
heavy rain spread across the south today, touching off high-water alerts, while snow was widely scattered in the plains and west and southern california had high winds
a drenching rain fell in northern florida. rain spread across alabama, georgia and south carolina, and prompted flood warnings in sections of southeast louisiana. flash flood watches were issued in sections of southeast mississippi, southern and central alabama and the florida panhandle
a narrow band of rain and snow extended from northeast oklahoma across southeast kansas and west central missouri
rain and mountain snow dotted eastern arizona and western new mexico
strong winds developed across much of southern california. high wind warnings were posted for much of the region warning of gusts of 60 to 70 mph
today's forecast called for rain widespread from the middle mississippi valley across the tennessee and ohio valleys into the mid-atlantic states and carolinas; showers and thunderstorms from the central gulf coast across georgia and northern florida; snow over southwest michigan and northern sections of illinois and indiana; and rain and mountain snow showers across southeast arizona and southern new mexico
highs were expected to be in the 30s from the dakotas across the upper mississippi valley to the great lakes and across portions of illinois, indiana, northern maine and the central rockies; 60s and 70s over california, southwest arizona, south texas, the central gulf coast region, northern florida, southern georgia and coastal south carolina; 80s in central and southern florida; and 40s to 50s across most of the rest of the nation
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from zero at craig, colo., to 74 degrees at key west, fla
