every day, neighbors say, a retarded 13-year-old boy would go behind his house and play with a toy gun
silvielo grohse's youthful game turned into tragedy when two officers mistook his plaything for the real thing and fatally shot him
he was such a sweet boy,'' said steve diamond, the seventh-grader's teacher. ``he loved to be hugged. he would come up and put his head on your shoulder and just hug you.''
the youngster was shot wednesday by the officers after they ordered him to drop the weapon and he instead spun around toward them, police said thursday
the boy is retarded, and he played back here every day because it's not safe in front of the projects,'' said neighbor debra judkins. ``the cops should know better than to gun down a child.''
grohse was dead on arrival at san francisco general hospital, said dr. richard cales. the boy stood 5-foot-8 and weighed about 190 pounds
police spokesman jerry senkir said there was no evidence the officers, michael huddleston and janet campbell, acted improperly. he said grohse's toy gun resembled a .22-caliber revolver
according to senkir, the officers were answering a call of shots being fired in the drug-plagued area when they spotted the youth walking with the toy gun in his hand. they pulled within 40 feet of him, got out of their patrol car and crouched behind open doors with guns drawn, ordering the youth to drop his gun
the suspect then turned and pointed the gun at the officers,'' senkir said. ``at the same time, he crouched down and let out a yell. both officers immediately opened fire.''
the officers fired four shots from their .357-caliber magnum service revolvers, he said
weren't they supposed to give him a warning or something, like `freeze?''' asked grohse's 12-year-old cousin. ``couldn't they have shot in the air first instead of killing him?''
police union officials have called for community meetings between residents and police to defuse the tension surrounding the shooting
