a hot-air balloon billed as the largest ever built lifted off at sunrise today from a frozen lake on its first flight
the super maine, 10 percent to 20 percent larger in volume than the largest hot-air ballon on record, rose 50 feet off the ground just before 6:30 a.m. with 25 crew members aboard
it stayed in the air, tethered to ropes, for several minutes while 100 people watched from the western shore of sebago lake in southern maine
everything's come together almost perfectly,'' project coordinator and chief pilot tom handcock said after the flight, which organizers hoped would earn them an entry in the guinness book of records
organizers of the super maine project did not try to beat the flight time of the virgin atlantic flyer, which set records by flying from maine across the atlantic ocean last summer. handcock said they only wanted to build a balloon that was larger in volume than the flyer
to qualify as an air balloon, it had to lift off the ground, no matter how briefly
the balloonists could not fly the balloon today even if they had wanted to. since organizers did not complete federal aviation administration paperwork in time, they were required to keep the balloon tethered, handcock said
after the first flight, organizers took the balloon up several more times, adding more people each time to its 8-by-12-foot gondola. at one point, 60 people were in the balloon's basket, with one man hanging onto the side as the balloon lifted off the the ground a few feet
the 210-foot-high, 168-foot-wide balloon is considered the largest because it holds 2.6 million cubic feet of hot air, between 300,000 and 500,000 cubic feet more than the 195-foot virgin atlantic flyer, handcock said
aboard the gondola on the first flight were 25 commercial balloon pilots, who built the balloon with the help of 25 other balloon enthusiasts from new england, kentucky, maryland and canada
the balloon was constructed of a polyethylene derivative called olifin and was assembled with an adhesive the organizers developed, said handcock and his wife, mig. it was constructed in four days in a massachusetts warehouse and trucked to maine
richard branson and per linstrand flew the virgin atlantic flyer into the guinness book last july by taking the balloon 2,789.6 miles from carrabassett valley to a brief touchdown in ireland before it crashed into the sea. the balloon flew 87.7 mph and took 31 hours and 38 minutes to cross the atlantic
government soldiers killed 33 anti-marxist rebels in the past week in three battles in southern mozambique, the national news agency reported today
eleven guerrillas of the mozambique national resistance were killed tuesday in fighting at bela vista, the aim agency said. it cited an unidentified military source
in addition, 17 rebels died in a battle at funhalouro, north of the capital, and five were killed at namaacha, 45 miles west of maputo, the news agency said
aim said the two battles were fought in the past week, but did not give the exact date. the aim report made no mention of government casualties in any of the conflicts
the rebels have been fighting for 11 years to topple mozambique's marxist government. guerrilla attacks on both civilian and military targets have seriously disrupted the economy and food supplies. an estimated 4.5 million of the country's 14.5 million people are in need of food aid
mozambique accuses neighboring south africa of aiding the rebels, but south africa claims it stopped providing support under the terms of a mutual non-aggresion pact signed by the two countries in 1984
both sides regularly accuse the other of violations and often trade harsh criticism
a computer whiz may face the death penalty if convicted of any of seven murder charges stemming from a shooting rampage through the silicon valley plant where he once worked
richard wade farley, 39, was arraigned thursday in san jose municipal court on the homicide charges, three counts of attempted murder and a count each of felony vandalism and second-degree burglary. he did not enter a plea
after the two-minute hearing, santa clara county deputy district attorney alan nudelman said he will seek capital punishment in the murder cases
about 200 employees at esl inc. on thursday toured the building where the attack occurred two days earlier as ``part of the healing process,'' said company spokeswoman edie cartwright
the employees saw walls, floors and furniture riddled with bullet holes and dozens of computer terminals with screens shot out, cartwright said. many windows were shattered. bloodstains were painted over and most rugs removed
the building, where 300 of the company's 2,200 employees mainly work on classified defense projects, was to reopen its first floor today. employees will return monday to the second floor, where most of the damage occurred
the first funeral for victims of the attack was scheduled later today for glenda moritz, a 27-year-old planner
farley was brought to court in handcuffs and shackles from an isolation cell where guards said he has been quiet and apparently writing letters
it was with rambling and threatening notes sent through the mail that the software engineer harassed former co-worker laura black before finally wounding her and two others and killing seven people tuesday in a six-hour siege at esl in sunnyvale, 40 miles south of san francisco
investigators and colleagues said farley apparently had no criminal record, was honorably discharged after 11 years in the navy, was intelligent and had held several high-security defense jobs
while in jail, farley ``has been kind of pondering his thoughts,'' said sheriff's sgt. cary colla, who added he had asked for envelopes to mail letters. farley, colla said, also inquired about phone privileges
wearing glasses and a red jumpsuit, farley looked around the courtroom during arraignment before judge hugh mullin iii, who ordered that he continue to be held without bail. he is to return to court march 4 to enter a plea
gregory c. paraskou, a deputy county public defender appointed to represent farley, said he had not spoken to his client about a plea
farley is being held in a isolation cell reserved for high-risk inmates. it is outfitted with a large observation window which allows guards close supervision
still recovering thursday were the four esl employees injured in the attack, including black, who was in stable condition with a gunshot wound to her shoulder
the 26-year-old electrical engineer, called the main target of the shootings, said she was haunted for four years by strange gifts, threatening letters and obsessive behavior involving a man she never dated
a son of polygamist matriarch vickie singer has been found in contempt for refusing to answer a grand jury's questions about the bombing of a mormon chapel and subsequent two-week standoff with police
after a brief closed hearing, u.s. district judge j. thomas greene opened the courtroom thursday while arguments were presented on the government's motion seeking the contempt citation against hans benjamin singer, 15
greene ordered the teen-ager under house arrest at the fairview home of ramon and harriett swapp while the matter is under appeal to the 10th u.s. circuit court of appeals
the swapps are the parents of addam swapp, who is married to two daughters of mrs. singer
earlier this month, four members of the clan _ including mrs. singer, widow of slain polygamist john singer _ pleaded innocent to federal charges stemming from the bombing of a mormon chapel in marion and the 13-day siege that followed at the clan's nearby farm
the standoff ended jan. 28 when corrections lt. fred house was killed and clan patriarch addam swapp was wounded. swapp, 26; his brother jonathan, 21; mrs. singer, 44, and her son, john timothy singer, 21, were indicted on counts ranging from conspiracy, possession and use of a bomb and firearms violations to assault and attempting to kill federal agents
a homicide charge is expected to be filed by prosecutors later this month
on feb. 5 and again wednesday, hans singer refused to answer questions from the grand jury. the boy refused to give information on matters about which he had ``personal, eyewitness knowledge,'' greene said
greene said he had granted the youth immunity from prosecution, a move authorized by the department of justice so that there could be no question of his incriminating himself
singer's refusal to answer questions from the panel came in the wake of greene's ruling that the boy had no rights to ``parent-child privilege.''
the youth's attorney, steven kuhnhausen, argued that his client ``has deeply held religious beliefs that he believes preclude him from being compelled to testify against his mother or members of his extended family.''
u.s. attorney brent ward argued that there was every indication that the boy could be a competent witness possessing first-hand knowledge of crimes ``by persons already indicted and persons not yet indicted.''
according to mrs. singer's diary, used as evidence at a previous hearing, the youth accompanied addam and jonathan swapp when they bombed the chapel. morning news show comment from aids coordinator, transition. adds 1 graf at end with more comment.</note>
aids should be attacked by creating a series of specialized institutes that bring together key scientific disciplines, medical experts told the president's aids commission
the strategy, modeled after the comprehensive cancer center program of the early 1970s, would provide a useful cross-fertilization of ideas for dealing with the complex disease, they said
medical schools and universities would be logical places to build four or five such comprehensive centers, richard ross, dean of the medical faculty at the johns hopkins university school of medicine in baltimore, said thursday
the centers could combine such disciplines as prevention, education, patient care, studies in humans and basic research into the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome, he said thursday
ideas developed in the laboratory could then be tested quickly in patients, he said
another aids expert, dr. anthony fauci, coordinator of federal aids research for the national institutes of health, defended today the rigorous testing process promising aids treatments must undergo before approval
the reason that only one drug has been made available, azt, is because it is the only drug that thus far has been shown in scientifically controlled trials to be safe and effective. it isn't a question of there are a lot of drugs around and only one is being released. that's the only one that has been shown to be effective,'' fauci said on abc-tv's ``good morning america.''
ross told the presidential commission on the human immunodeficiency virus epidemic that lack of space is one obstacle in developing comprehensive aids centers
we have the people, we have the interest, we have the commitment, but we don't have the space,'' he said. ``and we need your help in getting the space.''
retired adm. james d. watkins, chairman of the commission, asked ross to develop details of his proposal and supply them to the commission later
in an interview, ross said he did not know how much the proposed centers would cost. he estimated the buildings alone would cost some $75 million to $100 million apiece, but said he did not know what an annual operating budget would be
in his testimony, he also urged that about an equal amount of money as would go to the comprehensive centers be earmarked for institutions proposing research in one or more subject areas, short of the comprehensive approach
the idea of comprehensive centers was also proposed by aids researcher jerome groopman of deaconess hospital in boston, who urged consideration of establishing 10 to 15 such centers
he also suggested federal aids research grants be extended beyond the traditional three-year or five-year terms because research toward a vaccine or cure could well take far longer
on testing drugs for aids treatment, fauci, who also is director of national institue of allergies and infectious disease, said in the abc interview, ``if you look at the clinical trials that are going on now, there are a number of drugs that are in clinical trial, hopefully they will be expeditiously shown to either be safe and effective or will be discarded because they have been proven not to be safe and effective.'' 02-19 0630</first>
if president reagan's proposed budget actually becomes america's budget for 1989, it will mean that the federal government will collect $1,687 in individual income taxes for every man, woman and child in the country
that's an increase of $65 from the budget he presented a year ago, due almost entirely to economic growth
the mathematics are straightforward. divide the $412.4 billion expected through individual income taxes during the year by 244.4 million people, the u.s. population as of jan. 1. last year, when the total population was 242.1 million, the assumption was that individual income taxes would bring in $392.8 billion
according to the budget proposal reagan sent to capitol hill on thursday, the federal government expects its total receipts in 1989 to be $964.7 billion. besides the personal income tax, the sum includes corporate income taxes of $117.7 billion and social security taxes of $354.6 billion. the rest will come from estate and gift taxes, customs duties, excise taxes and the like
using the same population formula for this year, the total receipts represent $3,947 for everyone from the tiniest to the oldest centenarian
the source of money flowing in to the government has changed greatly in the reagan years, the administration points out. the individual and corporate income tax share of total receipts in 1989 is expected to be 4.7 percentage points less than 1980 when three out of every five dollars came from income taxes
the administration tagged two displaced worker programs for extinction because they have not ``operated efficiently to help workers adjust.''
one provides unemployment benefit payments when unemployment insurance runs out. the administration feels those additional weeks of payments ``encourage workers to delay efforts to seek new opportunities in the hope that somehow their old jobs will reappear.'' in the current year, the program cost $48 million in federal money
the second program, costing $287 million in 1988, pays states for helping dislocated workers find new occupations that use their skills, get training in new skills or meet the cost of looking for jobs. that money, says the budget, should go into a new worker readjustment program
the administration also wants to drop a work incentive program that provided job services, training and public service employment to welfare recipients
although its aim is to help curb welfare dependency, it has not proved successful or cost-effective,'' the proposal said. the government budgeted $93 million for the program this year
reagan's budget proposal for 1988 asked congress to tack on $1 for every ticket for international travel to and from the united states to be used for a government program that encourages foreign travel to the united states
congress did not pass the legislation last year and the administration wants it brought up again
money for recreation is to be cut back under the proposal from $1.7 billion this year to $1.4 billion
to make that cut, the administration wants to reduce the amount spent for buying land from $232 million to $51 million. and it proposes a halt in buying some land for park and refuge purposes through 1993 _ except for wetlands acquired with revenue from sale of duck hunting stamps and the like
the budget also makes clear that pardons are on the increase. last year, there were only 23 pardons granted by the president. that number is estimated to increase to 50 this fiscal year and 50 again in the next. there was no explanation. the number of ``denials and no actions,'' _ 290 in 1987 _ is expected to increase slightly to 300 this year and next. arrest.</note>
after a police detective was fatally shot in a drug raid, mayor raymond flynn criticized the federal government as a missing partner in the fight against ``america's vicious cycle of drugs and guns.''
detective sherman c. griffiths, 36, died thursday of a head wound suffered wednesday night. his death and those of two other officers since october were related to drug or weapon violations
flynn and police commissioner francis m. roache on thursday claimed washington is relaxing handgun controls and drug enforcement and rehabilitation programs just when tougher measures are needed
they've almost given up at the federal government,'' said roache. ``but we haven't given up in boston. we're doing everything humanly possible to protect our neighborhoods.''
this is a very, very sad day for the boston police department,'' flynn said. ``america's vicious cycle of drugs and guns has claimed another victim
great efforts are being made by our police department. they're out there doing their job every day, but there's a partner that's missing,'' said flynn. ``we need allies on the federal level.''
we're not satisfied here with nice catchwords about drugs, we want good solid programs,'' said flynn. ``at least we shouldn't throw up our hands at our border and say nothing can be done.''
griffiths was shot when he and five other plainclothes officers, armed with a search warrant, tried to force their way into an apartment in the dorchester section to look for illegal drugs
two shots were fired from inside, and one bullet hit griffiths. one officer returned fire, but did not wound anyone in the apartment
griffiths, who was married and the father of two, died at boston city hospital
albert lewin, 33, of boston, pleaded innocent to a murder charge and four other related weapons and assault charges at his arraignment thursday. he was ordered held without bail, a court clerk said
four other people pleaded innocent to charges of conspiracy to violate drug laws, said police spokesman james jordan. trial was scheduled feb. 29. a sixth person was arrested today and also is accused of murder and related offenses
the first of the three officers to die since oct. 26 was detective roy sergei, 42, who died three weeks after being wounded in a shootout. his partner was also wounded but survived
the suspect in that shooting, ted otsuki, is on the fbi's most wanted list
on feb. 10, detective thomas j. gill, 38, died after he was struck by an amtrak train while searching for guns taken in a housebreak
two officers, one on the boston force and one with the metropolitan district police, were wounded during a drug bust last month. an alleged cocaine dealer turned a shotgun on an undercover officer in the jan. 29 incident and was killed in the ensuing shootout. graf pvs, sen. sam nunn. edits throughout to conform.</note>
defense secretary frank carlucci said today america faces higher risks because of president reagan's military budget, which kills some weapons and reduces troop strength
the reductions were sent to congress on thursday as part of the budget's military spending package, which was cut in the effort to reduce federal deficits
carlucci said he chose to cut by eliminating some older weapons and by small decreases in troop strength, rather than by wholesale reductions
what it translates into is a smaller military force,'' carlucci said on nbc-tv's ``today'' show. ``it clearly means higher risks. but we have elected to do this rather than hollow out the force.''
we want to maintain good people, adequate readiness, good sustainability and we want to continue the modernization program of those weapons that we consider absolutely essential and we want to do so in the most cost-effective way,'' he said
reagan's military budget was praised by lawmakers
sen. sam nunn, d-ga., chairman of the senate armed services committee, told carlucci on thursday that he made ``exactly the right choices.''
sen. carl levin, d-mich., a critic of past pentagon budgets, praised carlucci for a ``very helpful'' budget
sen. william roth, r-del., said, ``the pentagon appears to have taken its responsibility for budget cutting more seriously in this proposed budget than in those of the past years.''
the budget proposed to authorize $299.5 billion in pentagon spending for the fiscal year starting oct. 1, including $294 billion that would actually be paid out during the 12-month period. that compares with $291.4 billion authorized for the current year
the overall pentagon budget level had been set during talks between the administration and congress last november, when reagan approved the $299.5 billion level
he originally had wanted $332.4 billion, which would have been an increase after three years of decreased spending. those reductions followed large buildups during reagan's first four years in office, when the pentagon budget doubled as part of reagan's pledge to ``rearm america.''
in the past eight weeks, carlucci said, civilian and military leaders have made ``hard choices'' to reduce spending by the $33 billion needed to reach the $299.5 billion level
carlucci said he chose ``a smaller force that was fully ready to perform its mission as opposed to a large force that was not ready. the priorities in this budget were straightforward _ people, readiness and efficient acquisition.''
i believe these choices to be not in the best interest of our national security posture,'' said carlucci. ``however, i have made them. they reflect the fiscal realities we face today and my assessment of the direction'' the pentagon should go
adm. william crowe jr., chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, said ``in a fiscally constrained environment, we had to borrow somewhat against the future to nourish the deterrent stance we have today.''
among the choices:
_the total strength of the four uniformed services will drop by 34,000 men and women, to a total of 2,138,000. the air force will take the largest reduction, accounting for 23,000 of the total cuts. but carlucci also called for a 4.3 percent pay hike for the troops and said the money is needed to keep up the high quality of recruits and re-enlistments
to meet the reductions, the army plans to cut its brigade of motorized infantry at fort lewis, wash., and cancel a previously scheduled activation of two light infantry battalions in alaska
the navy will scrap plans to establish a 14th air wing at the miramar, calif., naval air station. sixteen frigates and a missile-firing submarine will be retired and the sailors will be sent to other ships. the air force will deactivate two fighter wings and start deactivating a third
other reductions include army plans to retire 450 vietnam-era utility helicopters and 170 scout copters; cancel the troubled aquila surveillance drone program and stop production of copperhead laser-guided artillery shells; cancel development of the anti-tactical missile; and develop only one new light helicopter instead of two
_delay development of the single-warhead midgetman nuclear-tipped missile, but include $200 million to keep the program alive until a new administration can decide its fate. nunn is a supporter of the weapon. carlucci also proposed putting all 100 mx weapons aboard trains, rather than having 50 of the 10-warhead weapons aboard trains and the other 50 in land-based silos in wyoming
_kill the air force anti-satellite weapon, which congress had banned for two years from final-stage testing. the pentagon had pushed for continued development of the weapon, but carlucci said it was dropped this year because of the continued opposition from capitol hill
the foreign ministry said the regime of cuban president fidel castro violates most civil and political rights and that hundreds of thousands of people want to leave the nation, a newspaper reported
the right-wing madrid daily abc also quoted the confidential report as saying the united states was hoping to persuade the united nations to include cuba among nations periodically studied for possible human rights violations
susana ansorena, a foreign ministry spokeswoman, today confirmed that a report on the overall situation in cuba had been compiled, but she refused to reveal its contents and described it as a ``normal, confidential ministry document.''
spain has been consistently concerned with human rights in cuba and has done everything within its possibilities to defend them,'' she added
as reported thursday in abc, the document stated that, ``given the characteristics of the cuban regime, the number of people that seek to leave the country is estimated at between 200,000 and 500,000.''
abc quoted the report as saying the castro regime ``violates most civil and political rights, including the rights of free speech and assembly, has a judicial system that fails to protect rights and currently has between 1,000 and 10,000 political prisoners.''
the newspaper said the foreign ministry also found that ``a campaign to rectify errors'' under way for more than a year in cuba, had led to ``a serious economic and ideological crisis.''
abc said the document went on to add that ``the line adopted by cuba to overcome its crisis does not coincide with _ and in fact is contrary to _ that which (soviet leader mikhail) gorbachev envisions for the soviet union and the socialist bloc.''
ms. ansorena said the government of socialist prime minister felipe gonzalez saw the publication of the confidential report ``as an attempt to prejudge its position and thus pressure it into condemning the human rights situation in cuba'' in an upcoming meeting of the u.n. human rights commission in geneva
the independent counsel investigating the iran-contra affair has retained noted constitutional scholar laurence tribe to represent his office during an expected supreme court review of the special prosecutor law
independent counsel lawrence e. walsh on thursday asked the high court for permission to allow tribe, a harvard university law professor, to file a friend-of-the court brief to defend the constitutionality of the special prosecutor law
another independent counsel, alexia morrison, has asked the court to review last month's decision by the u.s. circuit court of appeals here that struck down the contitutionality of judicial appointment of special prosecutors to investigate alleged wrongdoing by high government officials
the divided appellate panel ruled that court appointment of special prosecutors, or independent counsels as they are formally called, encroaches on the president's exclusive consstitutional authority to enforce the law
the court could agree to take the case as early as monday
unlike morrison, walsh has a parallel appointment from the justice department to investigate the iran-contra affair, so the appeals court decision does not threaten his prosecutorial authority
but his office participated as a friend of the court in appellate court arguments last year on the challenge to the law
