in one moment, the shouts of happiness turned to groans of sorrow and golden hopes became dashed dreams
oh no, not again,'' exclaimed one hometown fan as he watched olympic speed skater dan jansen fall to the ice with about 200 meters left in the 1000-meter race at the calgary games
he's got too much hurt,'' said another. ``he's trying too bad to win something for his sister.''
jansen's friends and fans had gathered thursday night to watch the televised race at a tavern next to the state fairgrounds, where earlier this month he won the world sprint speed skating championship
on this night, however, they saw jansen lose his balance just as he did four nights earlier, trying to carry the hope for an olympic medal and the burden of his sister's death
danny comes in here all the time,'' said randy strumberger, a bartender at the tavern. ``when he comes in again, i'll run around the bar and hug him and buy him his first drink.''
for jansen's friends and family in this milwaukee suburb of nearly 64,000, thursday's race was another chapter in a week of tragedy. on sunday, jansen's sister, jane, died of leukemia. hours later, jansen fell in the first turn of the 500-meter race, in which he was favored for a medal. he did not finish
between then and thursday, the community rallied behind their hometown hero, and thousands of people signed a banner that was sent to jansen in calgary
the banner proclaimed: ``dan be strong. keep the faith. wisconsin is with you all the way.''
it's amazing the number of people i run into who know the jansen family,'' said jim hill, a customer at the tavern. ``this is a small community.''
but the dreams of jansen overcoming his emotional turmoil and skating to victory and gold were shattered in an instant once again
it was horrifying,'' said his father, harry jansen, who watched the race at home with other family members. ``it was unbelievable, especially that it happened like that on a straightaway.''
jansen spoke with his son earlier in the day. ``i asked him how he was doing, and he said he was feeling pretty good. but then he would read some of the nice telegrams he got and he said would start feeling down again
i told him he's a champion in my book.''
but while jansen believed his son fell in the earlier race because of pressures from the sister's death, he doubted the same was true for thursday's fall
he was skating too good,'' jansen said. ``his concentration looked good. his stamina was good. i thought he was going to skate a good race, and he did.''
jansen said he would offer his son encouragement when he arrived home today for his sister's funeral on saturday
i'm proud of him,'' he said. ``he did well just to get out there and set an example for everyone else.'' graf pvs: `it could...'</note>
pope john paul ii today blamed the east and west for the world's economic and social injustices and said their ``exaggerated concern for security'' widened the gap between rich and poor
in his seventh encyclical, the polish-born pontiff said the injustices forced developing countries to be ``cogs on a gigantic wheel.''
the 102-page document is an authoritative statement of the church's social doctrine. titled in latin ``sollicitudo rei socialis,'' meaning the social concern of the church, it represents an effort by john paul to give force to themes he has espoused during the 9{ years of his papacy
the pontiff said the church took a critical view of both liberal capitalism and marxist collectivism and that both systems needed urgent reform. he also called for democratic political change in nations with corrupt, dictatorial or authoritarian governments
he called for reform of the international trade, monetary and financial systems and free access for all to advanced technology
an unacceptably exaggerated concern for security ... deadens the impulse toward united cooperation by all ... to the detriment especially of peaceful peoples who are impeded from their rightful access to the goods meant for all,'' he said
the document also said the church should avoid accumulating ``superfluous church ornaments and costly furnishings.''
it could be obligatory to sell these goods in order to provide food, drink, clothing and shelter for those who lack these things,'' it said
at a vatican news conference today, two prelates said the passage on selling church property was ``prophetic'' but did not represent a new position
cardinal roger etchegary, president of the vatican's justice and peace commission, said the passage was symbolic, recalling the time john paul gave away his pastoral ring during a visit to brazil
etchegary said the encyclical was not for the third world or any particular groups. ``its strength of attraction consists in the insistence of depicting the world in its globality and its fundamental unity,'' he said
the pope reviewed problems of social development in the two decades since the encyclical ``populorum progressio'' (development of peoples) was published by pope paul vi in 1967
john paul broke new ground in his forceful attack on the division of the world into ideological and military blocs, which he called ``a direct obstacle to the real transformation of the conditions of underdevelopment in the developing and less advanced countries.''
a vatican official familiar with the drafting of the letter said it reflected the pope's polish background, and addressed problems of people living in the east bloc that had not been raised in paul vi's encyclical
john paul complained of the suppression by some governments of economic initiative, which he said led to emigration, and that some countries were deprived of political and economic sovereignty
while the east and west blocs existed in 1967, ``in light of the subsequent economic and political repercussions and dependencies, the danger is seen to be much greater,'' the document said
each of the two blocs harbors in its own way a tendency toward imperialism ... or toward forms of neo-colonialism,'' it added
the pope said tension between the two blocs has dominated the world political scene for 40 years through the ``cold war,'' ``wars by proxy'' and the threat of nuclear war
john paul said world peace won't be achieved ``unless the world's leaders come to recognize that interdependence in itself demands the abandonment of the politics of blocs, the sacrifice of all forms of economic, military or political imperialism, and the transformation of mutual distrust into collaboration.''
noting that the danger of nuclear conflict ``seems to have receded'' and that the superpowers recently agreed to eliminate a class of nuclear weapons, he added, ``the existence and opposition of the blocs continue to be a real and worrying fact which still colors the world picture.''
conflicts ... between east and west (are) an important cause of the retardation or stagnation of the south,'' the document said
the developing countries, instead of becoming autonomous nations concerned with their own progress toward a just sharing in the goods and services meant for all, become parts of a machine, cogs on a giant wheel.''
explaining the church's role, he wrote, ``the church's social doctrine is not a `third way' between liberal capitalism and marxist collectivism, nor even a possible alternative to other solutions less radically opposed to one another: rather, it constitutes a category of its own ... of theology and particularly of moral theology.''
the document said that 20 years after the ``populorum progressio'' encyclical, hopes for development ``appear very far from being realized,'' and for many poor people ``the situation has noticeably worsened.''
it also lamented an overemphasis on the economic side of development
on other points, the pope denounced totalitarianism and terrorism
he said government birth control campaigns subject people to ``intolerable pressures, including economic ones, in order to force them to submit to this new form of oppression.'' clarify non-binding nature of primary and to correct that primary results can be overturned on march 12; picks up 20th graf pvs, bgng, `of the.'</note>
although the super tuesday primaries of march 8 are grabbing most of the campaign attention, south dakota will bask in a bit of the political limelight as well next week
we're suddenly involved in the process of picking the next president of the united states,'' said clint roberts, the former congressman who came up with the idea of an early primary
the state's presidential primary election had been held early in june, but in 1986 the legislature moved it to feb. 23, sandwiched between the new hampshire primary and super tuesday
south dakota's decision to move the presidential portion of its prirmary from june to february drew a steady trickle of candidates for campaign visits last fall, but the frequency of the visits picked up late in 1987 as candidates combined trips to iowa and south dakota
the trickle turned into a steady stream this week
officials for the campaigns of vice president george bush and sen. bob dole have said dole had an early lead in south dakota because he campaigned and built a strong organization, but that bush has gained somewhat in the past month or so
dole, bush and pat robertson have all advertised on south dakota television
in one television ad, dole stresses that he's the best candidate for the midwest because he grew up in a kansas farm town
dole has visited the state frequently, starting in 1986, when he appeared on behalf of republican candidates for state office
on the democratic side, state party leaders believe rep. richard gephardt of missouri and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis have the best chances in tuesday's primary because they have the strongest state campaign organizations
sen. paul simon of illinois is also seen as having strong support
gephardt and dukakis have spent the most time campaigning in south dakota. gephardt picked up the endorsement of sen. tom daschle on wednesday
following the iowa caucuses, gephardt, simon and dukakis moved extra campaign staff into south dakota
south dakota secretary of state joyce hazeltine predicted wednesday that almost half of the state's registered republicans and a third of democrats will vote in tuesday's presidential primary
both figures are higher than the turnout for the democratic primary in 1984 and the republican primary in 1980, the years on which hazeltine based her predictions
all 18 delegates the south dakota republican party will send to the republican national convention will be selected in the presidential primary. the gop has set a 20 percent threshold in the primary, meaning any candidate who gets less than 20 percent of the popular vote will not get any delegates in south dakota
the democratic national committee had objected to south dakota's early primary because it falls before the party's national deadline for holding primaries, but a compromise was worked out so the primary results could still mean something
as a result of the compromise, south dakota democrats have agreed that tuesday's primary results are officially non-binding, but south dakota party officials say the delegates eventually selected will be apportioned according to the popular vote
however, the statewide caucus on march 12 will have the option of accepting or rejecting the results of the primary. if the primary's results are rejected, the national convention delegates would be awarded to conform to the presidential preferences of the people attending the caucus
the democrats have a threshold of 15 percent for candidates to begin claiming delegates
of the 19 democratic delegates from south dakota, 10 will be based on the primary and another five pledged delegates will be chosen by the democratic state central committee on april 23. the four remaining delegates, top state party officials, will be unpledged. reprimanded, not censured.</head>
rep. mario biaggi faces a fate that has befallen only one congressman in the past 126 years: expulsion from the u.s. house of representatives
that expulsion came eight years ago, when rep. michael ``ozzie'' myers, a pennsylvania democrat, was expelled from congress on oct. 2, 1980, five weeks after his conviction in the abscam bribery scandal
sen. harrison a. williams jr., d-n.j., who was also convicted in abscam, resigned his seat on march 11, 1982, shortly before the senate was about to make him the first senator expelled since the civil war
in 1861 and 1862, fourteen senators and three members of the house from the south were expelled for siding with the confederacy in the war between the states
the first expulsion took place in 1797, when william blount, one of tennessee's first two senators, was turned out of office. president james madison had accused blount of conspiring with the british and the creek and cherokee indians to conquer west florida, then under the control of spain
from blount to myers, only 19 men _ four representatives, 15 senators _ have been expelled in the entire 200-year history of the senate and the house of representatives
in 1967, the house voted to exclude rep. adam clayton powell, d-n.y., but he won a court suit prohibiting congress from denying him a seat
the list of congressman indicted and convicted in office runs much longer. some resigned their seats; others lost re-election bids
then-rep. thomas j. lane, d-mass., spent four months in jail in 1956 for evading $38,542 in income taxes, but was re-elected that fall
myers was one of six house members convicted and sent to prison in the abscam scandal. myers and four others _ reps. john jenrette, d-s.c., john muphy, d-n.y., frank thompson, d-n.j., and richard kelly, r-fla. _ lost re-election bids a few months after their indictments in 1980
rep. raymond lederer, d-pa., won re-election in 1980 while under indictment in that scandal, but was convicted two months later and resigned his seat before going to prison
rep. george hansen, r-idaho, was indicted in april 1983 and convicted in 1984 of violating the 1978 ethics in government act by failing to report $333,978 in loans and other transactions on his financial disclosure forms. the house voted to reprimand him in july 1984. hansen was freed in october 1987 after serving nearly one year in prison
last dec. 18, the house voted 324-68 to reprimand rep. austin murphy, d-pa., for hiring a no-show employee, misusing congressional resources and twice having someone else cast votes for him
the house ethics committee also decided last december that former rep. william h. boner, d-tenn., violated house rules by using his campaign to obtain personal ownership rights of equipment, a building, a car and other items worth more than $200,000. but the committee said it ``lost jurisdiction'' when boner resigned last october to become mayor of nashville
the justice department last march dropped a grand jury probe of boner's finances
the house ethics committee unanimously cleared rep. fernand j. st germain, d-r.i., last april of allegations of financial wrong-doing, and rep. mary rose oakar, d-ohio, advoided disciplinary action after she reimbursed the treasury $45,000 paid to an aide who had moved from washington to new york
the ethics panel is investigating allegations that rep. charles rose, d-n.c., converted more than $63,000 in campaign money to personal use, and that fofo i.f. sunia, american samoa's non-voting delegate, had ``ghost'' employees on his house payroll
rep. harold e. ford, d-tenn., was indicted last april on charges of bank, mail and tax fraud. no trial date has been set
then-rep. claude ``buddy'' leach, d-la., was indicted in july 1979 on charges of buying votes in the 1978 elections and violating federal campain finance laws. he was acquitted of some vote-buying counts and the others were dropped, and a federal appeals court dismissed the charges of campaign finance law violations
then-rep. joshua eilberg, d-pa., was indicted in october 1978 on federal charges of illegally receiving compensation to help a philadelphia hospital get a $14.5 million federal grant. he pleaded guilty in february 1979 and was sentenced to five years' probation and fined $10,000
then-rep. daniel j. flood, d-pa., was indicted in the fall of 1978 on 13 counts of bribery, conspiracy and perjury. after a mistrial, he resigned from the house in january 1980 for health reasons after the house ethics committee had accused him of 25 rules violations. in february 1980, he pleaded guilty to conspiracy in a plea-bargaining arrangement and was given a year's probation
then-rep. charles c. diggs jr., d-mich., was indicted in march 1978 and convicted in october 1978 on 29 felony counts of illegally diverting employees' salaries to his personal use. censured by the house in 1979, diggs resigned from congress in 1980 and served seven months of a three-year prison sentence
about two dozen members of the house have been censured for misconduct, including two for sexual misconduct in 1983: daniel b. crane, r-ill., and gerry e. studds, d-mass
then-sen. thomas dodd, d-conn., was censured in 1967 for paying personal bills with campaign funds. his son, christopher, is now a senator
