it was the second fatal shooting by dallas police within 30 hours and the third this year. two officers were killed last month in separate shootings
the chase, which began when officers noticed that a car's license plates were covered with cloth, ended on the southern methodist university campus, the scene a few hours earlier of a debate among democratic presidential candidates, police said
the man, identified as thomas holloway, 34, of dallas, was pronounced dead at parkland memorial hospital, said bill white of the dallas county medical examiner's office
during the chase, police sgt. r.d. houston said, the officers were told that the driver may have committed one or two armed robberies involving a man with a knife. houston declined to identify the officers
when the car was stopped, the man got out and cut one officer on the hand, police said. the officer fired once, striking the man, police said. the officer's partner then opened fire when the man allegedly threatened him with the knife
at least five shots were fired, police said
on wednesday night, a man who pointed a loaded pistol at an officer was shot dead by the officer's partner
police chief billy prince ordered two-officer patrols after two officers were shot to death within nine days last month
a transient was killed by police jan. 23 after he shot and killed officer john chase in a downtown parking lot. in that incident, officers said some bystanders had urged the transient to shoot the officer
on jan. 14, off-duty police cpl. james joe was killed in a shootout with two burglary suspects in an apartment complex parking lot
south korea said today it plans to lower import tariffs between 2 percent and 20 percent on cars and more than 400 other products next month
the ministry of finance said the decision was part of efforts to help curb inflation and reduce the country's trade surplus
a year ago, the united states formally asked south korea to cut tariffs and dismantle other import barriers for 982 items as a way to correct the trade imbalance between the two countries. as a result, south korea slashed import tariffs between 5 percent and 20 percent on 266 items
under the latest action, tariff rates for passenger cars will go down from the current 50 percent to 30 percent
some of the other 435 tariff cuts include: pianos, to 15 percent from 20 percent; color tv sets to 15 percent from 30 percent; computers, to 15 percent from 20 percent; film to 15 percent from 20 percent; cosmetics, to 25 percent from 30 percent; tiles, to 10 from 20 percent; and wheat and corn to 5 percent from 10 percent
plo leader yasser arafat made his debut before the u.n. human rights commission today and likened israeli practices in the occupied territories to the nazi extermination campaign
arafat also called for the formation of an ``international force'' to protect palestinian residents
the united states, he said, was encouraging israel to ``carry on with aggression and crimes'' by giving the jewish state ``unlimited support.''
the u.s. delegation left the crowded conference hall before arafat began to speak from the dais
a member of the u.s. delegation, marshall breger, declined to call it a walkout, saying only: ``we are not present.''
the seat of the israeli delegate, who has observer status in the 43-nation commission, remained empty. the delegate, ambassador pinhas eliav, said in a press statement that arafat's presence at the commission ``makes a mockery of everything that body stands for.''
in his speech, arafat said the israeli methods of dealing with the recent arab unrest in gaza and the west bank were ``operations of collective extermination''
he said israel was carrying out ``heinous massacres and crimes'' and was ``repeating today the same crimes committed against humanity at the hands of the fascists and the nazis.''
arafat said more than 120 palestinians had been killed in the recent waves of unrests and more than 3,000 wounded. in addition, he charged, 7,000 others were held in ``six new concentration camps'' set up by the israeli authorities
u.n. officials say israeli gunfire has killed at least 55 arabs in the west bank and gaza strip since protests began dec. 8. israel seized the territories during the 1967 middle east war
arafat charged that arms used by israel in quelling the unrest included ``internationally prohibited gases.'' he said he was calling on the world to ``guarantee international protection for our people'' against a ``terrorist and racist enemy who is indifferent to international law.''
such protection could be assured, he said, through the formation of an international force to enable the establishment of an independent palestinian state ``with jerusalem as its capital.''
when asked at a press conference to clarify his call for an international force, he said no new forces would be needed because u.n. peacekeeping troops were already in the area
arafat reacted heatedly when another questioner asked him whether he was hurting the situation by comparing israeli practices to the extermination of 6 million jews by the nazis
have you been commissioned by israel to ask the question?'' he countered
arafat said the u.s. threat to close the palestine liberation organization mission to the united nations in new york was a ``threat against any other state that may have views divergent from those of the united states.''
he said a closure would be a violation of international law. as a last resort the case should be taken to the international court of justice, he said
here are highlights of pope john paul ii's social encyclical released by the vatican friday:
_ problems caused by the east and west:
each of the two blocs harbors in its own way a tendency toward imperialism ... or toward forms of neo-colonialism. ... conflicts ... between east and west (are) an important cause of the retardation or stagnation of the south.''
_ reforms of international economic and financial systems:
the world monetary and financial system is marked by an excessive fluctuation or exchange rates and interest rates, to the detriment of the balance of payments and the debt situation of the poorer countries.''
_ the church's role:
the church's social doctrine is not a `third way' between liberal capitalism and marxist collectivism, nor even a possible alternative to other solutions less radically opposed to one another.''
_ church property:
faced by cases of need, one cannot ignore (necessities) in favor of superfluous church ornaments and costly furnishings for divine worship; on the contrary, it could be obligatory to sell these goods in order to provide food, drink, clothing and shelter for those who lack these things.''
_ dangers of totalitarianism:
no social group, for example a political party, has the right to upsurp the role of sole leader, since this brings about the destruction of the true subjectivity of society and of the individual citizens.''
central bank officials said today the $8 million stolen from a u.s. currency shipment to the bank was insured, and its loss won't hurt the country
the money, stolen in brazil on feb. 4, was part of $52 million the united states had sent to help argentina pay foreign bonds. argentina is the developing world's third largest debtor after brazil and mexico
thirteen sacks stuffed with $4 million dollars cash each were en route from kennedy international airport in new york to buenos aires on brazil's carrier varig when the flight made a stop in rio de janeiro, brazil
police say two of the sacks were stolen during the stopover, but that the remaining $44 million arrived without problem at buenos aires' airport
the cash was being shipped by the federal reserve bank in new york
a 15-year-old accused of fatally shooting a high school official and wounding two teachers has been moved to a medical unit because a psychologist termed him a suicide risk
in my opinion, at this time, jason harless presents an increased suicidal risk. i am recommending that the necessary protective measures be taken,'' psychologist robert clapp wrote in a report
juvenile court administrative judge jack page ordered harless moved thursday from a juvenile detention center to the medical wing of the pinellas county jail
clapp said harless became more despondent after learning of the wednesday death of richard allen, 53, assistant principal at pinellas park high school
allen was shot in the head when he and two teachers tried to break up a fight between harless and another youth in the high school's packed cafeteria on feb. 11
the teachers also were shot; both have been treated and released from a hospital
harless has been charged with five counts of attempted first-degree murder, for the shootings in the lunchroom and shots fired at two policemen. his friend jason mccoy was charged with three counts of the same offense although he is not accused of firing a weapon
a grand jury that meets march 1 will consider charges against the youths. if indicted, they will be tried as adults, said richard mensh, pinellas-pasco chief assistant state attorney
four infants in need of livers are being evaluated for transplant after a baby kept on life-support systems as a potential organ donor was declared brain dead, a hospital official said
the brain-dead diagnosis for the 7-pound infant born tuesday, was confirmed thursday after examinations by three neurologists, said joyce peabody, chief of neonatology at loma linda university medical center
the boy's heart was beating, and a respirator supplied oxygen to his organs, but he had no higher brain activity, she said. the child was born tuesday
the boy's condition, known as anencephaly, kills most babies within days after birth. their healthy organs can be transplanted if organ damage is prevented by maintaining the infants on life-support
the southern california organ procurement center would choose organ recipients, ms. peabody said. liver and heart were the most likely organs for transplant, she said, adding that loma linda officials know of one baby in need of a heart but not of the right blood type
the names of the baby's parents were withheld to protect their privacy, but ms. peabody said the mother had expressed satisfaction with the procedure
the national right to life committee, which accused loma linda of going beyond prevailing medical ethics, denounced the procedure. protesters said doctors at the hospital hadn't done enough to ensure that organs weren't removed from live children
however, ms. peabody said, the case may have answered several medical and ethical questions about the practice of maintaining anencephalics in order to use their organs
it demonstrated that the baby didn't suffer discomfort or distress, she said. it also indicated organs can be kept in condition suitable for transplant, and that the life-support apparatus didn't artificially prolong the time until the baby suffered brain death
one of the hospital's 13 heart transplant patients under age 4 received the heart of an anencephalic baby earlier this year from a donor child in canada. billions.</head>
the $1.3 billion that president reagan proposes to spend fighting aids next year _ his ``highest public health priority'' _ would be by far the largest percentage increase in any major federal program
but the 38 percent boost over current aids spending of $951 million approved by congress would pale if compared with the $534 million that the president initially requested last year
by that measure, reagan could just as well have boasted that he was more than doubling his aids request. but that would have drawn attention to the reality that congress has consistently voted much more for aids research and education than the president has requested
for fiscal 1987, for example, reagan sought $213 million and congress appropriated $502 million
with the white house calling for a drastic increase in aids spending next year, congress is considered unlikely to approve any significant increase on top of that, as it has in the past
one reason is that the overall fiscal 1989 budget plan was written in consultation with congressional leaders in deficit-reduction negotiations prompted by the october stock market crash
another is that both administration and congressional leaders have said the proposed budget is calculated in part to avoid a knock-down fight in an election year
but a high-ranking administration official said reagan gave a hint of his plans for a dramatic increase in aids spending during a meeting last summer when the president decided to appoint a white house commission on the deadly disease
this official, who discussed the budget only on condition that he not be identified, quoted reagan as saying, ``i want it (the commission) to have whatever money it needs.''
the official, who helps referee spending fights among federal health agencies, remembered thinking at that moment: ``there goes my budget.''
the 38 percent rise in aids spending compares with a net proposed increase of 5.8 percent for the 250 programs administered by the department of health and human services under the fiscal 1989 budget plan that reagan sent thursday to congress
nearly 95 percent of the huge department's proposed $396.8 billion budget, which represents about one-third of all federal spending, goes for so-called entitlement programs such as social security, medicare and medicaid
the administration has relatively little control over entitlement programs because eligiblity criteria are fixed by law
social security spending alone is expected to grow by $14 billion, or 6.4 percent, to $233.8 billion during the new fiscal year which starts oct. 1
medicaid, the state-federal health program for poor people, will cost the federal government $32.7 billion in 1989, up 7 percent from the current $30.7 billion. much of the increase is attributed to heavier spending on aids patients, from $375 million to $600 million
medicare spending for 33 million retirees and disabled workers is projected to rise to $84 billion from $78.9 billion this year
the most controversial part of the hhs spending plan is likely to be reagan's request for $1.2 billion in medicare cuts which he says are required to meet an agreed target of a $3.5 million reduction
if projections of overall medicare spending by the congressional budget office are correct, the $3.5 billion reduction target already has been met. if the administration is correct, an additional $1.2 billion in cuts would be needed
of that $1.2 billion, the administration proposes to cover about $1 billion by reducing payments to large teaching hospitals that help them with educational costs
hhs chief of staff thomas burke said a recent internal study showed that the medicare profits of teaching hospitals are 2{ times higher than those of non-teaching hospitals
it would seem these hospitals are going to be able to absorb this reduction,'' burke said
a computerized robot named robodoc may one day help surgeons perform hip replacements in an operating room of the future, university of california researchers say
orthopedic surgeon william l. bargar and veterinarian howard paul said robodoc's ability to drill and measure precisely will prove valuable in assisting physicians in hip replacements and other types of surgery
bargar and paul showed off the machine thursday at a news conference at the university's davis campus, about 15 miles west of sacramento, where bargar is an assistant clinical professor and paul is an assistant research veterinarian
the robot, which was billed as the first of its kind and is at least five years from use in hospitals, looks and sounds in its current phase much like a giant dentist's drill
bargar and paul developed the computerized mechanical arm to drill deep holes down through thighbones during hip replacement surgery so they could slip artificial hip joints inside
currently, surgeons must use a mallet and metal rasp to bore holes under the socket, at the risk of cracking the leg bone and getting a poor fit
in 1985, bargar began testing custom-made hip implants that eliminate the need to take several standard sizes of artificial hip joints into the operating room and fit the patient during surgery
so we thought, if a machine can make a prosthesis accurately, why can't a machine make the same envelope so that (the joint) will just press in,'' said paul, who replaces hips in one to two arthritic dogs every week
the better the fit, the surgeons reasoned, the easier the bone will grow onto the artificial joint and the longer it will last
traditional hip surgery is fine for older, sedentary people, but younger, active or overweight patients face a 40 percent risk of having their implants loosen within five years, bargar said
about 120,000 people undergo hip replacement surgery every year
in early laboratory tests, bargar said, the robot drilled with accuracy up to seven-thousands of an inch, nearly 60 times as accurate as the hand-held rasp and mallet
such accuracy could be a boon to other surgery, such as removal of brain tumors or implanting of teeth in the jaw, he said
we hope it's going to be picked up by oral surgery, opthmology, neurosurgery,'' said bargar. ``each of these disciplines has some procedure where the accuracy they need is better than what they can achieve.''
the researchers stressed that the robot is intended to assist human surgeons, not replace them
i initially didn't even want to use the word `robot,' because i was afraid it would scare people,'' bargar said. policy</head>
a formerly homeless woman who challenged new york city's policy of forcibly hospitalizing mentally ill street people told a harvard law school audience the policy was more humiliating than helpful
i will never, never, ever forget what happened to me and what mayor (edward) koch's program did to me,'' joyce brown, 40, said at a harvard law forum
ms. brown, who also has called herself billie boggs, called for more affordable housing and criticized government programs for the homeless, particularly new york's project help
ms. brown was the first homeless person picked up under koch's program to remove the mentally ill from the streets for treatment
a former secretary in new jersey, ms. brown lived for months on a sidewalk in manhattan until oct. 28, when city workers took her to bellevue hospital, where she was kept in a locked psychiatric ward
she protested in court, and on jan. 19 she was released after a judge ruled she could not be treated with drugs against her will
ms. brown said programs like project help only exacerbate the problem of the homeless
mayor koch wants to pick you up, humiliate you, degrade you and embarrass you by taking you to the hospital and forcing you to take medication,'' she said
since being released from the hospital, ms. brown has moved to a new york hotel for formerly homeless women where she receives meals and social services and says she is looking for work. she was accompanied to harvard by her two lawyers from the new york civil liberties union
she urged governments to build more housing for people with low and moderate incomes and described her experiences in shelters for the homeless as ``not good at all.''
there are murders, theft, rapings,'' she said. ``it is a very dangerous place to live.''
before her speech, she told the new york post she wishes she had a family
if i could pick anything i want to be right now, i'd be married with children,'' she said
armed with flashlights, walkie-talkies, and in some cases, police escorts, more than 100 volunteers took to the streets and alleys of boston today to count the number of homeless
the 117 census-takers were instructed to look behind buildings and trash bins, in doorways and all-night movies
we just about walked every street in the city,'' said allan stern, the city's director of data processing, who will tally the findings
the homeless were recorded by gender and whether adult or child, but names were not taken. totals, which will include the number of homeless who spent the night in shelters and detoxification units, were to be calculated during the day, with a final analysis expected in about one week, said stern
the city's first census, conducted last year, found about 2,860 homeless, stern said
drinking coffee to help them stay awake, the census-takers gathered before midnight at city hall. temperatures hovered around freezing outside
it's important to be able to speak with authority,'' mayor raymond flynn told the group. ``people rely on the city of boston for these kinds of figures. when we start making statements about the homeless population in america, we can speak about it with actual statistics.''
boston is the only city in the country which takes to the streets to count the homeless, stern said
it shows the concern for the issue to have so many people come out here between the hours of 1 and 3,'' said richard weintraub, 34, director of the 360-bed long island shelter
most of the volunteers were homeless workers or advocates, recruited through word-of-mouth and posters. the boston fire department donated two cars and two drivers, and police escorted some groups
in the boston's south end, a book and sweater scrunched on top of a stove in an alcove built of discarded appliances alerted weintraub's three-person group to signs of occupancy
a quick hop up on the stove and a peek into the makeshift dwelling found two people fast asleep
we still don't get all the homeless. there are people hidden away in buildings we'll just never find,'' weintraub said
the volunteers were told to be inconspicuous and not to disturb the homeless unless they were in need of assistance
at 3 a.m. a man was spotted hobbling on crutches, and the group radioed for a rescue van, which took him to a shelter, weintraub said
weintraub's group finished searching its 30-block area in the south end at 4 a.m., finding 10 men and one woman
if we don't find a lot of people on the street, that's successful,'' he said
the city uses the statistics to help determine the number of beds, resuce vans, food and medical supplies needed to care for the homeless, said ann maquire, executive director of the city's emergency shelter commission, which organized the survey
chrysler corp., under fire for planning to close a plant it acquired in its buyout of american motors, will consider a ``modest, short'' extension of production there, chrysler chairman lee iacocca says
he made the announcement after meeting thursday in washington with gov. tommy g. thompson, who has threatened to have the state sue chrysler
the meeting ``got very heated'' while wisconsin officials gave iacocca their opinion of chrysler's plans to close the factory in kenosha on sept. 30 and throw 5,500 people out of work, thompson said
the state accuses the company of violating a 1987 promise to maintain production for five years in exchange for $5 million in job-training funds
i had some things i wanted to get off my chest,'' the governor said
iacocca said after the meeting he had agreed to requests by rep. les aspin, d-wis., to look elsewhere in the company for work that might be transferred to kenosha when production of omni and horizon models ends there
we don't hold hopes too high but they specifically asked if we could have a modest, short extension,'' iacocca said. ``we're going to look and see if we can seriously do that.''
asked if iacocca meant weeks or months with the term ``modest, short extension,'' the governor said, ``he didn't put it in those kinds of terms.''
while talking to reporters, iacocca mentioned ``a couple months.''
thompson said talks will continue with chrysler in hope of averting a breach-of-contract suit against chrysler
thompson said he hopes iacocca's promise to look for new work for kenosha can prolong operations for more than a month or two but realizes ``it's not going to be five years.''
in a telephone interview from washington, the governor said the meeting ``started out very rocky. it got very heated. at times we thought the meeting was going to break up.''
i reiterated my positions to him about how they treated the state, the city, the county and the union,'' thompson said. ``we are a long way from reaching an agreement (but) it was a positive meeting.''
chrysler denies making a written commitment to maintain production for five years. iacocca says company officials are guilty of nothing more than being ``cockeyed optimists'' in originally planning to keep the plant open that long
when the 86-year-old factory closes, about 1,800 workers would be eligible for pensions, leaving 3,700 facing unemployment. state officials say the unemployment rate in the city of 75,000 could rise past 20 percent
the only defendant in u.s. custody of those named in the drug indictment of panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega pleaded innocent today in federal court
brian alden davidow, 26, a student at florida international university, had turned himself in to authorities last week, four days after being indicted for racketeering and drug trafficking along with noriega and 14 other people
davidow, free on a $500,000 bond, pleaded innocent to two indictments in a brief hearing before u.s. magistrate linnea johnson
he could face up to 60 years in prison and fines of $750,000 if convicted of conspiring with noriega to smuggle drugs from panama to the united states for the colombia-based medellin cartel, which supplies up to 80 percent of this country's cociane imports
according to prosecutors, davidow is a miami-based cocaine distributor who worked with cesar rodriguez, ruben diario paredes jimenez and others. davidow allegedly met with noriega and others in panama to arrange transportation of cocaine to florida, the indictment says
the defendant also entered an innocent plea in a second indictment accusing him of conspiracy and distribution of cocaine in 1983 and 1984
federal guidelines intended to bring consistency to sentencing for those who commit federal crimes have been declared invalid by two u.s. district judges
judge rudi brewster concurred thursday with arguments that the commission that issued the guidelines violated separation of powers among government branches
brewster found that the u.s. sentencing commission was unconstitutional because it was placed under the wing of the judicial branch of government, when the power of that branch is limited to resolution of cases, not rule-making
shortly after brewster filed his opinion, judge john rhoades issued a brief order adopting brewster's findings
the rulings came one day after brewster, rhoades and six other federal judges for the southern district of california heard arguments on the valididity of the commission created by the sentencing reform act of 1984
the act was intended to bring consistency to sentencings and affects those who commit federal crimes after nov. 1, 1987
challenges to the new rules have been filed throughout the country, but the san diego hearing was the first to reach trial
i think it's a well-written opinion and i think it will be influential,'' said judy clarke, executive director of federal defenders of san diego, which argued against the federal sentencing mandates
it tells district court judges they are not alone in concluding that an act of congress is unconstitutional, she said
assistant u.s. attorney roger haines jr. said he was disappointed with the rulings, but predicted that when other judges rule, the ``government's position will be vindicated.''
defense and government attorneys have agreed that constitutional issues ultimately must be decided by the u.s. supreme court. haines said thursday that the justice department is investigating the best strategy for appeal
in the meantime, different judges may use different sentencing standards. haines said it will cause no practical problems, but clarke contends there will be ``chaos'' in the courts
the san diego judges, who normally hear pretrial motions individually, joined in a time-saving maneuver to hear arguments raised in eight cases by 16 defendants awaiting trial on offenses ranging from drug to immigration violations. rulings from the other judges are pending
the justice department and the commission sought to preserve the new rules, but relied on different arguments
attorney kenneth geller, representing the commission, said the guidelines brought order to the inconsistent sentencing system and defended the commission as independent of the executive branch
douglass letter, the justice department's appellate litigation counsel, conceded that there could be constitutional problems because of the commission's assignment to the judicial branch
he said it should have been placed in the executive branch, under which it could legally execute laws
secretary of state george p. shultz ``most likely'' will visit syria when he goes to the middle east next week to weigh prospects for an arab-israeli negotiations, a u.s. official said today
shultz' purpose would be to discuss the situation with president hafez assad, whose support for any long-term sattlement of the arab-israeli dispute is considered essential by experts in the state department's near east bureau
a stop in damascus would be a major prestige boost to syria and mark an improvement in its u.s. relations. the country is one of six listed by the state department as a supporter of terrorism. in november 1986, president reagan imposed sanctions against syria
among the punitive measures was a ban on high-level meetings with syrians. but shultz sent richard w. murphy, the head of the near east bureau, to damascus two weeks ago to confer with assad
the u.s. official, who demanded anonymity, said shultz was ``most likely'' to schedule a stop in syria on his trip to the middle east beginning next thursday
another u.s. official, who demanded anonymity, said restrictions on visas for syrians to visit the united states are likely to be lifted
ambassador william eagleton was sent back to his post in damascus last september, after a year's absence, and u.n. ambassador vernon a. walters also visited the country
shultz's other stops will be egypt, jordan, israel and probably saudi arabia. he is trying to set up negotiations between israel and a mixed delegation of jordanians and palestinians to deal especially with the troubled west bank and gaza
the immediate aim is some form of self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinian arabs who have lived under israeli control since egypt and jordan lost the territories in the 1967 six-day war
the long-range goal is to hold a second stage of talks _ possibly in the format of an international peace conference _ by the end of the year to consider an overall settlement
shultz plans to be in the middle east until march 2 when the north atlantic treaty organization holds a summit meeting in brussels. president reagan will attend
he is making a separate trip to the soviet union, starting out today for helsinki, finland. shultz will be in moscow for talks sunday and monday, report to the nato countries in brussels on tuesday and return home for a brief rest before heading for the middle east
an influential communist party weekly criticized the official anti-semitic campaign in 1968 that led to the flight of most of the country's surviving jewish population
the article in the feb. 20 issue of the weekly polityka, seen today, was the first in an official publication to offer a detailed account reappraising the 1968 events and referring specifically to an ``anti-semitic'' campaign
its publication comes before the 20th anniversary of march 1968 student protests against censorship, which sparked what authorities then called an ``anti-zionist'' campaign that led to the dismissal of thousands of jews from official posts
government spokesman jerzy urban on tuesday promised a ``detailed discussion'' of the 1968 crisis in official publications. the government condemns ``any manifestations of anti-semitism, both in the past and at present,'' he said
a party source close to polish leader gen. wojciech jaruzelski said the polityka article was the first in a series of reappraisals that will appear in the press, radio and television, including a major commentary planned for the party's official newspaper trybuna ludu
this is the time of perestroika (reconstruction) and it is time to liquidate the mistakes, the black points on the moral side,'' said the source, requesting anonymity
perestroika describes the social and economic reforms promoted by soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev. the soviet union has been re-evaluating its history in a more critical light
we will take a clear position against anti-semitism,'' the source said. ``we want to close this chapter, which was a very unhappy chapter in our history.''
in a front-page introduction to a chronology of events connected with 1968, two polityka staff members, wieslaw wladyka and zbyslaw rykowski, wrote that ``march (1968) has been an embarrassing issue for 20 years.''
the legacy of march remains: the shame of the anti-semitic fuss, the reform of socialism buried for years, the intelligentsia left at odds with the working class, human damage.''
they wrote that the crisis was triggered by the failure of then-communist party leader wladyslaw gomulka to make basic political and economic reforms, partially under the influence of conservative soviet leader leonid brezhnev. as the country stagnated, gomulka reacted with repressive measures against reformers and dissident intellectuals
they said the ``anti-semitic syndrome in political thinking'' was part of a power struggle within the party leadership aimed at unseating gomulka. his opponents tried to appeal for popular support with nationalist slogans
the anti-semitic campaign was ignited after the 1967 arab-israeli war when some polish officials and army officers of jewish origin were accused of celebrating the israeli victory over the soviet-backed arab armies
but the campaign did not pick up momentum until after the march 1968 student riots, which authorities blamed on ``zionist traitors.'' about 9,000 jews were dismissed from posts in the party, party, government, army and other institutions
the campaign led to the emigration of most of the 30,000 jews living in poland. before the nazi holocaust of world war ii, poland was home to about 3.5 million jews, or 10 percent of the population
polityka said the precise number of emigres is unknown, but cited various estimates saying that 12,000 to 20,000 jews left poland in 1967-69
prime minister anibal cavaco silva likely will call for a review of a treaty allowing the united states to use a mid-atlantic air base if washington refuses a large increase in aid, a newspaper said today
cavaco silva planned to visit to washington next week for talks with u.s. leaders. the talks are expected to center on a 1983 bilateral accord that gives the united states use of the lajes air base in the azores islands
today, the left-of-center lisbon weekly o jornal reported sources close to the government expect ``the prime minister will officially call for a formal review of the (lajes) agreement if washington refuses a substantial increase in aid'' during his u.s. trip
two weeks ago, u.s. defense secretary frank carlucci paid a one-day visit to lisbon to discuss portuguese complaints over recent drops in u.s. assistance
carlucci and portuguese defense minister eurico de melo announced after intensive meetings in the portuguese capital feb. 3 that both sides had agreed to form a joint task force to study alternative forms of u.s. aid to portugal
congressional cuts dropped washington's military and economic assistance totals to portugal from $208 million in 1985 to $117 million for fiscal 1987
carlucci's visit to lisbon followed months of public complaints by cavaco silva and other portuguese leaders that the united states had failed to live up to its pledge in the 1983 base accord to provide increasing amounts of aid
the u.s. state department announced thursday the administration would seek $163 million in aid to portugal for fiscal 1988, which begins oct. 1
the united states first received base rights at lajes in 1951, and the u.s. presence at the portuguese-run base on the azores' terceira island has been extended in a series of subsequent accords
the latest extension agreement for use of the refuelling depot and submarine reconnaissance facilities at lajes was signed in december 1983, and expires feb. 4, 1991
in a major address thursday night, foreign minister joao de deus pinheiro reiterated portugal's strategic role in the atlantic alliance but signalled increasing concern in lisbon over the cuts in aid
