bryan tucker, who had burns over 10 percent of his body, was reported in good condition friday at memorial hospital
the members of motley crue are very sorry to learn that a young fan was injured trying to copy the `human torch' stunt as seen on the live wire video taped in 1982,'' said the statement released thursday by management firm mcghee entertainment inc. in los angeles
various of motley crue's show stunts require special equipment, clothing and other materials ... and should not be attempted at home. fire stunts are especially dangerous,'' the statement said
bryan's mother, wendy tucker, said he was in great pain but that motley crue was not to blame for her son's experiment at their home wednesday
in my day, my mom would not let me watch superman, because he jumped out of buildings,'' she said. ``it's just a different time. if you think, some of these cartoons are really rough. it didn't start with rock videos.''
tucker, who takes electric guitar lessons and wears an earring in the shape of a cross, is known around apollo middle school as a ``headbanger,'' or heavy-metal rock fan, friends said
the boy poured rubbing alcohol on his jeans and torched them. he put the flames out in a filled bathtub
a man sought in five bank robberies in the san diego area, including three committed in one day, was tracked to an apartment where he barricaded himself before apparently committing suicide, the fbi said
the man, identified as william patrick mcgrovern, 43, was found dead inside his san diego apartment thursday night, said fbi special agent james bolenbach
apparently he had shot himself shortly after barricading himself in the apartment,'' bolenbach said. no hostages were taken, and no one else was injured
fbi agents and police officers from san diego and el cajon staked out mcgrovern's apartment thursday after tracing a license plate number on a getaway car used in one of three robberies that same day
a bank in el cajon and two in san diego were robbed within a 1{-hour period and police and fbi investigators found that the same person was responsible, bolenbach said
when the officers attempted to arrest mcgrovern, he fired a shot and fled into his apartment
throughout the afternoon, further attempts to contact him and negotiate received no response,'' bolenbach said
officers heard a single shot at about 5 p.m., and when they entered about three hours later they found mcgrovern dead of a gunshot wound, he said. several weapons, ammunition and an unknown amount of money were found in the apartment
mcgrovern also is suspected of robbing a bank in escondido and one in poway last month, bolenbach said
it is not believed that mcgrovern had any accomplices, he said. the fbi did not disclose the amount of money taken in the five robberies
a traditional keepsake certificate that mclean county has been giving to newlyweds is pitting clergy against one another in a debate over the separation of church and state
the controversy also has sparked an angry response from the public, including threatening phone calls to public officials, ministers and others involved
at issue is the religious nature of the elaborate certificates, which declare a couple united in ``holy matrimony, ordained by god.'' they also bear a bible passage from the book of matthew
i think it's inappropriate for the county to be distributing religious materials,'' said david robins, minister at the unitarian church of bloomington
robins says the keepsake is a christian document and that its distribution by the county displays a lack of sensitivity toward religious minorities who don't share the same beliefs
he said the county should leave such religious keepsakes to the churches rather than involve government in the issue
i realize i'm a religious minority in a christian society and i'm sorry if this curtails the pleasure of the majority of the people in the county,'' robins said. ``but i just think this is an inappropriate activity for the county to be involved in.''
robins enlisted the support of rabbi clifford librach of the moses montefiore temple in bloomington, and together they complained to the county
mclean county clerk jeanette barrett decided to end distribution of the keepsakes on the advice of eric ruud, assistant state's attorney
however, that brought about 50 angry phone calls to the clerk's office, as well as several ``vicious, venomous'' calls to ruud and robins, librach said
we've decided to give them their choice,'' mrs. barrett said. ``i'm going to issue one without all the religious references. if they don't want either one, they don't have to take one
i think people should have a choice. they don't think the county should be in the religion business. but i don't think we've done anything wrong.''
robins and librach think mrs. barrett is missing the point. they don't think it's proper for the county to hand out any religious certificates, whether christian, unitarian or jewish
if the majority of the people in mclean county were jewish, i'd be offended if the county issued a jewish-style keepsake,'' librach said
the rev. ron r. lee, pastor of st. john's lutheran church, said his church strongly supports the separation of church and state government
freedom of religion means each group is allowed to pursue its own beliefs in a free and open environment,'' lee said. ``the government does not promote religion. any document the government produces should be free of religious statements.''
ralph e. wingate, pastor at the calvary baptist church, disagreed with robins, librach and lee
the whole thing is ridiculous to me,'' wingate said. ``they might have an argument about espousing the bible, but i think it's a non-issue.''
librach said the keepsakes go further than a simple ``in god we trust'' as appears on u.s. currency
these certificates contain excerpts from the gospel of matthew and clearly are christian documents,'' he said. ``it's a violation of the constitution. we may have to look to the courts, where i have no doubt as to what the decision will be.''
rotten row, which is said to be the world's oldest urban horseriding path, may get back its bollards and railings 47 years after they were ripped out for the world war ii effort
the rotten row tercentenary committee, set up to restore the bridle path to its former glory by its 300th anniversary in 1991, launched an appeal friday for $260,000 to finance the fence
the mile-long sandy path through hyde park in central london will be lined on each side with 1,000 cast-iron bollards linked by metal railings
major donors will have their names inscribed on the black, 3-foot high bollards, said committee chairman neil mitchell
built by king william iii and originally called the king's road, the path stretched four miles from westminster to kensington palace and was the first continuously lighted thoroughfare in britain
scholars have never agreed on the origin of the name rotten row
some trace it to ``route du roi,'' french for king's road. others say it comes from ``rotteran,'' a german verb meaning to muster, because it was used for military parades
today it is open to any horserider free of charge and is part of a network of bridle paths used as a basis for designing central park in new york
mitchell said he has invited the claremont riding academy in new york to join in the tercentenary ceremonies
the u.s. supreme court on jan. 11 let stand a federal judge's decision freeing carter, who had served 19 years of a life term. the judge found carter's conviction was tainted by racism and by prosecutors witholding information from the defense
the ruling left to the passaic county prosecutor's office the decision on whether to seek another trial for carter and artis, whose convictions were first overturned by the new jersey supreme court before a 1976 retrial
defense attorneys had considered a third trial unlikely because the eyewitness testimony had been so discredited during appeals
goceljak made the decision on a third trial in consultation with the state's director of criminal justice, donald r. belsole
belsole had said the decision would be based in part on the state of 22-year-old evidence and ``the impact of another trial on society.''
