james meredith, who broke the color barrier at the university of mississippi 26 years ago, said education remains the best vehicle to break the cycle of poverty and oppression
meredith, 54, was the first black student to attend the university of mississippi in 1962. violence broke out on the ole miss campus, and president john f. kennedy called in federal troops to maintain order
meredith graduated from the university and went on to earn a law degree at columbia university
in a speech to air force academy cadets thursday, meredith said american blacks need to take more advantage of their citzenship rights to improve their economic and political opportunities. by seeking a state-funded education at ole miss, meredith said he chose to challenge white supremacy
former vice presidential candidate geraldine ferraro says life at her fire island summer home is no day at the beach _ in fact, she can't even go to the beach because she's so recognizable
that's why ms. ferraro and husband john zaccaro are asking for a variance to build a swimming pool on their property and provide them with some privacy
because of the burden of celebrity, we are unable to take advantage of the beach except for early morning or late evening,'' ms. ferraro told an unusual manhattan meeting of the saltaire village board of zoning appeals on thursday
under village laws, an owner must have at least 10 lots to build a pool; the former congresswoman and her husband own nine. the board has reserved decision on the request, but it was not met enthusiastically by some members
when we give variances it's usually because of hardship, and i don't see the hardship here,'' said board member hilliard farr, a summer softball teammate of zaccaro and his wife
ms. ferraro ran unsuccessfully in 1984 on the democratic ticket headed by walter mondale
george bush must tone down his whining, paul simon should aim for a less professorial sound and albert gore jr. could help his campaign with a little humor, says a university of pittsburgh rhetoric expert
ted windt, professor and editor of two books on presidential rhetoric, rated the candidates' speaking style in this campaign's early grading period, giving democratic hopeful jesse jackson the best mark, a-minus, and former colorado sen. gary hart an f
regardless of whether people vote for him or not, they respect and respond to his speaking,'' windt said of jackson. ``i do think rhyming periodic sentences will grow thin after a while. he should beef his theme up with some less soaring statements.''
hart, meanwhile, fails in windt's grade book
he's had four years to answer the question, `where's the beef?' he's still unable to do it,'' the professor said. ``although he talks new ideas, he's talking about the past. in debates he cannot reply on the sensitive ... issue without attacking the media.''
on the republican side, bush ``frequently sounds like he's whining,'' according to windt, who gave the vice president a c-minus. however, in new hampshire, bush changed his style which enabled him to capture the primary
in new hampshire he began to speak rather than whine. he recognizes he's going to have to fight for the nomination with dole, and has begun to mix it up,'' windt said
the rhetoric expert gave bush's chief rival, kansas sen. bob dole, a b for the theme ``i'm one of you,'' which played so well in the iowa caucuses. the slogan, however, may prove short-sighted, he said
dole also ``has an incisive sense of humor that some think is mean,'' windt said
former television evangelist pat robertson gets a b as ``a natural tv performer.''
he's attempting to soften the hard image of a self-righteous evangelical who's out to vanquish evil. in softening his image, he has not yet developed a clear-cut image or person,'' windt said
new york rep. jack kemp, although hard to grade, gets a c plus for being ``lackluster in debates,'' windt said
among the other democrats, simon gets a c for being ``professorial, more a lecturer than a speaker,'' windt said of the illinois senator. ``he should remember that a campaign is not a required course for students, but an elective that voters can choose to attend or skip,'' he said
gore gets an incomplete for campaigning so little in iowa and new hampshire, windt said. ``he doesn't project any sense of humor'' and ``still looks like he's running for class president of a very expensive, preppy school,'' windt said
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis gets a c for coming across as a ``technocrat and a manager without human warmth,'' said windt
the university of california faces a growing admissions crisis that threatens to set black, white, hispanic and asian students competing against one another for admission, officials said
three years into the system's 15-year growth plan, enrollment has already reached levels predicted for 1995, and the university could be forced for the first time to turn away qualified high school graduates, the board of regents said at a special meeting thursday
the university has 140,000 undergraduates on its nine campuses
part of the reason for the soaring applications is the university's success at recruiting minority applicants, said university president david p. gardner
there needs to be very strong leadership by the regents and the administration to reduce the growing tension between affirmative action and ... the concerns among white students over their declining enrollment at the university,'' said henry der, a member of the asian-american task force on university admissions
der, one of a panel of educational leaders that addressed the regents, has accused the berkeley campus of setting informal quotas denying admission to asian students, who have been gaining entrance in greater and greater numbers during the past decade
he predicted such policies will lead to ``political and social wars'' if uniform admission standards are not adopted throughout the system
we have to ask whether this university is ready to let asian and white students compete on a color-blind basis,'' said der
the regents discussed raising entrance requirements but that could further widen the gap between the percentages of black and hispanic students enrolled compared to whites, they said
five percent of hispanic high school graduates and about 4 percent of blacks meet entrance requirements consisting of a combination of high school courses, a 3.3 grade point average and scholastic aptitude test results. this compares to 15 percent of white students and 32 percent of asian graduates, according to figures compiled by the california post secondary education commission. figures; picks up 5th graf pvs, `ford's 1987...'; subs 12th graf, `for workers...' with 2 grafs details of announcement.</note>
ford motor co. earned the highest profits in automotive history in 1987, out-earning general motors corp. for the second straight year and generating record profit-sharing checks for its workers
ford workers will receive an average of more than $3,700 each in profit-sharing checks as a result of ford's 1987 earnings of $4.6 billion, the company said today
the no. 2 automaker's fourth-quarter earnings rose 19 percent from a year ago and full-year earnings jumped 41 percent over 1986, but some analysts said they had expected ford to earn even more
for the final three months of 1987, ford said it earned $932 million, or $1.87 a share, on revenue of $18.8 billion, up from $785 million, or $1.50 a share, on revenue of $16.26 billion in the final quarter of 1986
for the year, ford earned $9.05 a share, on revenue of $71.6 billion, up from 1986 earnings of $3.29 billion, or $6.16 a share, on revenue of $62.7 billion
ford's 1987 earnings topped the previous record of $4.5 billion set by gm in 1984. earnings for the fourth quarter were a ford record, ford said
per-share earnings in 1986 were readjusted to reflect a two-for-one stock split on dec. 10, 1987
gm's 1987 earnings rose to $3.6 billion, or $10.06 per common share. at no. 3 chrysler corp., earnings fell slightly to $1.3 billion, or $5.90 a share
market expectations that ford's earnings would be somewhat higher for the year and quarter depressed the price of ford stock after the announcement, said douglas laughlin, industry analyst with dean witter reynolds inc. in new york. ford's stock closed down $2.25 per share at $42.25
the stock's mostly down on a gut reaction to the number but not on any real conclusive detail. it was a very respectable quarter and the year has been excellent,'' laughlin said
thomas o'grady, an analyst with integrated automotive resources inc. of wayne, pa., said the weaker-than-expected fourth quarter may have been caused by sales incentive programs, which were unnecessary a year ago when buyers were flooding showrooms to beat 1988 tax reforms
by the end of 1987, ford's nest egg of cash and marketable securities had grown to nearly $10.1 billion from $8.6 billion a year ago
ford will distribute a record total of $635 million in profit-sharing on march 8 to salaried and hourly workers. ford announced the preliminary figures today to workers at its michigan truck plant in wayne. more than 160,000 workers received an average of $2,100 for 1986
the company's u.s. employees can take pride in their performance as members of the ford team. it is fitting that they will share in the results by receiving their largest profit-sharing checks ever,'' ford chairman donald petersen said
gm workers received no share of 1986 or 1987 profits because the company's u.s. auto earnings were too low
ford's profit-sharing also is based on u.s. earnings, which jumped nearly 40 percent to $3.44 billion in 1987 from $2.46 billion in 1986 due to higher car and truck sales and increased production efficiency, ford said
ford was the only big three automaker to sell more cars and trucks in 1987 than in 1986
ford attributed its performance to improved sales worldwide, strong earnings by subsidiaries and a comfortable relationship with the united auto workers union
early in the fourth quarter, ford signed a three-year, job-protecting uaw pact that was negotiated without a strike and helps the company improve production efficiency and cut costs
the homeless, a group of americans with a major stake in the outcome of this year's election, may find themselves unable to exercise much political muscle at the polls
these cold and hungry people have attracted added attention this year as their growing visibility on city streets has brought them before both voters and those seeking votes
a recent survey by a coalition of national organizations found that most voters believe helping the hungry and homeless should be one of the top priorities of the next administration
but while the poll called on politicians to give some attention to the homeless, the question remains whether the homeless can return the attention on election day
theoretically they could make up a significant bloc
estimates of the number of homeless americans vary widely, from the 360,000 reported in a 1986 economic research study to up to 3 million claimed by some advocacy groups
it's a very difficult number to get at, because it's a difficult population to count,'' said james stimpson of the department of housing and urban development
whatever their number, it's not likely that many will be able to sign up and cast ballots
in general, registration and voting hinges on residence and the rules vary widely from state to state, according to craig donsanto of the justice department
in states such as mississippi, the rules can be very strict, while in some other parts of the country anyone who can show up at the polls may be able to vote, donsanto explained through a department spokesman
in places like new york city, for example, the homeless can use a shelter for an address, while others may even be able to list a grate on a street corner as their usual place of residence, he said
the question for new york homeless was settled by a federal court ruling in 1984, said bill kimberling of the federal election commission
he said the ruling requires the state to allow people to register to vote even if homeless. they must list an address where mail can be sent, he said, but that can be a shelter or some other location where people agree to hold the mail for them
their residence can then be listed as a separate place, wherever they are usually to be found, he added
while that court case established the homeless' right to vote in new york, beth gorey of that city's office of the national coalition for the homeless, said she was unable to estimate how many may have done so
we do take advantage of opportunities to encourage them to register, at meetings and so forth, and we always provide voter registration cards. but we don't know how many have'' registered, she said
tim hager of the coalition's washington office said voting registration efforts also have been undertaken in washington and some other areas, but he had few details
chris sprowal of the philadelphia-based national union of the homeless said that outside of major cities such as new york, chicago, philadelphia and a few others, homeless people generally find themselves barred from voting
for the most part, if they would go in and say, `i stay on the river' or `in a cardboard box' they would be denied the right to vote. they have to lie and give a residence,'' he commented
sprowal said his group is planning a meeting in atlanta to discuss launching a nationwide fight for voting for homeless people
an added problem is the near-homeless, pointed out linda davidoff of the group human serve
many people are doubled up in tight housing markets, living with friends or relatives in violation of leases, she commented. if they register and turn up on voter lists at the address where they are living, the landlord could then evict them, she said, resulting in these people being disenfranchised just like the homeless
despite their reportedly large numbers, at least in major cities, there are ``not a lot of aggressive efforts to organize'' the homeless into voting blocs, said keith summa of the coalition for the homeless atlanta office
deborah livingston of the churches committee for voter registration said a drive was conducted in new york and there have been smaller efforts in other cities
but neither major political party and none of the presidential campaigns is currently targeting formal registration drives at the homeless
the kennedy center honored seven public school superintendents friday for outstanding arts education programs
the seven are: donald s. bruno of the newport news, va., schools; ralph downs of putnam city school district in oklahoma city; laruth gray of abbott union free school district in irvington, n.y.; robert henley of the independence, mo., schools; chris l. huber of independent school district no. 16 of spring lake park, minn.; thomas marx of maine school administrative district no. 28 in camden, maine., and robert e. walton of fayette county schools in lexington, ky
the awards were being presented friday night to the superintendents by the center's alliance for arts education at the american association of school administrators' convention in las vegas
among the highlights of arts education program in each of the winning districts were:
_newport news has established a six-week summer enrichment program in the arts, and an art magnet program for high school students
_the postal service is considering drawings from two first-graders at tulakes elementary school in a competition for a future postage stamp, and another elementary student's drawing served as the state's christmas seal
_the abbott union schools use the arts to bolster instruction for at-risk youngsters in primary and secondary schools
_the independence, mo., schools sponsor a michelangelo project of art lessons for talented youngsters from low-income families and also help expose students to ballet, theater, symphonies and museums through a program called art partners
_district no. 16 in spring lake park, minn., employs a visual arts curriculum for grades k-6 and an artist-in-residence
_district no. 28 in camden, me., has added staff to all arts departments and given students in the rural area access to a mini-theater, music facility, acoustically renovated gym and visual arts facility
_the fayette county schools in lexington, ky., have visual arts specialists who instruct all elementary students one hour each week; it also has an ``arts in basic education'' program to integrate music, drama, visual arts and movement with other subjects
two convicted killers took the witness stand today to testify that an inmate trying to escape the death penalty had loaned them money and had been kind and friendly in prison
darrell edwin hoy and arthur rutherford were among eight current or former death-row convicts brought from florida state prison near starke to testify about the character of james ernest hitchcock, 31
hitchcock was convicted and sentenced to death 10 years ago for the murder of his 13-year-old step-niece
the u.s. supreme court overturned his sentence and ordered the circuit court to hold a new sentencing hearing to determine if he will die in the electric chair or receive life in prison
hoy and rutherford were brought into court today singly in handcuffs, shackles and blue prison uniforms. they were seated in the witness stand before the jury was brought in
prosecutors asked the inmates their feelings on the death penalty
i feel that's wrong for certain reasons, if i may say so,'' said hoy, whose death sentence for the 1975 slayings of two teen-agers was changed to life in prison
rutherford, who faces electrocution for a 1986 murder, agreed
i'm in florida state prison on hearsay, no evidence, no nothing,'' said rutherford. ``i'm against it.''
both described how hitchcock had loaned them money for canteen items. hoy said the defendant had given him his own radio after hoy's was stolen. he also said hitchcock helped him study for a general education degree
hitchcock spent more than a decade in a one-man cell just a few feet from florida's electric chair for the 1976 rape and strangulation of cynthia driggers
the jury now is getting a shortened version of trial testimony and hearing more than 20 witnesses testify for and against hitchcock in his effort to escape death
the jury recommendation _ life or death _ is only advisory to circuit judge gary l. formet sr
extraordinary security was in force at the orange county courthouse as a result of the appearance of the inmates. six of them are awaiting electrocution; two have had their sentences reduced to life in prison
defense attorneys, who argued successfully for their appearance, pointed out that they knew hitchcock well because they lived near him for more than a third of his life
the jury also heard a tape-recorded confession by hitchcock in which he admitted the raping and killing. he later recanted, claiming the confession was given under duress because he was held for four days in solitary confinement. using leadership to mask undercover work for cia, sted `his' undercover work. pick up 3rd pvs, `u.s. state...'</note>
a pro-iranian group said today it kidnapped a u.s. marine colonel serving with the u.n. peacekeeping force in south lebanon and released identity cards bearing his photograph
the oppressed of the earth accused lt. col. william r. higgins, 43, of using his leadership of a group attached to the u.n. interim force in lebanon to mask undercover work for the cia
u.s. state department spokesman charles redman denied thursday that higgins had any links with the cia
in a rescue attempt, shiite amal militiamen today seized six activists of the iranian-backed hezbollah, or party of god, in the southern port of tyre. the amal sealed off a 300-square-mile area
the amal, the main shiite militia in lebanon, is headed by lebanese justice minister nabih berri. it has fighting hezbollah for control of southern lebanon
the claim by oppressed of the earth was made in a typed arabic-language statement delivered to a western news agency in beirut. it was accompanied by two identity cards, one in english and one in hebrew
both bore photographs of higgins, a native of danville, ky., and what appeared to be his signature
it was the second claim of responsibility for wednesday's abduction. the first was made by a previously unknown group calling itself the islamic revolutionary brigades
william higgins, agent of the central intelligence agency who uses his u.n. observer's work as a cover for his dangerous espionage role, is in the hands of our heroic mujahedeen (holy warriors),'' the statement said
the group said it would release higgins following a complete israeli withdrawal from its security zone in south lebanon. it also demanded the release of an estimated 300 lebanese and palestinian prisoners held in khiam detention camp in south lebanon and the immediate cessation of u.s. activity in lebanon
oppressed of the earth is believed made up of shiite moslem zealots loyal to iran's revolutionary patriarch, ayatollah ruhollah khomeini
it has claimed responsibility for hijackings, bombings and and kidnappings including the abduction of 12 lebanese jews in moslem west beirut since 1984, eight of whom it said it killed
oppressed of the earth also claims to have staged the june 1985 hijacking of a twa jetliner in which a u.s. navy diver was killed
during the hijacking, the captors demanded israel free several hundred arabs it held. although israel denied any deal was made, prisoners were released in batches in the weeks that followed the americans' release
in washington, defense secretary frank carlucci said today u.s. officials are studying whether americans should be withdrawn from the u.n. observer group in light of higgins' abduction
but later, president reagan said americans will not be withdrawn. ``no. we are going to meet our obligations to the united nations,'' he said during a white house photo session
carlucci, appearing on nbc-tv's ``today'' show, said ``everything possible'' is being done to secure higgins' release
higgins, a decorated vietnam veteran, heads a 76-man observer group that operates along the lebanon-israel border and has its headquarters in jerusalem
he was kidnapped by gunmen as he was driving from tyre to unifil headquarters in the border town of naqoura. at the time he was violating u.n. rules for travel by americans
an amal spokesman said the hezbollah fundamentalists were rounded up in pre-dawn raids on houses in the port city
we suspect they were monitoring higgins' movements in tyre before his abduction. they will be interrogated,'' said the spokesman, who refused to be identified
we want higgins back and we have no red line as far as his case is concerned,'' amal's military commander, daoud daoud, said thursday
today, daoud told reporters: ``we have clear clues about the identity of the kidnappers. we're still optimistic.'' he did not elaborate
the comment came after a 30-minute meeting between amal's military, security and political chiefs in tyre and senior unifil commanders
the abduction brings the number of foreign hostages in lebanon to 25, including nine americans. most are believed held by pro-iranian shiite extremists
on thursday, a man speaking arabic telephoned a western news agency in beirut, said the islamic revolutionary brigades had kidnapped higgins and accused him of being a cia agent. he did not identify himself
when higgins was seized, he was violating u.n. rules for travel by americans in dangerous areas, unifil spokesman timur goksel said. but, the spokesman added, the colonel ``felt he couldn't abide by these restrictions
higgins felt that as chief, he should be out with his men and know what they are doing.''
american members of u.n. forces are restricted to the headquarters area and are permitted to travel in lebanon only with a u.n. military escort, he said
higgins was the third u.n. official kidnapped in lebanon this month
the other two, a swede and norwegian of the u.n. relief and works agency, were seized feb. 5. after that abduction, the u.n. put plans to revive a development program in lebanon on hold
terry a. anderson, 40, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, is the longest held of all the hostages. he was abducted march 16, 1985. replacements</head>
the surgeon who has performed the largest number of successful lung transplants says the procedure is at a stage comparable to that of heart transplantation 10 years ago
since 1983, dr. joel d. cooper, chief of thoracic surgery at the university of toronto and toronto general hospital, has performed 15 single-lung and seven double-lung transplants
of the single-lung patients, 11 are long-term survivors, including the world's longest-living at 4{ years, and six of the seven two-lung recipients are still living
about 10 or 11 other double-lung transplants and six single-lung procedures have been attempted elsewhere during the same time, said cooper, who also has done heart-lung transplants
he said lung transplantation is no more difficult than heart transplantation, ``just different.''
the next five years will tell us how to use these transplants: singles, doubles, heart-lungs,'' cooper said thursday, the first day of a three-day international conference on thoracic organ transplantation
dr. kathryn a. hale, a pulmonologist at the university of minnesota, said she hopes the next three to five years will bring lung transplantation ``to the stage where it is no longer considered experimental.''
cooper said heart transplantation clearly has ``hit the end of phase one. clearly there will have to be more education'' to increase the availability of donor organs
and ``there will have to be other strategies developed,'' including such approaches as the use of animal organ grafts, to increase the number of transplants, he said
dr. william a. baumgartner of johns hopkins university, who last year performed a ``domino donor'' transplant in which a cystic fibrosis sufferer received the heart and lungs of a brain-dead donor after his own heart was donated to a second recipient, said that operation, and a second, have shown the procedure works
part of the reason for the double-organ procedure was a belief that a heart-lung transplant was easier and safer than a straight lung transplant
as these transplants evolve, there's going to be a role for all of these procedures,'' unilateral lung, double lung, heart-lung and domino donor, he said
he said the domino donor procedure is one ``that can be done with good results.''
but cooper said ``it's probably not good science'' in the sense that lungs now can be transplanted without the heart being removed, and the domino donor procedure ``may be a ripple of the past.''
cooper called the first johns hopkins domino donor procedure last may ``high drama'' because of the news coverage it engendered, but he said he feels it is best to leave the lung recipient with his own heart whenever possible
cooper said he was not trying to be critical of the johns hopkins team, but that he viewed the procedure from his perspective as a lung transplanter
a jury today ruled that the battle creek enquirer libeled a man who was arrested during an investigation of rape but never was charged with the crime, and awarded him $1 million
the six-member jury deliberated four hours over two days before finding that the paper had libeled cereal company mechanic david rouch when it reported on his 1979 arrest during the investigation of a rape case
jurors found that the enquirer published false information and failed to exercise reasonable care
the case set a new standard for libel in michigan when the state supreme court ruled rouch did not have to prove malice, that the report was published with knowledge of its falsity or reckless disregard for the truth. that is one of the elements generally required for a private citizen to prove libel
rouch, 52, had sought $500,000 each for punitive and actual damages. calhoun county circuit court judge stephen miller thursday threw out his claim for punitive damages after the newspaper argued rouch hadn't proven malice, a requirement of a punitive damage award
robert bernius, an attorney for the gannett co. inc.-owned newspaper, said he would appeal to the michigan court of appeals. he and publisher robert miller jr. declined further comment
during closing arguments, rouch attorney john jereck blasted the paper for ``bulldozing'' over his client's rights. ``it was a flagrant disregard under the camouflage of the claim of the public's right to know, freedom of the press,'' jereck said
bernius cited testimony from experts who said the enquirer followed standard practice by making routine checks and accurately reporting the assault and the arrest of rouch as described by police. bernius also urged the jury to focus on what the newspaper knew when the story was printed and not on subsequent developments
rouch, 52, was arrested on suspicion of raping a 17-year-old babysitter. a magistrate approved by telephone an interim personal recognizance bond and he was released. the newspaper reported his arrest and release
before he was arraigned, the investigation changed and rouch never was formally charged. because there was no arraignment, miller ruled that the state's ``official proceedings'' act didn't protect the newspaper
the enquirer didn't learn through its daily police calls that there was another arrest in the case and neither rouch nor his attorney complained until nearly a year had elapsed and the lawsuit was prepared
rouch sued the city for false arrest and received a $4,000 settlement
volunteers armed with flashlights, walkie-talkies and, in some cases, police escorts combed the city's streets and alleys early friday in an effort to find out exactly how many people have nowhere to call home
in the city's south end, a book and sweater in an alcove built of discarded appliances alerted a volunteer to the presence of life. a quick peek into the makeshift dwelling found two people fast asleep
they were left undisturbed while three volunteers recorded them by gender and approximate age
similar groups throughout the city gathered such information to be compiled into what the city believes is the country's only hands-on homeless count. a similar attempt in january to quantify the number of homeless in pennsylvania tallied only those in shelters
boston's first such count, conducted last year, found about 2,860 homeless people
the volunteers took a census of shelter occupants thursday night, then headed into the streets at midnight to look for others occupying makeshift accommodations
it's important to be able to speak with authority'' about the extent of homelessness, mayor raymond flynn told the 117 volunteers before they set out in the freezing night
people rely on the city of boston for these kinds of figures,'' he said. ``when we start making statements about the homeless population in america, we can speak about it with actual statistics.''
the city uses the statistics to help determine how much food, beds, rescue vans and medical supplies are needed to care for the homeless, said ann maquire, executive director of the city's emergency shelter commission, which organized the survey
the volunteers were given maps outlining their assigned search areas
we just about walk every street in the city,'' said allan stern, the city's director of data processing who is charged with compiling the statistics. rough numbers are expected this weekend and a final analysis is expected in about one week, he said
it shows the concern for the issue to have so many people come out here between the hours of 1 and 3'' in the morning, said richard weintraub, 34, director of the 360-bed long island shelter
the boston fire department donated two cars and two drivers. police in the downtown area introduced the census-takers at roll call, alerting officers that people would be poking through the district's nooks and crannies on a legitimate city mission
most of the volunteers were people who regularly work with the homeless and were recruited through word-of-mouth and posters. their experience proved an asset to the thoroughness of the count
one man walking slowly down a south end street hardly appeared to be homeless, but weintraub recognized him from one of the shelters. he was included in the count
we still don't get all the homeless. there are people hidden away in buildings we'll just never find,'' weintraub said
the volunteers were told to be inconspicuous and not to disturb people unless they needed help. at 3 a.m., a man was spotted hobbling on crutches and the volunteers radioed for a rescue van, which took him to shelter, weintraub said
weintraub's group finished searching its 30-block area in the south end at 4 a.m., finding 10 men and one woman
if we don't find a lot of people on the street, that's success,'' he said
some people with dangerously weakened blood vessels in the head may benefit from a new therapy that permanently inserts balloons in the arteries that supply the brain with blood, researchers said friday
the technique appears a highly effective way of preventing strokes in people with bulging arteries at the base of the brain, the researchers said
doctors have experimented with the technique for several years, but they say the latest refinements have overcome earlier drawbacks and should make it a safe way to stop lethal attacks in some people
the treatment is designed to block off vessels that are likely to burst, flooding the brain with blood. doctors from the university of illinois in chicago said they have tried it on 14 people, and in 13 of them it appears to be working well
all of the patients had giant aneurysms. these are bulging weak spots, often an inch across, in one of the two internal carotid arteries that supply blood to the brain
about 1,500 people are diagnosed with this condition in the united states each year. even with standard treatment, the weakened artery eventually bursts in about 30 percent of them, flooding the brain with blood and causing disabling and often fatal injury
the treatment is not intended for people with smaller aneurysms that can be treated in other ways
the results of the latest study, directed by dr. jafar j. jafar, were presented at a stroke conference sponsored by the american heart association
we can do it with far less mortality and morbidity than before,'' jafar said. ``patients are very grateful.''
the balloon therapy represents one of several new medical and surgical approaches being developed to prevent strokes or minimize the damage once they occur
strokes are the third-leading cause of death in the united states after heart disease and cancer. they kill about 150,000 people annually
most strokes occur when a blood clot blocks an artery in the brain, starving the tissue of oxygen. however, about 10 percent result from burst blood vessels that cause bleeding, or hemorrhage, inside the head
earlier attempts to block off giant aneurysms with balloons have been marred by small strokes called transient ischemic attacks, among other problems
in the past, there have been a lot of complications with this approach,'' said dr. vladimir c. hachinski of university hospital in london, ontario. ``this paper seems to be saying that there are instances where it will help.''
four main arteries supply blood to the brain. even when one of these arteries is shut off with a balloon, enough blood reaches the brain from the other three
it's like the water system of a city,'' jafar said. ``four viaducts bring the water in. you shut one of them off, and the others can still supply enough water to the city.''
jafar said he was able to avoid complications with a series of refinements in the technique, including measuring the brain's blood supply before permanently inserting the balloon
the patient first receives a blood-thinning drug. while the patient is awake under local anesthesia, doctors use a thin tube called a catheter to push a deflated balloon through the arteries into the head. it stops just before the aneurysm, which usually occurs at the base of the brain in one of the carotid arteries
then the balloon is filled with fluid, shutting off the artery. next, the doctors check the flow of blood to the brain from the other arteries. if it is adequate, the balloon is left in place. but if it's too weak, the balloon is removed
when this happens, the patient is given a drug called mannitol, which increases the flow of blood through the other three arteries to the brain. in a day or two, the balloon is put back and re-inflated
the one patient in whom the treatment failed suffered a mild stroke during the procedure. all the other paients are doing fine during follow-up periods ranging from six months to four years
this series was very effective,'' said dr. louis r. caplan of tufts medical school in boston. ``it's not applicable to all people with run-of-the-mill aneurysms.''
soviet pact
the u.s.-soviet nuclear arms treaty has major military and political gains for the nato alliance and should be approved without delay, a group of arms control experts told the senate foreign relations committee on friday
the overriding question is whether it lessens the risk of nuclear war,'' said paul. c. warnke. ``by getting rid of a category of nuclear weapons that are particularly vulnerable and adapted for first use, the treaty admirably meets this test.''
warnke formerly served as director of the arms control and disarmament agency. his testimony, along with the other three experts, concluded a third week of hearings by the committee, which is one of three in the senate considering the pact
the treaty also was criticized friday by william van cleave, of the hoover institution at stanford university. he told the panel that ``it is not in our interest.''
the accord was signed in december by soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev and president reagan. it eliminates u.s. and soviet nuclear-tipped missiles with a range of between 310 and 3,400 miles
the administration has pushed hard for senate ratification, which will require a two-thirds vote of the 100-member chamber. senate leaders say approval is likely
warnke told the panel that ``from the standpoint of strategic policy, intermediate and shorter-range missiles fail to meet the basic criteria strategic stability.''
because of their areas of deployment, many of them are highly vulnerable,'' he said. ``moreover, because of the shorter ranges involved, ballistic missiles in these categories can strike their targets within a few minutes and thus provide virtually no warning time.''
the treaty also offers political gains, warnke said, because it shows the ability of the 16-member north atlantic treaty organization to stand together and face down political opponents who opposed the u.s. weapons that were deployed starting in 1983, he said
ralph earle jr., policy director of the lawyers alliance for nuclear arms control, a private group, echoed warnke's comments
to discard the treaty now would undermine the solidarity and support the united states has received from our allies around the world,'' earle said
what this treaty does is put arms control back on the track following a hiatus of eight years,'' he told the panel. ``it puts the signature of a conservative american president on an arms control pact, lending the process further credibility with the public and in congress.''
this treaty can, and should, be used to galvanize support for further reductions in conventional and strategic nuclear arms,'' earle said
jonathan dean, arms control adviser to the union of concerned scientists, said the treaty ``has done more than any event of the past 40 years to promote a european feeling of responsibility for their own defense and for intra-european defense cooperation.''
the chief military effect ``is to improve nato's theater-range nuclear position while enhancing crisis stability,'' dean told the panel. ``consequently, the agreement creates no new need to improve nato's nuclear forces. it makes no sense to build down nuclear weapons with one hand and build them up with the other.''
william schneider jr., chairman of the u.s. general advisory committee on arms control and disarmament, praised the treaty's verification provisions, which include short-notice inspections and on-site inspections
he noted the soviets' ``abysmal record'' of complying with past arms control agreements and noted the new treaty ``provides an important opportunity to begin to correct this problem.''
van cleave, criticizing the treaty, said he believes the main soviet aim is to cripple reagan's star wars anti-missile defense research program and other u.s. efforts aimed at building up western defenses
virtually every western modernization program, particularly in the nuclear areas, would be greatly dampened by the current climate of arms control,'' he told the panel
new jersey has decided not to try rubin ``hurricane'' carter a third time for murder, ending the former boxer's 22-year legal saga, a prosecutor said today
john goceljak, acting prosecutor in passaic county, said the decision was based on the long period of time since the 1966 murders, the unavailability of witnesses, the likely exclusion of the only eyewitness testimony and the decision by a federal judge that carter's conviction was racially tainted
goceljak said his office today was filing a motion in superior court in paterson to dismiss the indictment against carter and john artis, accused of being his accomplice
goceljak said the decision was made in consultation with the state's criminal justice director, donald r. belsole
it's not a relief,'' said belsole, ``it's the way the system works. it's the right thing to do. it's time now to close the book on the case.''
a judge must sign the motion to finalize dismissal of the indictment, and attorney myron beldock, in a statement on behalf of carter and artis, said he hoped for quick consideration by the court
we are extremely pleased with the decision of the state of new jersey to dismiss the case against our clients, and hope that the appropriate orders will be signed promptly,'' said beldock
on jan. 11, the u.s. supreme court let stand a federal judge's ruling that cleared carter. the lower-court judge found carter's conviction was tainted by racism and by prosecutors withholding information from the defense. carter had been free on bail pending appeal after serving 19 years of a life prison term
the supreme court ruling left to the passaic county prosecutor's office the decision on whether to seek another trial for carter and his alleged accomplice, whose first convictions were overturned by the new jersey supreme court before a 1976 retrial
defense attorneys all along had considered a third trial unlikely because the eyewitness testimony had been so discredited during appeals
carter, a former middleweight contender now 50, has been living in seclusion since being freed by u.s. district judge h. lee sarokin in 1985
his cause was taken up by bob dylan, who wrote and sang ``the ballad of hurricane'' in the 1970s, actress ellen burstyn, boxer muhammed ali, singer joan baez and others who elevated carter as a symbol of racial injustice
but after a few highly publicized fund-raising events _ some touched by scandal _ carter's all-star backing faded
the legal odyssey began on a hot night june 17, 1966, when two black gunmen entered the lafayette bar and grill in paterson and killed the bartender and two patrons. hours earlier, a black paterson bartender had been shot to death by a white man
carter and artis were arrested three months later and convicted by an all-white jury in may 1967
but two witnesses later recanted, saying they had been pressured by detectives into giving false testimomny at the trial, and the case was reopened in 1974. the state supreme court threw out the first verdict in 1976
the state put carter and artis back on trial and they were convicted again in 1976, in part with the testimony of one of the recanting witnesses who retracted claims he was coerced. this time, the state's highest court upheld the convictions by a 4-3 vote in 1982
the case went to federal court and sarokin found that the 1976 convictions were tainted by ``racial stereotyping, fear and prejudice,'' and by the defense not having the full results of a lie detector test given to one of the recanting witnesses. update with rhodes announcing candidacy. picks up 6th graf pvs, `mecham's letter...' ^by larry lopez</note>
impeached gov. evan mecham says acting gov. rose mofford is replacing his administration before the senate can decide whether to remove him permanently, but a mofford aide said she has ``bent over backward'' to be fair
may i ask you to recognize that i have only been accused and not convicted of any act,'' mecham said thursday in a letter to mofford. the embattled republican also demanded that mofford forward all his mail unopened
i must convey my deep disappointment and surprise at the way your people are turning a temporary acting governorship into a complete disruption and replacement of my administration,'' mecham said
the republican-controlled house impeached mecham on charges he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan, misused $80,000 in state money and obstructed justice. his impeachment trial in the senate is scheduled to start feb. 29. he also faces a criminal trial in march in connection with the campaign loan
mecham also faces a recall election may 17, and today former u.s. rep. john rhodes, a republican, announced he would be a candidate
our state needs effective gubernatorial leadership to help our legislators solve our problems,'' said rhodes, 71, who retired from congress in 1982. ``we cannot afford continued paralysis.''
mecham is guaranteed a spot on the recall ballot, and the only other major announced candidate is carolyn warner, a democrat who lost to mecham in 1986 in a three-way race. about 80 people have picked up packets to collect the 3,336 petition signatures that are needed by march 18 to get on the ballot
mecham's letter came as mrs. mofford, a democratic secretary of state who became acting governor upon mecham's impeachment, accepted the resignation of washington lobbyist fred craft
last week, mecham urged mrs. mofford to retain craft, who has helped arizona lobby for the federal superconducting super collider and rented part of his law offices for use by arizona. craft tendered his resignation feb. 11
mecham's efforts to use craft on the superconducting super collider and other issues were controversial and stirred allegations that he had tried to get around the state procurement code
mrs. mofford issued a statement thursday, saying, ``members of the (arizona) congressional delegation have promised to continue to be especially vigilant with the issues facing arizona, especially the supercollider.''
mecham's letter criticized the way mail has been handled since his impeachment
what i protest the most is the sudden ordering of the mail room staff to vacate tuesday afternoon,'' he wrote
i realize that your people said that mail marked personal or confidential would not be opened but i insist that all mail addressed to me is to be forwarded without opening,'' he wrote
mrs. mofford's chief of staff, andy hurwitz, confirmed that state department of administration officials were brought in to handle the mail but said he would be willing to work out further compromises if needed
we have, i think, bent over backward to try and accommodate him,'' hurwitz said of mecham, noting that only those who offered resignations had actually been let go
acting mofford press secretary athia hardt said mecham aide bonnie simons and her aides were reassigned after ms. simons took the position that any mail addressed to office of the governor should go to mecham first
much of the mail requires immediate action and ``it would be irresponsible for us to bundle it up and send it off to glendale,'' ms. hardt said, referring to the suburban offices mecham has referred to as his government-in-exile
a leftist social action group on friday called for an international investigation of human rights violations by president corazon aquino's government
the philippine alliance of human rights advocates said it was filing a petition friday asking the geneva-based united nations human rights commission to investigate mrs. aquino's human rights record
the petition, copies of which were released at a news conference, alleges that ``human rights violations have increased under the aquino government.'' it asks that the commission condemn the aquino and u.s. governments for allegedly abetting them
there was no immediate comment from the aquino government. military officials had earlier denied allegations of human rights violations and said they were concocted by communist rebels and their supporters
the philippines' house of representatives is investigating charges that some of the 20 alleged rebel leaders arrested in raids early this month had been tortured
the alliance is an umbrella organization of church-affiliated human rights groups which the military claims are infiltrated by members of the rebel new people's army
in its petition, the alliance cited specific allegations of abuses, including extra-judicial executions and torture of suspected rebels, bombing of civilians, forced evacuation of rural villagers and use of armed civilian anti-communist vigilantes
it said it included the united states in the petition because the u.s. government ``has intensified its intervention in the counter-insurgency program of the aquino government.''
judge maximiano asuncion of the regional trial court in suburban quezon city said the trial of 20 alleged rebel leaders will begin next month. six of the defendants pleaded innocent to charges of illegal possession of firearms
in a televised interview after the arraignment, asuncion said he supports a proposal that trials of rebels be conducted by military tribunals instead of the civil courts because the military is in a better position to handle possible reprisals
also friday, suspected communist rebels killed a police informant in an ambush in manila, and three men shot and killed a major in the southern province of zamboanga del sur, police and military officials said
informant petronilo lim died in a manila hospital a few hours after suspected communist urban guerrillas gunned him down in the capital's tondo district, police said
in zamboanga del sur province on mindanao island 500 miles southeast of manila, three unidentified men shot maj. carlos pumano after they called him out of his home after midnight thursday, military officials said. pumano was operations chief of the philippine constabulary command in the province
flocks of pesky pigeons seem impossible to scare away and killing them is messy, but some oklahoma legislators think they've hit on a way to limit the feathered population ... birth control
state sen. leo kingston introduced an amendment that would allow game officials to use birth control-treated feed instead of poison for pigeon control
his proposal was approved as an amendment to a house bill passed by the senate on thursday that removes pigeons from the status of game birds. such status has meant they can't be shot except during hunting season. the measure would allow pigeons to be eradicated or removed from areas where they have become a nuisance
state sen. gilmer capps raised one question about the birth control idea that wasn't fully answered: what will happen to the population of stray cats that catch and eat pigeons that are ``on the pill?''
annette himmelein only met perri doughty of australia one week ago, but on saturday doughty will serve as bridesmaid at himmelein's wedding
six years ago, the young women became pen pals through a project at himmelein's high school and they later vowed to stand up for each other when they married
doughty arrived last saturday to fulfill her part of the bargain and one of the first things that struck her was the difference in climate between her 21-year-old pen pal's home and her own native city of goondiwindi in the state of queensland
i've never seen snow before,'' said doughty. ``i left a nice hot summer to come here.''
australia isn't the only foreign nation to be represented at the wedding of himmelein and mark shepherd
also attending are nanna rintala, 20, of kauhava, finland, and patrick coenen, 22, of lamaken, belgium. both are former exchange students who lived with the himmelein family
my parents' house is sort of like the u.n. right now,'' said himmelein, an assistant nurse. ``i sent all of them invitations. it was just the natural thing to do, because i consider all the exchange students we've had here my brothers and sisters.''
doughty said she was flabbergasted by the scale of the wedding
i nearly fell over when she told me she was going to have 700 people there,'' doughty said
leaders of two former tamil rebel groups that surrendered their weapons to peacekeeping troops said friday they have applied to have the groups recognized as political parties
spokesmen for the tamil eelam liberation organization and the people's liberation organization of tamil eelam said they supported the peace accord signed in july to end the four-year war by minority tamils seeking an independent homeland
the election commission announced wednesday that nominations for nine provincial councils would be accepted march 2-9. the council elections are a part of the peace accord
the commission has already granted political recognition to the former militant group eelam people's revolutionary liberation front
we have applied to the election commission for recognition as a political party,'' said subramanian haridarraj, a politburo member of the tamil eelam liberation organization. he said his group fully backed the peace accord and wanted to turn its military organization into a political movement
when asked what the once gun-wielding members are doing now, haridarraj said, ``we have got fairly large-scale poultry projects going on in mannar and vavuniya in the north and east. our members are keen to develop this kind of self-employment
and right now chicken prices are good in colombo,'' he added
a leader of the people's liberation organization of tamil eelam said, ``we are not signatories to the peace accord, but we back it. we are gearing ourselves to participate in the political process.''
the leader identified himself by his military code name, haran
the peace accord has been rejected by the largest and most powerful tamil militant group, the liberation tigers of tamil eelam
more than 45,000 indian troops are in sri lanka to disarm the tigers and enforce the pact, which was mediated by india
india is sri lanka's northern neighbor and has a large tamil population of its own. in sri lanka, tamils comprise 18 percent of the 16 million population and claim they are discriminated against by the majority buddhist sinhalese
the leaders of the less militant tamil groups both demanded that 986 rebel suspects being held in sri lankan jails be released as stipulated by the accord
we cannot afford to lose sight of our cadres yet behind bars. this is the only sore point,'' haridarraj said
the sri lankan government released hundreds of suspects immediately after the accord was signed july 29 but later stopped the process when the tigers refused to surrender arms
sri lanka's largest opposition party, the sri lanka freedom party, announced it would boycott provincial council elections, saying general elections should be held before any local polls
the moderate tamil political party tamil united liberation front also has said the elections be postponed because of the turbulence in the north and east, the tigers' stronghold
president-elect roh tae-woo announced his new cabinet lineup friday by retaining seven ministers from the old cabinet and placing three hard-liners in top security posts
roh, who takes office feb. 25, has pledged to usher in full democracy but political observers said the makeup of the cabinet indicates roh is favoring stability
roh urged new ministers to maintain administrative continuity in the face of legislative elections, economic problems and the olympic games in seoul
the former general demanded the next government establish a fresh moral standard to gain public trust but opposition parties said his cabinet lacked freshness in its character and background
the new lineup of 20 ministers plus a prime minister and deputy prime minister contained many technocrats and academics. five figures with military backgrounds were appointed as ministers of defense, labor, communications, transportation and government administration
opposition parties rejected an invitation to field candidates for the cabinet, charging that roh would continue the authoritarian rule of outgoing president chun doo-hwan no matter what they did
the move obviously limited the opposition's effect on the cabinet's formation. but it also removed the opposition from any responsibility in the policies of the new government
roh, who helped chun seize power in 1980 with military backing, won presidential elections last december after promising to end the country's long tradition of military domination
he was opposed by two opposition candidates, kim young-sam and kim dae-jung, who split the opposition ticket thereby allowing roh to win
roh gave the top security posts to three hard-liners: new defense minister oh ja-bock, home minister lee sang-hee and justice minister chung hae-chang
oh retired as chariman of the joint chiefs of staff in december and retains considerable influence in the military. he is expected to be roh's link to the armed forces
ahn moo-hyuk was retained as head of the powerful intellignece organization, the agency for national security planning, whose director works with the cabinet but is not a member
roh stressed his desire to ensure sustained economic expansion by filling economic posts with noted experts
his economic considerations were underlined feb. 11 when he named lee hyun-jae, a political moderate and noted economics professor, as prime minister
roh has said he would reduce presidential power and increase the influence of the prime miniser and his cabinet. ministers held little power in the past, with most decisions being made by the presidency
the top economic post went to a leading technocrat, rha woong-bae, who was promoted from trade minister in the old cabinet to deputy prime minister and economic planning minister
right now, we are on the threshold of entering from a developing country to an advanced country,'' roh told the new cabinet in calling for a renewed export drive
economic ministers pledged to give top priority to ensuring price stability. roh has promised development projects but the new government is expected to adopt a tight money policy with limited spending
there has been growing concern that high inflation could damage the economy. another thorny economic issue is growing trade friction with countries that have trade deficits with south korea. seoul is under strong pressure from the united states to open its markets wider to u.s. goods. as redundant; picks up 4th graf pvs, delvalle is</note>
the state department denied today reports that the u.s. government has approached panama about the possibility of dropping charges against panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega if he and his military associates withdrew from politics
according to reports in newsday and the new york times, assistant secretary of state elliott abrams had discussed the possibility of a deal during a meeting this week in miami with panamanian president eric arturo delvalle
but state department spokesman charles redman said abrams ``made no deal, offered no deal and was not in a position to offer a deal''
he said that in response to a panamanian inquiry, abrams told delvalle that it was legally possible for the united states to drop the indictments against noriega. two florida grand juries handed down a series of drug-related indictment against noriega earlier this month
we have every intention of carrying through on the indictments,'' redman said
but justice department spokesman john k. russell earlier today did not dispute an account in today's new york times that quoted him as saying abrams had notified senior department officials that he would seek to have the indictments dropped if noriega left the country
we told him we would be against the idea,'' russell told the times
redman said russell's account was ``slightly wrong.'' redman added that he stood by his own version of what happened
at the white house, president reagan refused to discuss the subject
this is a case before the courts and i am not going to comment,'' the president said in response to a reporter's question during a picture-taking ceremony in the oval office with west german chancellor helmut kohl
delvalle is panama's titular leader, but political authority rests largely with noriega, the general who heads panama's defense forces
noriega was indicted feb. 5 by federal grand juries in miami and tampa, fla., on racketeering and other narcotics-related charges. his extradition appears highly unlikely because a 1904 treaty between the two countries does not oblige either state to extradite its own nationals
the times reported that abrams had told delvalle the charges might be dropped if noriega and his top associates withdrew from politics and go into exile. newsday published a similar report in thursday's editions
the times said the justice department told abrams it would oppose any move to drop the indictments, and that any decision to drop the indictments would have to be made by president reagan
newsday, quoting unidentified sources close to delvalle, said that delvalle agreed to discuss the offer with noriega in panama
the newspaper quoted an unidentified state department official as saying that abrams and delvalle ``discussed the situation and (abrams) urged delvalle to take a larger role as a civilian in a move to get the military to step back.''
the question of noriega's indictment did come up in the discussion,'' the newspaper quoted the official as saying. ``it is not correct to say that deals are being made.''
newsday quoted a source as saying abrams had asked delvalle to fly to washington after the meeting and telephone noriega with the offer. delvalle declined and returned to panama
the times said the proposal for a deal was initiated by delvalle, not by abrams. officials said abrams had told delvalle that the state and defense departments probably would be receptive to a dismissal of the indictments if noriega left panama, but that the justice department would oppose it
a judge said friday he would rule march 7 on union carbide corp.'s appeal of a court order that it pay $270 million in interim relief to victims of the bhopal gas leak
another judge hearing the government's $3 billion damage case against union carbide adjourned proceedings until march 16 to await the decision in the appeal
high court judge s.k. seth heard closing arguments on the appeal of the interim relief order, which carbide says is unfair until liability in the 1984 disaster is determined
more than 2,800 people died and at least 20,000 were seriously injured when gas leaked from a carbide subsidiary in bhopal, in central india
attorney f.s. nariman, representing the danbury, conn.-based company, told the court friday that the order would not be enforceable in the united states, the united news of india reported
but indian government attorney k. parasaran said india had succeeded in previous claims cases, the news agency said
meanwhile, bhopal district judge m.w. deo adjourned hearings in the main damages case until after the appeals verdict is issued
it was deo who ordered carbide last december to deposit $270 million to be used as ``interim relief'' payments for victims. he said the victims were in great need and could not wait for help until the damages case was settled
the government filed its suit on behalf of the victims sept. 5, 1986, accusing carbide of negligence. union carbide claims the accident was the result of sabotage by a disgruntled employee
the leader of south africa's poorest black homeland told president p.w. botha on friday that partitioning the nation into such ``self-governing'' states won't solve its political problems
kenneth mopeli, chief minister of qwaqwa, was essentially saying ``no thanks'' to plans botha had outlined for more self-sufficiency and eventual independence for the tribal areas
the territories comprise 13 percent of south africa's land and are meant to be homelands for the nation's black majority, which has no voice in national affairs
mopeli called botha one of south africa's greatest leaders but challenged his view of the future for the 10 homelands
the president was in phuthaditjhaba to dedicate a new government-funded legislative assembly building for the tiny homeland in the dusty foothills of the drakensberg mountains. the president also unveiled a bust of mopeli
botha told the 80 black legislators that the self-governing areas ``have a proud history.''
he said development taking place in qwaqwa _ which means ``whiter than white'' in southern sotho dialect _ had convinced him the homeland wanted to be more self-sufficient
mopeli has steadfastly resisted independence for qwaqwa, saying it does not have enough land or industry to be economically or politically viable
qwaqwa, covering 240 square miles, is the smallest of the homelands, and many of its workers earn about $30 a month. it is one of six homelands classified as ``self-governing states.'' four homelands are recognized as independent republics by south africa
the self-governing states as they exist today are apartheid-affirmed structures,'' mopeli said, referring to the government's policy of racial separation
we are still convinced that our political salvation does not lie in the partitioning and fragmenting of this country for various groups,'' he said. ``we need ... a more viable formula.''
botha said homeland leaders such as mopeli, who have rejected independence, will be invited to ``share in discussions on continued constitutional reform for all the black communities.''
he specifically mentioned the proposed national council, an advisory body intended to negotiate a political system that would for the first time bring blacks into national politics
currently, the 5 million whites lead the government and control the economy, while the 26 million blacks are not represented in parliament
most prominent black leaders, including mopeli, have rejected the national council idea
the national council that is being envisaged as an instrument of negotiation shall always be viewed with suspicion, since according to its chief spokesman (botha), it is intended to design a constitution that will be built on the group concept,'' mopeli said. ``the fears we harbor are that once the group concept has been entrenched in the constitution, some groups may find themselves being more equal than others.''
a legislative committee beat a retreat friday after republicans and democrats alike threatened rebellion over a policy to ban food from committee rooms and the house chamber
the four-member house services committee reversed itself on a 3-1 vote, allowing legislators to have their cake and eat it, too, while working
the vote came early friday morning after majority republicans in the house stalled work thursday on dozens of major bills awaiting action. instead, the legislators went into caucus to argue over the no-food policy
the lone holdout on the committee was rep. tom ratterree, a retired air force colonel who has strong feelings about the subject
when i came up here several years ago, before i was elected, i was amazed at what i saw, people eating in committee meetings and leaving a mess,'' he told a reporter thursday
at that time ratterree vowed not to change his position
i think it's a mess,'' he said. ``i don't know of any businesses that allow that to happen.''
no vote was taken in the caucus, but several members circulated letters and gathered names in support of a reversal
several hours after the caucus at least two lawmakers defiantly munched cookies in a house committee room
earlier this week, house speaker carl ``bev'' bledsoe proposed the no-food policy when outside groups began offering legislators breakfast in the capitol before each morning's session. he said crumbs and debris from the on-the-job meals had gotten out of hand
the policy forced minority democrats to abandon their luncheon caucus and move it into the office of gov. roy romer
a u.n. spokesman said friday that a kidnapped u.s. marine serving with a peacekeeping force in lebanon was not violating travel restrictions when he was abducted, contradicting an earlier u.n. report
u.n. spokesman mario zamorano said lt. col. william r. higgins, who disappeared wednesday, was operating within u.n. guidelines when he drove from tyre to the headquarters of the u.n. interim force in lebanon in the border town of naqoura
thursday unifil spokesman timur goksel said that american members of u.n. forces are restricted to the headquarters area and are permitted to travel in lebanon only with a u.n. military escort
zamorano called goksel's report ``totally inaccurate.''
as all his predecessors, he travelled freely in the area without escort,'' zamorano said
higgins, chief of the observer group, was the 10th american to head the u.n. truce supervision organization in lebanon in the 40 years since it was formed. the 76-man group, with eight other americans besides higgins, is attached to unifil in south lebanon
for 40 years, he said, u.n. observers in the middle east have had a ``categorical rule: they do not carry weapons or move with armed escorts. that is something they want themselves
they believe their protection comes from being unarmed,'' he said
in times of danger, it has been suggested that the observers should have armed escorts,'' he said, but added, ``they always have rejected this.''
zamorano said that u.n. undersecretary-general marrack goulding met higgins' fellow officers friday and was told ``even after the abduction that they do not, repeat do not, want to be armed or have armed escorts.''
the u.n. spokesman said that on thursday higgins' u.n. observer force was pulled out of the u.n. peacekeeping area in south lebanon and withdrawn to the headquarters near naqoura
the u.n. spokesman in new york had no comment on claims of kidnap responsibility by two groups. he said the matter was under investigation
the spokesman said higgins had gone to tyre for a meeting with amal militia leaders as part of his official duties
the second court-martial of marine cpl. lindsey scott on controversial charges of raping and trying to kill a fellow marine's wife went to a military jury thursday as his father predicted acquittal
i am very confident that we will win it,'' james scott said after deliberations began. ``i just think there's justice in the world.''
scott, 32, of louisville, ky., was convicted of abduction, rape, sodomy and attempted murder in an april 20, 1983, attack at the quantico marine base
that verdict was overturned in 1987 by the u.s. military court of appeals on grounds scott had not received adequate counsel from his first civilian attorney
meanwhile, civil rights activists established a legal defense fund for scott, and cbs' ``60 minutes'' broadcast a story on the case. jesse jackson directed aides to lobby the congressional black caucus to pressure the pentagon for a new trial for the black serviceman
scott had become a suspect almost immediately after the woman, the 23-year-old wife of a military policeman who worked with him, was found dazed and bleeding
she told investigators she had been lured from her apartment by a telephone call from a man who said her husband had been in an accident and who offered to take her to the hospital
instead, the man drove her to a remote spot, raped her, choked her, stabbed her in the neck and left her for dead, she said
the white woman picked scott from a group of photographs and then from a lineup, but each time she equivocated, saying other men in the groups resembled him. once she picked out scott because she said he ``scares me the most.''
investigators said she also identified his car
the 17-day retrial ended with civilian defense attorney john leino arguing there was a lack of evidence against his client
leino repeated his charge that the naval investigative service used improper lineup techniques and led the victim to her identification of scott
the victim picked scott because ``in her mind, someone has to pay,'' he said
lieno said the only bit of forensic evidence presented in the case _ a hair taken from the victim's clothing _ did not belong to scott
we think that the motive in this case was sex ... and we believe that the intent was murder,'' military prosecutor maj. ron mcneil told the jury of seven marines
was there a conspiracy here to make this up? absolutely not. there's no conspiracy here.'' mcneil said
a crucial part of scott's defense was the testimony of a department store security guard who said she saw scott in a store at the time of the attack
the prosecution said the testimony of cynthia ausby was ``incredible.'' mcneil said ms. ausby did not firmly recall seeing scott until almost 10 months after the crime. she did not testify in the first court-martial
the defense argued that ms. ausby's recollection was aided by her checking of store arrest records. talks</head>
the justice department said friday it is declining to participate in any further settlements with families of the seven astronauts killed in the challenger shuttle crash
the department negotiated settlements with four of the seven families in december 1986
the justice department's position is that it would be unfair to contribute to any settlement higher than the amounts negotiated in 1986 and that the government has no legal liability in the accident, said department spokeswoman amelia brown
last week, the father and brother of mission specialist judith a. resnik signed an agreement with shuttle contractor morton thiokol inc. for payment of from $1.5 million to $2.5 million. the justice department declined to participate in the negotiations leading to that settlement
resnik's relatives weren't involved in the 1986 settlement
in addition to resnik, the federal government didn't make payments to the family of ronald e. mcnair, who also settled separately with thiokol
the widow of challenger pilot michael smith has sued the national aeronautics and space administration and thiokol
brown said the resnik family had rejected a ``generous'' offer prior to the 1986 settlement, which was made on behalf of nasa and morton thiokol
brown said the offer took into account the different financial needs in the families based on the number of dependents and also took into account the requests from the families that they be treated as similarly as possible in the settlement. resnik was the only challenger crew member who was not survived by a spouse and children
the justice department has never released the terms of the settlements, citing the survivors' privacy, but justice department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, have said the amount was at least $1 million for each of the four families
a burglar with an eye for art stole an original watercolor by thomas hart benton valued at $46,000, an autographed color photograph and two other paintings, police said
the benton watercolor, ``trading at westport landing,'' apparently was a detailed study for benton's mural ``old kansas city,'' commissioned by the river club and completed in 1956
the most recent appraisal of the study put its value at $46,000
also stolen in monday's break-in was a color photograph of ``persephone,'' signed by the artist. ``persephone'' is a 1939 benton painting bought by the nelson gallery last year for a reported $2.5 million
a painting of streetcar tracks by duard marshall and a work depicting a cherry tree by an artist identified only as winchell, also were taken, but nothing else in the house was touched
sgt. bob watts, of the metro patrol burglary unit, said the fact that only the paintings and photo were stolen during the break-in ``seems to indicate they went there for the specific purpose of stealing his art.''
the owner, who asked not to be identified, and his family were friendly with benton and the owner's father bought the westport landing painting and bequeathed it to his son
some israeli soldiers who confront arab rioters are firing soft-nosed dumdum bullets, which have an exploding effect on impact and make large, tearing wounds, british opposition leader neil kinnock said friday
kinnock, leader of britain's labor party, said he saw an x-ray taken of the wound that forced doctors to amputate the lower part of a palestinian's leg
he said it ``showed shattering of the bone and flesh consistent with the use of an explosive bullet.'' at another point in the news conference, he said the injury also was consistent with ``the wound inflicted by a dumdum bullet.''
smaller caliber ammunition is being modified to make it more dangerous, he said, and displayed two .22-caliber bullets that had been filed to give them rough edges
the filed-down bullet with its extra effects of internal wounding is deliberately done ... and that conforms to many of the definitions of dumdum,'' kinnock said the third day of his visit here
since november, israeli snipers have used .22-caliber rifles under supervision of their superiors to hit leaders of palestinian protests
dumdum bullets are outlawed by the geneva conventions for use in warfare
israeli officials have denied the army uses them, but palestinian doctors have said for several weeks that only dumdums could have caused some of the wounds they treat
kinnock, who has met with israel's top leaders during his visit, said none denied such bullets were being used
on the occasions on which i've put the point, i've received rationalizations and descriptions of the terrible pressures under which the israeli defense forces are operating, but no one has attempted to deny that the bullets are used,'' he said
kinnock added, however, that he believed such ammunition was ``being used without any form of permission or direction or acceptance or endorsement by the israeli army and the israeli authorities. of that i have no doubt.''
kinnock also said there was ``clear evidence, irrefutable evidence'' that israeli soldiers had shot arab protesters in the back since arab riots began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
on visits to two hospitals in the occupied territories, kinnock said, he saw seven palestinians hospitalized with bullet wounds in the back
he said he expressed his concern about the use of modified bullets and the back wounds to israeli officials and ``it is possible that these tactics may be adjusted, are indeed possibly in the process of being adjusted now.''
kinnock arrived in israel after visits to jordan and egypt, and has toured both the west bank and gaza
a book collector has written a happy ending to a dying man's quest for a rare book to complete his collection of works by western novelist zane grey
mack landers' quest for a copy of ``don, the story of a lion dog,'' of which only an estimated 100 copies exist in this country, got national publicity when syndicated columnist bob greene wrote about him
after hearing about landers, dr. james h. vickers, president of the national zane grey's west society in ijamsville, md., sent a copy to greene, who will deliver it to landers on sunday at his home in this fort worth suburb
anybody that thought that much of zane grey, i'm happy to send it to him,'' vickers, 57, said thursday. ``i hope he gets a lot of enjoyment out of it.''
doctors gave landers, 73, less than three months to live in january, after they found that cancer had spread in his body
landers was near tears when he learned that a copy of ``don'' soon would be added to his 92-book collection of grey's books
i don't have the vocabulary to express how i really feel,'' said landers. ``i know it's true, but i can't believe i'm going to get it. it's wonderful that someone would do that for an old man.''
out of appreciation for greene's efforts, landers said he will accept the copy the chicago tribune columnist is delivering rather than one offered by a fort worth woman or those offered by people from california, colorado, connecticut and several other states
we're going to go with mr. greene because he was the one who instigated the story in the first place,'' said landers' wife, alliene. ``everyone is being so kind. we're real grateful.''
greene said he even was contacted by zane grey's granddaughter, who offered to give landers a copy
greene said he was surprised by the response to his column that appeared last week in about 200 newspapers
the books are starting to pop up,'' he said. ``it's been estimated to me that there are only about 100 in the country. we had no idea we'd have this kind of response.''
don'' is a limited-edition tale about a hunting expedition grey and friends took to the grand canyon area in the early 1920s. the men were hunting mountain lions, not to kill but to sell to zoos and circuses
about 350 students from tufts university will discuss the cold war and nuclear arms race in a classroom session with undergraduate counterparts in the soviet union via television, the school said
the march 5 teleconference is the first of three scheduled sessions between students from tufts and moscow state university in a jointly run course on the superpowers' arms buildup
tufts professor martin j. sherwin, course instructor and director of tufts' nuclear age history and humanities center, said the project coincides with the rise of glasnost, soviet leader mikhail gorbachev's policy of openness
given the new climate in the soviet union, this appears to be the right step at the right time,'' he said
an american panel of historians and foreign policy experts is scheduled to discuss the arms race with a panel of soviet counterparts
these programs will be lively discussions,'' sherwin said. ``panelists will be directed to engage in a dialogue rather than to present set pieces.''
students will have an opportunity to question both countries' panelists, he added
the first session will focus on the history of the nuclear age, including the consequences of the u.s. bombing of hiroshima and nagasaki in world war ii, the first united nations' arms control debates and the origins of the cold war, sherwin said
the 1962 cuban missile crisis and current nuclear policy issues _ including the u.s. strategic defense initiative program, the geneva arms talks and the december signing of an intermediate range missile reduction treaty _ will be discussed at april 9 and april 30 sessions. places</head>
a rundown housing project that some critics say should be razed has been placed on the national register of historic place, a move hailed by residents and other opponents of demolition
thank the lord,'' shirley johnson, treasurer of the allen parkway village residents council, said after getting word of the decision wednesday
i just hope this helps to end all that demolishing business. this is my home, and although a lot of the project is boarded-up now, it could some day be home to a lot of the homeless who have no shelter,'' she said
however, a texas historical commission official said the designation doesn't mean the project won't be demolished
the national register's austin office was notified wednesday by the national parks service, which makes the final determination, that the project had been put on the register, said marlene casarez, the office's administrator
the project was nominated for the designation by stephen fox of the anchorage foundation of texas, which backs architectural preservation and architectural history projects
the project is architecturally significant because ``it is a very fine example of modern architecture design in the field of public housing,'' fox said. the project was built in 1942 and 1944 as housing for war-industry workers and their families
allen parkway also met the state and national registers' standards of being a significant example of community planning and for social and humanitarian purposes, he said
about 130 mainly black and vietnamese families live in the 1,000-unit project today
as other residents moved out, the city's housing authority sealed the empty units in anticipation of federal approval of a plan to raze the project and sell the prime 37.5-acre tract west of downtown for development. this could still be done, officials said
everyone has to understand that listing in the national register is no protection per se,'' said jim steely, director of national register programs for the texas historical commission
but it does ensure that documentation will exist for posterity showing that allen parkway was here and that it was important in the history of houston, of texas and of the nation.''
steely said texas preservationists will work with the advisory council on historic preservation, an independent agency set up by the federal government, to monitor the spending of any federal funds on allen parkway. him</head>
a man has been charged with shooting his wife to death two months after she asked prosecutors to treat him leniently on charges that he had wounded her, officials said
linda joyce hubert, 26, was found dead in her apartment thursday shortly after neighbors heard several shots and saw a man get into a car and speed away
kenneth leon hubert, 27, surrendered to police a few hours later and was charged with murder. he was ordered held without bond
homicide sgt. jerry novak said hubert surrendered after hearing he was being sought and that hubert insisted he is innocent
hubert had been free on $5,000 bond on an attempted murder charge in the dec. 18 wounding of his wife, and on $2,000 bond on a charge of kidnapping his girlfriend in november
ms. hubert asked prosecutors for leniency and said she would not testify against her husband about the dec. 18 shooting
she wanted us to offer the guy probation,'' assistant harris county district attorney mike anderson said. ``we contacted her and she said: `oh, no, he just needs help. i don't want to prosecute unless he'll get help instead of prison time.'''
she seemed very forgiving,'' he added
the huberts had been separated for about three years. a neighbor said hubert often drove by the apartment where ms. hubert lived with her two sons, ages 2 and 9
i thought the husband was a boyfriend trying to make up with her, because he was always coming around harassing her,'' ola aubrey said. ``he would come every day and stay in that car and blow his horn. she would just stay inside. she would never let him in her apartment.''
anderson said he had two other cases this week in which women injured by their husbands refused to testify against them
rhonda gerson, director of aid to victims of domestic violence, a non-profit agency in houston that offers legal information and services, said various things influence a woman's decision not to testify against her husband
she may feel that she's the one sending him to jail, rather than his own behavior,'' ms. gerson said. ``or she doesn't want the father of her children in prison
sometimes, there is a lot of fear and intimidation'' from the husband not to testify, she added. or, a woman may be hoping to reconcile with the husband and doesn't want to make matters worse by testifying against him
or she may be afraid of what's going to happen when he comes out (of prison),'' said ms. gerson, who was not involved in ms. hubert's case
a hot-air balloon billed as the world's largest strained into the air carrying as many as 60 people at a time friday in a bid for the record books, even though it was firmly tethered to the ground
the balloon, the super maine, is bigger even than the virgin atlantic flyer hot-air balloon which crossed the atlantic last summer
it was immense, it was incredible,'' said gary lovell, who flew a regular-sized hot-air balloon alongside the super maine. ``it was very impressive being in the air next to something that large and be a fellow balloon. i've had 747s go overhead before; this would dwarf that.''
the super maine, 10 to 20 percent larger in volume than the flyer, established its flying ability by rising 50 feet off frozen sebago lake with 25 people aboard. it remained aloft, tethered to ropes, for about five minutes while 100 or so balloon enthusiasts watched
everything's come together almost perfectly, ... we're very happy,'' project coordinator and chief pilot tom handcock said after the flight, which he hoped would earn an entry in the guinness book of records
you can only do so much with good planning and a lot of it is up to mother nature, and mother nature cooperated,'' he added
after the initial flight, organizers took the balloon up several more times, adding more and more people to its 8-by-12-foot gondola. at one point, 60 people were in the basket, with one man hanging onto the side while the balloon lifted off the ground a few feet, said one organizer, ruth ludwig
the virgin atlantic flyer carried crew members richard branson and per linstrand 2,789.6 miles from carrabassett valley, maine, to a brief touchdown in ireland last july
the designers, builders and supporters of the 210-foot-high, 168-foot-wide super maine simply wanted to construct a balloon that was larger in volume than the flyer. the super maine was built to hold 2.6 million cubic feet of hot air, between 300,000 and 500,000 cubic feet more than the 195-foot-high flyer, handcock said
lovell said he could fit 40 regular-sized balloons, which are the size of two or three tractor-trailer trucks, inside the super maine
the balloonists could not release the ropes holding the craft to the ground because organizers did not complete federal aviation administration paperwork in time to launch a free flight
no one seemed to mind
the thing went great. we wish we could have flown it away, but our good old government wasn't into that,'' said brian boland, a burlington, conn., resident who has designed and flown hot-air balloons for 17 years
the champagne corks are poppin' left and right,'' boland said in a post-flight telephone interview from a nearby bar. ``it's an incredible thing. everybody's just glowing.''
the balloon and gondola, which cost a total of $7,000, were built with the help of volunteers, mainly commercial balloon pilots from new england, kentucky, maryland and canada. they assembled the balloon in four days last month in a massachusetts warehouse and trucked it to maine
handcock said he probably will not attempt to assemble the balloon again for another launch, citing the time and work involved, but offered to permit other pilots with the skill and knowledge required to give it a try
we (did) it mostly for our personal pleasure _ just to say we flew the largest balloon in the world,'' he said. ``i know that doesn't make sense. but it's a long winter up here.''
president reagan named former cabinet secretaries caspar weinberger and drew lewis on friday to a commission charged with seeking ways to reduce the federal budget deficit
completing the makeup of the bipartisan panel, senate republican leader bob dole and house republican leader robert michel also appointed members. democrats announced their members late last year
dole chose sen. pete domenici, r-n.m., ranking republican on the senate budget committee, and dean kleckner, president of the american farm bureau federation
michel selected rep. bill frenzel, r-minn., a member of the house ways and means committee, and donald rumsfeld, a former defense secretary and congressmen who also served as director of the office of economic oportunity and as white house chief of staff under president ford
the panel, known as the national economic commission, is supposed to issue a report on march 1, 1989, after reagan has left office
lewis, now the head of union pacific corp., was reagan's first secretary of transportation. weinberger was reagan's secretary of defense for seven years
in a statement announcing the appointments, the president said, ``i believe when all aspects of the budget are reviewed the primary policy problem will be viewed not as a lack of revenues, but an inexorable growth in spending
over the last seven years, revenues have increased by $250 billion but spending has increased by $325 billion,'' he said
and while defense has necessarily grown, it accounted for only $125 billion, or less than 40 percent of the increase.''
president reagan defended his tax and budget policies friday in an election-year economic report to congress, saying his administration had turned economic despair into hope
reagan's seventh annual economic report brushed off accusations by democratic presidential candidates that a $2.4 trillion national debt and record trade imbalances during the reagan years had hobbled the country and eventually would reduce americans' standard of living
beryl sprinkel, the president's chief economic adviser, said the new economic report was aimed at debunking ``myths'' that the country had become a second-rate economic power
he said that in reality the united states had out-performed the rest of the world, producing 2{ times the number of jobs as the other top six industrialized countries combined since the end of the 1981-82 recession
the president, in an eight-page introduction to this year's report, said the country is in a lot better shape than when he took office seven years ago
it is hard to believe that at the beginning of the 1980s, the prevailing attitude toward the economy could best be described as despair,'' the president said. ``inflation and interest rates had ratcheted higher with each successive business cycle and ... the goal of sustainable growth appeared increasingly elusive.''
in a theme sure to be sounded by the eventual republican presidential nominee, the report asserted, ``the past five years of sustained and vigorous growth in production, income and employment did not occur by accident. they were shaped by government policies explicitly directed toward fostering the inherent dynamism of the private sector.''
the report sought to downplay any problems associated with the doubling of the national debt under reagan and the string of foreign trade deficits that has transformed the united states from the largest creditor country to the largest debtor nation
the country's debt to the rest of the world stands at around $400 billion, the amount of foreign holdings in the united states that exceed american investments in other countries
sprinkel, in a briefing for reporters, said that the net payments to foreigners needed to service the country's foreign debt represented just 0.1 percent of the $4.6 trillion u.s. economy
disaster does not loom in our future. this current level of (international) indebtedness is not worrisome,'' he said. ``the argument that we can't grow and make economic progress because we are debt-ridden is wrong.''
sprinkel said that the recent string of three consecutive declines in the index of leading indicators was signaling slower growth in the first half of 1988 but not a recession this year
he also discounted recent big declines in housing construction in december and january, a key economic sector that is often the first to turn down at the start of a new recession
sprinkel blamed the housing declines on a too-restrictive monetary policy being pursued by the federal reserve in the months before the record collapse of stock prices that occured last oct. 19
sprinkel said by late spring construction should start rising again in response to recent declines in mortgage rates, which have now dipped back to single-digit levels, falling to 9.84 percent last week
a draft version of the president's economic report was critical of the federal reserve for tightening credit conditions in december, after initially pumping money into the economy immediately following the stock market crash
however, the final version of the report said that more recent actions of the fed this year indicate the central bank is again promoting lower interest rates as a way of stimulating economic growth
sprinkel said he was now satisfied with the fed's performance, calling their action in the past six weeks ``quite appropriate.''
the economic report claimed that significant progress has been made in reducing both the budget and trade deficits and predicted further gains on both fronts
sprinkel predicted that an improving trade deficit would provide about half of the country's overall economic growth this year, which the administration is forecasting will slow to a 2.4 percent, as measured by the gross national product. that is down from 3.8 percent in 1987
the president repeated his warnings that congress should not try to reduce the trade deficit by passing either of the omnibus trade bills now being considered by a house-senate conference committee
reagan said unless the measures were substantially modified he would veto the legislation because of objectionable protectionist provisions
the president also repeated his pledge, made in his state of the union address, to veto another 11th-hour, catchall spending bill such as the one passed by congress last december
in a chapter on airline deregulation, the report maintained that consumers are reaping a $15 billion annual windfall in lower fares. it said that while a 28 percent increase in the number of flights had raised concerns about safety, accidents had declined steadily since 1978
the ohio supreme court unveiled a continuing legal education program thursday that would require some 35,000 attorneys in the state to head back to school to keep their licenses
chief justice thomas moyer said the new rule, adopted unanimously by the high court, requires every attorney to complete 24 hours of legal education every two years beginning in 1990
lawyers who fail to comply could be faced with fines of up to $500 and even suspension from practice
ohio is the 30th state to adopt such a program, which moyer said would maintain and improve the quality of legal services
let me say that this is not a panacea,'' moyer said at a news conference. ``... but what it means is that we are making a minimum effort to assure people who use the services of lawyers that the lawyer they employ has been required to stay current.''
the rule was developed in cooperation with several state attorney groups. representatives of four of them who joined moyer at the briefing welcomed the court's action
joseph cook of akron, president of the ohio state bar association, said the requirement would not be a burden to most attorneys: ``most laywers have already been getting more (continuing education) than the rule requires.''
he said attorneys probably could meet their yearly requirements by attending seminars sponsored by the state bar at its annual meeting
the rule establishes, effective july 1, a supreme court commission on continuing legal education that will administer and accredit the programs
the program will be financed by a $15 filing fee. prisoner</head>
two convicted killers testified friday as character witnesses for a fellow convict trying to avoid the death penalty, telling the jury that the man lent them money and aided them with other acts of kindness
james ernest hitchcock, 31, was convicted and sentenced to death for the 1976 rape-murder of his 13-year-old stepniece, cynthia driggers. the u.s. supreme court ordered a new sentencing hearing last april
inmates darrell edwin hoy and arthur rutherford, wearing solid blue prison uniforms, were brought into the courtroom in chains and handcuffs that were removed before the jury was seated
the short, stocky rutherford, 38, awaiting death in the electric chair for a 1986 murder in santa rosa county, said hitchcock helped him upon rutherford's arrival on death row by lending him money to buy tobacco and other items
hoy, soft-voiced and polite, said he and hitchcock had side-by-side cells on death row for three years in the early 1980s and that hitchcock had given him his radio after hoy's was stolen, that he had lent him money and had helped him study to get a general education degree
on the death penalty, hoy said, ``i feel that's wrong for certain reasons, if i may say so.''
hoy was convicted in pinellas county of raping a teen-ager in front of her fiance and then shooting and killing them both. his sentence was overturned, and he was removed from death row in 1984
asked by prosecutor belvin perry for his views on the death penalty, rutherford sat up straight, crossed his arms, raised his voice and replied, ``i'm in florida state prison on hearsay _ no evidence, no nothin' ... i'm against it.''
extraordinary security measures were in place at the orange county courthouse, where a shootout several years ago left one bailiff dead and three people wounded, including the gunman
among the 50 courtroom spectators were 10 armed deputies in civilian clothes. another dozen uniformed and armed guards accompanied the prisoners or were posted at the front and sides of the courtroom
defense lawyers had argued for the appearance of the present and former death row prisoners because hitchcock had spent a third of his life on death row
circuit judge gary formet told attorneys he would not permit them to disclose the nature of the prisoners' crimes
hitchcock spent more than a decade in a cell just a few feet from florida's electric chair before his sentence was overturned
the 12 jurors are getting a shortened version of trial testimony and then hearing more than 20 witnesses testify for and against hitchcock in his effort to escape the chair. the jury's recommendation _ life or death _ is only advisory to the judge
one of hitchcock's two public defenders, robert wesley, told the jury in his opening remarks that the defendant's brother, richard _ the victim's stepfather _ beat and strangled the girl after he found hitchcock and the girl having sex
wesley said his client ``is not saying he is innocent. ... he participated in the crime. but he asks to live his life in prison.''
richard hitchcock took the witness stand earlier and denied that he killed his stepdaughter
the jury also heard a tape-recorded confession by james hitchcock in which he admitted raping and killing the girl. he later recanted the confession, claiming it was given under duress because he was held for four days in solitary confinement
stars and searchlights added a touch of hollywood to friday's opening of the first-ever american film festival here, but a clutter of ticket-seekers and security men lent the event a distinctive soviet air
more than 30 major american films are to be shown in seven moscow and leningrad theaters through march 2, ranging from the 1939 classic fantasy ``the wizard of oz'' to last year's sensitive portrayal of a deaf woman learning survival in ``children of a lesser god.''
actor richard gere, puppeteer jim hensen, actress daryl hannah and a cast of other hollywood figures added to the glitter attracting mobs of muscovites to the floodlit rossiya theater
i love all american films. they're great,'' said 37-year-old ina pozdnyakova, as she stood outside the theater pleading each passerby for the chance to buy a spare ticket. she didn't even know what film was to be shown
asked whether the ticket distribution system is fair, she snapped back: ``absolutely not.''
the festival was announced in this week's edition of leisure time in moscow, but the times and theaters where specific films were to be shown have not been made public
guides listing the films, participating theaters, guests and workshops were released only hours before the opening and only for organizers and foreign visitors
other films to be shown during the festival include ``a chorus line,'' ``an officer and a gentleman,'' ``singin' in the rain'' and ``king's row,'' a 1942 film regarded as ronald reagan's best
nearly every western cultural offering in moscow draws overflow crowds, though the festivals and concerts are given little, if any, publicity in the state-run press
the well-developed gossip grapevine and an entrenched system of favor-trading ensure that connections far outweigh currency in securing entrance to a popular event
festival spokesman peter fleischer said fair distribution of tickets for the films, selected by the private american groups and entertainers who organized the festival, had been agreed to by the soviets
fleischer said he was led to believe about 50 percent of the tickets went to the general public, but said the americans had no control over ticket sales
of course we can't satisfy all those who want tickets,'' said alexander i. kamshalov, head of the soviet state committee on cinematography, serving as host for the festival
in the minus 5-degree chill outside the rossiya, alyona narishkina shivered and stamped her feet
sure you can get tickets through your work enterprise, if they happen to get any and you manage to find out in time,'' ms. narishkina, a lawyer who waited for more than an hour friday night for tickets to ``roxanne.''
circling among the ticket-seekers were a handful of young men who had bought up some of the $2.60 tickets from those with extras
they conducted a brisk business reselling them for about three times the price to the film buffs. the scalpers moved about warily, avoiding the gaze of plainclothes policemen always stationed where crowds assemble
a sign outside the rossiya gave no indication when tickets for other films would be on sale, but assured would-be buyers that 45 percent of the seats are sold in public kiosks. half are distributed to unspecified enterprises and 5 percent are reserved for decorated heroes, war veterans and invalids, the sign explained
those with tickets for the opening night film were more supportive of the current system
you can always find out what is playing if you want to,'' explained slava belyankin, an 18-year-old student. ``you just have to be patient.''
