geovani azevedo, federal police spokesman in rio de janeiro, told the associated press, ``if we discover foreign investigators working on this case, we will expell them. this includes fbi agents.''
on thursday it was revealed that two canvas sacks containing $4 million each in u.s. currency were separated from a shipment of 13 such bags. the bags were being flown from new york to buenos aires, aregentina and contained a total of $52 million
central bank officials said the money was being sent by the united states to help argentina pay foreign bonds but that it was insured and the loss wouldn't hurt argentina
the bags were loaded as personal baggage on a varig flight out of kennedy international airport on feb. 5 and arrived at rio's international airport, where they were to be transferred to another varig flight to buenos aires
varig is brazil's national carrier, but brink's, the u.s.-based security company, was imn charge of the shipment
varig said a passenger known only as mr. denisco paid standard overweight charges for the bags and that brink's was in charge of transfering them from one plane to another in the airplane parking area at rio's international airport
the baggage never entered the terminal. brink's was entirely responsible for the operation,'' a varig communique said
brazil's federal police chief, romeu tuma, said thursday night, ``there obviously was a security failure.'' he said he also wanted to know ``why we only heard about this disappearance two weeks later.''
the money came from the u.s. federal reserve bank in new york. the other $44 million arrived safely in buenos aires
a 21-year-old sailor whose cargo boat overturned in the caribbean sea survived eight days floating on a raft with shipmates who suffered a ``psychosis'' and bit him, authorities said
the sailor's eight shipmates died
authorities said an unidentified west german vessel brought the sailor, jorge eliezer torres mejias, to puerto rico wednesday after rescuing him earlier this week
torres mejias was released thursday from puerto rico's medical center and was turned over to teresa berardinelli, colombia's consular officer in puerto rico
torres mejias was not available for an interview, despite several attempts to reach him at the colombian diplomatic office in san juan
details of what happened tothe sailor are sketchy. the u.s. coast guard office in san juan could only confirm that torres mejias had been brought to puerto rico and had received medical attention
dr. carlos gomez marcial, medical director at the puerto rico medical center, said torres mejias told him that he and the eight others left barranquilla, colombia, for another coastal town carrying a load of food on a cargo vessel, the marlon david. the craft overturned about 10 miles offshore and the nine boarded a raft
gomez marcial said ``apparently his eight friends suffered a general psychosis and they started to bite him.'' he quoted the young man as saying some threw themselves into the ocean and drowned. others died aboard the raft and he had to push the bodies overboard
the german ship spotted him at sea and rescued him
torres mejias suffered bite wounds on his arm and right hand, according to the doctor. he also suffered from dehydration and severe sunburn. reference to security concerns. deletes redundant material below pickup.</note>
pope john paul ii on friday blamed the rivalry between east and west for social and economic ills in the third world and delivered a sweeping indictment of totalitarianism, materialism and the ``all-consuming desire for profit.''
in his seventh encyclical, the pope accused both the u.s.- and soviet-led blocs of imposing ``imperialism'' and ``structures of sin'' on developing nations, reducing them to ``cogs on a gigantic wheel.''
he also said the rivalry between the east and west was main reason for the widening gap between rich and poor countries
an unacceptably exaggerated concern for security ... deadens the impulse toward united cooperation by all,'' he said
this obsession, he said, works to ``the detriment especially of peaceful peoples who are impeded from their rightful access to the goods meant for all.''
the encyclical called for reform of the international financial system and said the church could do its part by selling its ``superfluous'' goods to help the poor
the 102-page document also called for democratic political change in nations with corrupt, dictatorial or authoritarian governments
the pope said the church took a critical view of both liberal capitalism and marxist collectivism, saying both systems are imperfect and in need of urgent ``radical correction.''
the encyclical, titled in latin ``sollicitudo rei socialis,'' or the social concern of the church, included some of the strongest statements on social and economic issues made by john paul during his 9{ years as pope
an encyclical is a formal pastoral letter written by the pope for the entire church. while encyclicals are not infallible pronouncements, catholics are expected to heed the message
the pope said his letter was addressed to all followers of the world's great religions
the letter painted a bleak picture of the process of development since the publication of pope paul vi's encyclical ``development of peoples'' in 1967
twenty years later, hopes for development ``appear very far from being realized,'' and for many poor people ``the situation has noticeably worsened,'' john paul said
a vatican official familiar with the drafting of the encyclical said it reflected the pope's polish background and addressed issues facing people living in the soviet bloc that were not raised in paul vi's document
breaking new ground, john paul singled out east-west rivalry as the cause of many of the world's problems
the conflicts ... between east and west (are) an important cause of the retardation or stagnation of the south,'' he wrote. ``the developing countries, instead of becoming autonomous nations concerned with their own progress ... become parts of a machine, cogs on a gigantic wheel.''
the present division of the world,'' the document added, ``is a direct obstacle to the real transformation of the conditions of underdevelopment in the developing and less advanced countries.''
world peace is inconceivable unless the world's leaders come to recognize that interdependence in itself demands the abandonment of the politics of blocs, the sacrifice of all forms of economic, military or political imperialism, and the transformation of mutual distrust into collaboration.''
in an apparent reference to conditions in his native poland, the pope complained of the suppression of economic initiative, which leads people to emigrate, and the denial of political and economic sovereignty in some countries
condemning totalitarianism, he said, ``no social group, for example a political party, has the right to usurp the role of sole leader.''
the pope said the church itself should avoid accumulating ``superfluous church oranments and costly furnishings for divine worship.''
on the contrary it could be obligatory to sell these goods in order to provide food, drink, clothing and shelter for those who lack these things,'' he said
cadinal roger etchegary said the statement was mainly symbolic, recalling the time john paul gave away his pastoral ring during a trip to brazil. etchegary, president of the vatican's justice and peace commission, spoke at a news conference
the pope lamented the overemphasis on economic development, writing, ``development which is merely economic ... will end by enslaving (mankind) further.''
the document denounced the phenomenon of ``superdevelopment,'' or the excessive availability of material goods in some areas that makes people ``slaves of possession.''
it also condemned ``all-consuming desire for profit'' and ``thirst for power'' that afflicts both individuals and nations
if certain forms of modern imperialism were considered ... we would see that hidden behind certain decisions, apparently inspired only by economics or politics, are real forms of idolatry: of money, ideology, class, technology.'' plan</head>
congress' chief budget writers said friday that president reagan's conciliatory spending plan for fiscal 1989 should make for the least contentious and most bipartisan session since he took office
as he goes out the door, his last budget does what he railed against for seven years,'' house budget committee chairman william h. gray iii, d-pa., said, citing the restraints on defense spending and increases in many domestic programs in the $1.1 trillion plan
reagan actually will prepare one more budget just before leaving office, although the next president will take over and put his stamp on it
gray said in an interview that this reagan budget was so much less hostile than his past efforts, some lawmakers were unsettled
people are so used to a set pattern ... battle lines drawn and grenades thrown,'' he said. they look at reagan's new plan and say, ``something is wrong here. ... what's going on?''
at a hearing of the senate budget committee, lawmakers questioned white house budget director james c. miller iii about the optimism behind reagan's projection of a $129.5 billion deficit in the fiscal year beginning oct. 1
all the hot-wired calculators in the country won't hide the fact that the deficits are still high, and the national debt is a monster,'' said committee chairman sen. lawton chiles, d-fla
miller assured lawmakers that the administration would work with congress this year. if official estimates due in august show the deficit is above the $146 billion threshold for automatic spending cuts under the gramm-rudman law, the white house will cooperate in solving the problem, miller said
chiles and others complimented the administration on the budget priorities, although making clear some changes will be made
after eight years, it looks like you've finally seen the light on education, drug enforcement, health and the environment,'' chiles said, noting increases in those areas
we're about ready to welcome you to the ranks of the faithful, even though you have a few more things to learn _ like how to restore the two-thirds you cut from programs to help the homeless,'' he said
sen. pete v. domenici, r-n.m., senior republican on the panel, said the president's plan ``set a formula for congress to act quickly on the budget and appropriations.''
if ever there was a year we could complete our work on time, it's this year,'' he said
the primary reason the president's budget is closer to congress' priorities is because of the deficit reduction pact reagan struck with congressional leaders last fall. the agreement set overall figures for pentagon, domestic and foreign aid spending in fiscal years 1988 and 1989
what we're doing now is the second stage'' of the agreement, gray said. ``the whole debate now is going to be over the small details of the domestic part'' of the budget, he said
gray said he would expect congress to add money back to the urban programs reagan wanted to cut, such as mass transit and housing
rep. charles rangel, the chairman of the house narcotics committee, said friday he was ``obliged to acknowledge that president reagan ... appears to be moving off the fence with respect to this country's drug crisis'' by asking for a 13 percent increase in those efforts
but the new york democrat criticized the package for not including money to help state and local governments with their drug eradication efforts. description of ibarruri.</note>
spanish communists opened their 12th congress friday amid uncertainty over who would lead the party out of its worst crisis since it returned to legal political activity 11 years ago
secretary general gerardo iglesias, a 43-year-old miner, has made it clear he will step down this year as head of the party that is fighting for its political life
fierce internal squabbling and poor electoral showings have caused a sharp decline in voter support and membership, party spokesman and political analysts say
the communist-oriented united left coalition holds only seven of the 350 seats in the spanish parliament, down from the 20 seats the communists held nlone after general elections in 1979
the party suffered another defeat with the announcement by julio anguita, leader of communists in southern andalucia, that he had made ``an irrevocable decision'' not to accept iglesia's job if nominated
both iglesias and 92-year-old honorary party president dolores ibarruri, the legendary ``la pasionaria'' who became a symbol of loyalist resistance to franco forces during the civil war in the 1930s, called on the 619 party delegates to work for greater unity among communists to face the current crisis
this congress should and can put an end to any hint of confusion, confirming the political unity and internal democracy of the spanish communist party,'' iglesias said in his opening speech friday
he $dded that the party had managed to overcome ``the most difficult problems, including the real threat of disappearing altogether.''
acco,ding to political scientist ramon garcia cotarelo, the lack of a clear-cut choice of a leader to replace iglesias was a sign that the party's top echelons had no confidence in the party's future
he said it would not be clear who the new party chief would be until sunday when party delegates choose the new 90-member central committee, and it elects a new secretary general
data made public friday showed that from its peak in 1979 through its sharp decline to 1983, the party lost 65 percent of its membership or 120,000 people. as the crisis deepened after 1985, membership has further declined from 67,400 to 62,300
in its heyday, the party was at the forefront of the eurocommunism movement, which advocated independence from the soviet union and democratic elections
the current imbroglio stems from iglesia's replacement of historic spanish communist leader santiago carrillo at the 11th congress in december 1983, after carrillo resigned following the party's electoral debacle in 1982 general elections
carrillo, 73, headed the party from 1960 to 1982 and was a main proponent of eurocommunism. he led the spanish party in its clandestine years from exile in paris and after it was legalized in 1977, two years after the death of gen. francisco franco ended the 36-year military dictatorship
the party reached its zenith in 1979 when it got 10 percent of the vote. but in the 1982 general elections the socialist party headed by prime minister felipe gonzalez swept into power with a landslide victory, while the communists got only 3.8 percent of the ballots
the debacle led to carrillo's resignation and the ascendance of iglesias, his young protege
but when iglesias attempted to move the party away from its base among the working class to weave together emerging non-communist social movements such as pacifists and ecologists, the two leaders clashed
in 1985, the party ousted carrillo and many of his followers
attempts in the last two years to overcome their differences and to bring carillo and his supporters back into the fold have failed, costing the party prestige and votes, garcia cotarelo said
comedian jonathan winters has been admitted to st. francis hospital following what was described as a bad fall, and is expected to remain there until saturday
winters, 62, who lives in santa barbara, was admitted to the hospital thursday afternoon. no further details were provided as to what caused the fall, where it occurred or what type of injuries he suffered
a statement from winters' wife, issued through the hospital, said simply that the comedian ``had suffered a bad fall and was doing well'' and was expected to be home saturday
delivering mail to cluster boxes instead of to the door or a curbside mailbox saves the postal service more than $11 million annually, the general accounting office reported friday
cluster boxes are centralized mailbox groupings used in many apartment and townhouse developments, and some new residential areas. they allow letter carriers to deliver mail for several homes at one spot, saving time on their rounds
the gao, which does investigations for congress, studied the use of the boxes at the request of reps. william d. ford, d-mich., mickey leland, d-texas, and robert garcia, d-n.y
the report covered fiscal 1985, when about 1.9 million of the 53 million daily city mail deliveries involved cluster boxes
according to the study, in areas of detached homes, delivering mail to a cluster box instead of to a curbside mailbox saved about $10 per customer, for a saving of $4.5 million
in townhouse sections, the postal service saved about $11 per customer by delivering to clusterboxes instead of to mailboxes located by the door of the home. that netted a saving of $6.9 million, the report said
for low-rise apartment buildings, the cost of delivering to a cluster box was about the same as bringing mail to a group of boxes in the lobby
the parents of convicted spy jonathan j. pollard said friday that navy investigators showed him a list of names of 25 american jews and asked him to identify those who helped him commit espionage for israel
they kept badgering him to indicate which of those on the list was involved in the spy plot,'' said morris pollard, a professor of microbiology at the university of notre dame
both the senior pollard and his son denied that jonathan pollard had an accomplice in spying for israel. their statement came after the washington post reported friday that government investigators had concluded that someone in the cia or defense department also had spied for israel
justice department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there are differing views within the department on the question of whether there is another spy. while there appear to be some solid indications that there was another operative, some officials have doubts about whether that is the case, said the sources
neither the navy nor the justice department or its bureau of prisons had any immediate comment on the pollards' charges
we can neither confirm nor deny this,'' said lt. janet mescus, a spokesman for the navy. ``at this point, we have no comment.''
justice department spokesman terry eastland also declined comment
the post story, by reporters bob woodward and walter pincus, quoted unidentified sources as saying government investigators have dubbed the alleged second spy ``mr. x.''
but jonathan pollard, a former civilian intelligence analyst for the navy who was sentenced in march to life in prison, said he knew of no ``mr. x.'' he admitted selling american defense secrets to israel over a period of 15 months until his arrest in november 1985 outside the israeli embassy in washington
his wife, anne henderson-pollard, was sentenced to five years in prison for helping him
i gave no information suggesting the existence of a mr. x in government,'' pollard said in a statement he telephoned from prison to his mother, who conveyed it to the associated press. under a plea-bargaining agreement, pollard is not allowed direct contact with the news media
this was confirmed by nine months of polygraphing. having said that, i obviously have no knowledge of whether any other person or persons was helping israel,'' the statement said
pollards' parents said their son had been held in a psychiatric ward at the federal prison in springfield, mo., for 10 months as navy investigators tried to force him to implicate others
pollard's parents said the authorities hoped to ``break'' their son by surrounding him with mental patients. his attorney, richard hibey, said, however, he believed the idea was to keep him in protected surroundings to prevent him rom revealing national security secrets
george diffenbaucher, head of the penitentiary's social services department, said pollard was assigned to the diagnostic and observation unit, a psychological evaluation and treatment unit. he said pollard was not ``a mental patient'' but ``there are other considerations for keeping him there.''
hibey said the prosecutors had told him they were satisfied that pollard had told them all he knew about the affair during nine months of polygraph exams and debriefings
no evidence has been developed yet that points to the specific identity of a second person, the post said, citing unidentified sources for its information
pollard's mother, molly pollard, said that when a list of 25 names was shown to him and he was told they were prominent members of the american jewish community, he recognized only one name. she did not know what that name was
in the prison mental ward, pollard is ``surrounded by demented, screaming people'' in a cell that measures six by nine feet, his father charged. ``they hoped to break him,'' he said. diffenbaucher, asked if that charge was true, said, ``of course not. break him of what?''
the prison authorities ``told us they were upset with his being in a mental ward. they said it was like kgb tactics,'' said the father. ``but they also said they could not do anything about it because they had orders from the navy to keep him there.''
morris pollard wrote to rep. lee hamilton, d-ind., asking him to intercede on his son's behalf
an aide in hamilton's office, who asked not to be identified, said the congressman promised he would try to help. ``he felt pollard should not be discriminated against compared with other prisoners,'' the aide said
in his statement, pollard said the post based its report on claims by justice department officials ``who could not prove the existence of such a person on the basis of fact. so now, they are simply inventing him or her out of thin air and hoping to give their spectral image an air of substance.''
the post said the belief that a mr. x must exist grew out of a massive debriefing and polygraphing of pollard over many months
pollard told authorities that his israeli handlers often specified by date and control number the highly sensitive u.s. documents they wanted him to acquire, the newspaper said
the handlers once showed pollard a top-secret u.s. document to which he did not have access, the post said. it identified the document as an index or catalog that pollard then could use to obtain other documents from u.s. intelligence agencies
investigators concluded that another american _ ``mr. x'' _ had provided that index and other specific information on u.s. secrets that pollard learned from his israeli handlers, the newspaper said
madame chiang kai-shek made a brief visit friday to the mausoleum of president chiang ching-kuo, her stepson who died last month at the age of 77, the official news agency reported
the 86-year-old madame chiang, accompanied by unidentified family members, prayed in silence before chiang's bronze coffin at the tahsi mausoleum in a small rural town 30 miles southwest of taipei, the central news agency reported
the news agency said madame chiang made her first visit to the mausoleum shortly after she visited the mausoleum of generalissimo chiang kai-shek, the late president's father who died in 1975
the two mausoleums are a little more than a mile apart
madame chiang did not attend her stepson's funeral on jan. 30, three days after newspapers linked her to an unsuccessful last-ditch effort to delay newly installed president lee teng-hui from being appointed head of the ruling nationalist party
chiang ching-kuo had tapped lee as his successor
madame chiang, who is chairman of the ruling party's central advisory committee, also did not appear at earlier memorial services for chiang ching-kuo
she left taiwan for a mansion on long island in new york soon after her husband's death, reportedly because of difference in opinion with her stepson. she returned in 1986 to attend ceremonies marking the late generalissimo's 100th birthday
yuri ovchinnikov, a leading soviet biologist and vice president of the country's prestigious academy of sciences, has died at the age of 53, it was reported friday
ovchinnikov died wednesday after an unspecified ``grave and long illness,'' the official news agency tass said
he led research into the creation of gene-engineering interferons, insulin, and other medical preparations, and he was chairman of the federation of european biochemical societies, tass said
in addition to his position in the academy of sciences, ovchinnikov was an alternate member of the communist party's central committee and a member of the presidium of the russian republic's supreme soviet, or parliament. lifting of syrian sanction; subs pvs 10th graf, ``another u.s.,'' to delete outdated matter</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz ``most likely'' will visit syria when he goes to the middle east next week and is leaving his options open for a return to the region after a nato summit meeting in early march, u.s. officials said friday
as shultz set out for moscow on a trip in which he will seek soviet backing for his peace-making venture, his mideast journey was taking on dramatic new proportions
shultz's purpose in going to damascus would be to discuss the u.s. drive for arab-israeli negotiations with president hafez assad, whose support for any long-term settlement in the middle east is considered essential by specialists in the state department's near east bureau
reinforcing the impression that u.s.-syrian relations are warming was a disclosure friday by state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley that one of several sanctions the united states has imposed against syria has been ended
she said security clearance requirements on syrian applicants for u.s. visas have been lifted. under the sanction, all such applicants had been subjected to lengthy background checks to qualify for a visa
a visit by shultz to damascus would be a major prestige boost to syria and mark an improvement in its relations with the united states. the country is one of six listed by the state department as a supporter of terrorism, and president reagan imposed sanctions against it in november 1986
in that action, reagan banned the sale of sophisticated technology, such as computers, aircraft and related spare parts; ended the financing of exports to syria by the u.s. export-import bank; canceled the u.s.-syrian air transport agreement; reduced the u.s. embassy staff in damascus and pressured american oil companies to halt their operations in syria
the state department had linked syria to some 40 incidents of terrorism. reagan said the sanctions were intended to express ``outrage'' at what he called syria's involvement in international terrorism _ charges the syrians denied
among the punitive measures was a ban on high-level meetings with syrians. but shultz sent richard w. murphy, the head of the near east bureau, to damascus two weeks ago to confer with assad
u.s. ambassador william eagleton was sent back to his post in damascus last september, after a year's absence, and u.n. ambassador vernon a. walters also visited the country
a u.s. official, who demanded anonymity, said shultz was ``most likely'' to schedule a stop in syria on his trip to the middle east beginning next thursday
another official said shultz was ``leaving his options open'' to return to the area for a few days in early march
shultz plans to be in brussels with reagan for a summit meeting of the north atlantic treaty organization on march 2-3. but the official said shultz could go to the middle east from there if needed and then return to washington in time to greet visiting the chinese foreign minister on march 7
shultz's other stops next week will be egypt, jordan, israel and probably saudi arabia. he is trying to set up negotiations between israel and a mixed delegation of jordanians and palestinians to deal especially with the troubled west bank and gaza
the immediate aim is some form of self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinian arabs who have lived under israeli control since egypt and jordan lost the territories in the 1967 six-day war
the long-range goal is to hold a second stage of talks _ possibly in the format of an international peace conference _ by the end of the year to consider an overall settlement
shultz's separate trip to the soviet union began friday with a flight to helsinki, finland. he will be in moscow for talks sunday with foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze and monday with shevardnadze and general secretary mikhail s. gorbachev
shultz is due to report to the nato countries in brussels on tuesday and return home for a brief rest before heading for the middle east
the middle east is one topic on the shultz's agenda for moscow. so is afghanistan, where gorbachev said he would begin a withdrawal of the red army over 10 months, beginning may 15, if a settlement is reached by march 15
shultz said thursday in a telecast to asia that he would ask for a timetable with ``definite proportions.'' he warned that u.s. aid to the afghan rebels would end only if the soviets stopped helping the kabul government
the afghan rebels have been at war with the kabul government since 1973. the soviets sent about 120,000 troops into the country to back the government in december 1979
shultz supported the establishment of an interim government, which pakistan has demanded before an agreement on a soviet troop withdrawal is signed. that would mean a coalition government acceptable to the guerrillas and to the afghan refugees, about 3 million of whom are in pakistan
in discussing the middle east in a separate voice of america interview, shultz indicated he was prepared to accept an active role for the soviets in the search for a settlement of the arab-israeli dispute
obviously, the soviet union is a major power, and we will have to see how this whole process develops,'' he said
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir is resisting an active role in the middle east for the soviets, who do not have relations with his country and regularly support arab positions. shultz said on his last trip to jerusalem last october that he agreed with shamir
jordan and egypt, however, are demanding an international peace conference with the soviets participating. parties</head>
the democratic and republican parties will be forced to give serious consideration to the candidacies of jesse jackson and pat robertson despite labels that they are unelectable, says a former presidential candidate
people are saying that the candidates with the largest following, pat robertson and jesse jackson, have the lowest probability of success,'' shirley chisholm told a black history month audience thursday night
but whether you like them or not, their parties will just have to deal with them when the time comes because they'll both bring a large block of delegates to the convention,'' she said
robertson finished second among the republican candidates in the iowa caucuses and fifth in the new hampshire primary. jackson, a democrat, finished fourth in iowa and new hampshire
ms. chisholm, the first black woman ever to win a seat in the house of representatives, became known nationally for her fiery speeches and 1972 campaign for the democratic presidential nomination
she drew a crowd of about 300 people to the university of missouri-kansas city black history month activity on the campus
organizers of vice president george bush's campaign said friday they are confident of carrying massachusetts on super tuesday, but are running as if they're scared
i think it's important that the vice president win all of his six home states,'' ron kaufman, the bush political director for the northeast, told reporters in a wry reference to bush's claim to his massachusetts birth and his links to other states
we feel he'll do well here,'' kaufman said. but he said the campaign has done no polling that would help define ``well,'' and he refused to set a specific goal in the republican voting on march 8
on that day, republicans in 17 states _ most of them in the south _ will vote on their presidential preferences. fifty-two delegates are at stake in massachusetts
political contests are always a challenge,'' said andy card, who was bush's campaign manager in new hampshire, where the vice president won the primary. ``we're going to compete as if we're worried about massachusetts.''
tipper gore told a group of democratic women friday that her husband, tennessee sen. albert gore jr., would open a day care center in the white house if elected president
he must encourage corporations and businesses to respond to this very critical need,'' mrs. gore said during a campaign stop in huntsville
she said the next president must address the issue of working families and their children, and that means a day care center for white house employees
mrs. gore said that because of the increasing number of families with working parents, american society is currently ``placing a burden on our work force and our children.''
addressing about 60 members of the madison county women's democratic club in huntsville, mrs. gore steered clear of her crusade against pornographic rock lyrics and concentrated on family issues
i love rock and roll,'' mrs. gore told reporters after her speech. ``i grew up on it.''
a seven-officer marine corps jury friday acquitted marine cpl. lindsey scott in his second trial on charges he sexually assaulted and tried to kill the wife of a fellow marine in 1983
when the verdict was announced, scott turned to the jury and said, ``thank you, sirs.''
scott's mother screamed three times, ``thank you, jesus.''
later, scott told reporters, ``a weight that has been on my shoulders the last five years has been lifted.''
maj. ron mcneil, the marine prosecutor, said the investigation of the attack was closed
we'll probably never know what happened,'' he said after the verdict. ``after almost five years after the facts, the issue is dead.''
it took the jury 11 hours to reach the verdict on charges of rape, kidnapping, sodomy and attempted murder
scott, 32, of louisville, ky., had been convicted of the same charges in 1983 and sentenced to 30 years in prison. that verdict was overturned july 7 by the u.s. military court of appeals on grounds that scott had not received adequate counsel from his civilian attorney
although scott supporters have alleged racism was involved in the earlier conviction, because he is black and the victim white, scott said his feelings for the marine corps have not changed
the marines are the best fighting force in the world and the best branch of the service. there were six whites and one black on the jury. if it was racially motivated, i would have been convicted,'' scott said
during the 17 days of testimony, the defense attacked the naval investigation service's handling of the crime probe. john leino, one of scott's civilian attorneys, charged that investigators used an improper lineup and manipulated the victim into identifying scott
the defense presented witnesses who said the victim was uncertain when she picked scott from the lineups, and also identified other men as resembling her attacker
mcneil denied the investigation service conspired against scott
the victim positively identified scott as her assailant from the witness stand and picked scott from both a physical lineup and photographic lineup in 1983
also at issue was the testimony of cynthia ausby, a security guard at a woodbridge department store. she testified at the first trial that scott was in the department store, but could not remember the exact date
in the second trial, ms. ausby testified she was certain scott was in the store at the time the victim was attacked the night of april 20, 1983
mcneil said ms. ausby's sudden certainty was not credible, but the defense argued that ms. ausby's recollection was aided 10 months after the crime by her checking of store arrest records
ms. ausby said the records showed she had mistaken scott for a similarly dressed shoplifter she was pursuing the night of the assault. she also was aided by pictures of scott that were better than one shown her before the first trial by an nis agent
the victim of the attack, who now lives with her family in rochester, n.y., testified that she was lured from her off-base apartment by a telephone caller who said a marine would be over to give her a ride to her husband, who had been injured
her husband, another member of scott's battalion, was unhurt. she was driven by her escort to a remote section of the northern virginia base, where she was sexually assaulted, stabbed and left for dead
two other marines found her that night bloodied and dazed and brought her to a base clinic for treatment
buying by the soviets, china and morocco propelled export sales of u.s. wheat to more than twice the four-week average last week, the agriculture department said friday
soybean and sorghum sales also climbed, but corn, barley and cotton fell compared to the four-week average, the department said
wheat sales climbed sharply to 1,178,100 metric tons, primarily because of purchases of 308,500 tons by the soviets, 299,000 by china and 220,800 by morocco, the department said
it said sales of sorghum totaled 347,100 tons, the most in the current marketing year. the increase was attributed primarily to purchases by japan, venezuela and israel
sales of 589,500 tons of soybeans were 56 percent over the previous week's mark and 72 percent above the four-week average. japan was the main purchaser followed by romania, the netherlands and mexico
corn sales fell to 777,400 tons, 14 percent below the previous week and 44 percent lower than the four-week average, despite substantial purchases by japan and south korea. barley sales were down. tunisia purchased all of the 25,000 tons sold last week
the report said cotton sales totaled 55,700 bales, 13 percent below the previous week's mark and 50 percent off from the four week average
rice sales of 23,900 tons were 56 percent above the previous week but 46 percent below the four-week average. trinidad, canada and saudi arabia were the main purchasers
among other commodities, soybean cake and meal sales were up for the week but still well short of the four-week average while soybean oil sales were down. sales of hides and skins were lower for the week but a shade above the four-week average
the head of the president's aids commission said friday he would push for more money to help the food and drug administration review growing numbers of experimental aids drugs
research into aids drugs has been expanding quickly, and fda is reaching the point where ``they will not be able to handle the load and do the kind of regulatory work that's needed'' to make appropriate drugs available to people with aids, retired adm. james d. watkins said
a few tens of millions of dollars would help the fda handle the load, said watkins, chairman of the presidential commission on the human immunodeficiency virus epidemic
the fda approves drugs for marketing and also can allow expanded use of drugs still being tested
adequate money for the fda is very important to conquer acquired immune deficiency syndrome, watkins said in an interview during commission hearings
without such help, the agency might have to divert resources from evaluating other drugs for diseases that affect millions of people, he said
during the hearings, watkins asked fda commissioner frank young to work with the commission in detailing its needs in such areas as personnel and scientific facilities
he told young he wanted the commission to be ``your advocate'' in its report to the president
the needs are growing faster than we were able to calculate,'' young said at the hearing. ``i never thought we'd see this many drugs under development.''
approvals for experiments to try potential aids drugs in humans have soared in recent years, young said. as of jan. 31, he said, the fda approved 45 such applications for drugs to boost the immune system, 35 for chemicals to fight the aids virus, 31 for chemicals to treat infections that accompany aids and four for drugs to fight aids-related cancer
the fda looks at results of such experiments when it decides whether to approve a drug for marketing
while funding for aids research at the national institutes of health has jumped from $135 million in 1986 to $468 million in 1988, the fda's regulatory budget to handle the potential new drugs has gone from $10 million to only $25 million, young said. and private companies do more aids research and request more human experiments than nih does, he said
fifty-five pharmaceutical companies are developing or have developed 77 products aimed at diagnosing, preventing or treating aids, testified gerald mossinghoff, president of the pharmaceutical manufacturers association
i don't want fda to be the bottleneck'' in getting effective drugs to people with aids, young said
earlier testimony friday about use of unapproved aids drugs by some people shows ``a frustration on their part'' about lack of access to approved drugs, watkins said
one witness, michael callen, a founding member of the people with aids coalition in new york, said the six-month-old pwa health group in new york has sold more than 11 tons of one alternative treatment, egg lipids
the lipids appear to repair damage to cell walls, he said. the treatment seems to help in aids cases, although no formal experiments have been done, and it has no side effects, he said
new jersey prosecutors announced friday they won't seek a third murder trial against rubin ``hurricane'' carter, ending the former boxer's 22-year campaign for freedom that became a popular celebrity cause
the passage of time, problems finding witnesses, court decisions discrediting previous testimony and the burden posed by a third prosecution were cited in legal motions seeking dismissal of the indictment against carter and his alleged accomplice, john artis
acting passaic county prosecutor john goceljak, in papers filed in paterson, also said other reasons supporting dismissal were the intense scrutiny given the case
it has received the attention of more courts and proceedings than probably any other case in the history of this state and possibly any other state,'' the court papers said
in addition, goceljak noted that carter served 19 years of a life prison term before a federal judge ordered his release and artis has been paroled on the murder conviction. artis is serving a six-year term on an unrelated drug conviction
a federal judge's finding that their latest conviction was racially tainted would likely exclude testimony about the motive for the killings, goceljak said
three whites were shot by black men on june 17, 1966, hours after a black man was slain by a white assailant. carter and artis are black
carter's cause was taken up in the 1970s by celebrities such as bob dylan, who wrote and sang ``the ballad of hurricane,'' actress ellen burstyn, boxer muhammed ali and singer joan baez
they lionized the former middleweight contender and elevated him as a symbol of racial injustice. but after a few highly publicized fund-raising events, some touched by scandal, carter's all-star backing faded
goceljak's decision to seek dismissal was made in consultation with the state's criminal justice director, donald r. belsole
it's time to say enough is enough,'' belsole said. ``i think society is served, the system is served and the defendants are served.''
a judge must sign the prosecutor's motion to finalize dismissal of the indictment, and attorney myron beldock, in a statement on behalf of carter and artis, said he hoped for quick consideration by the court
we are extremely pleased with the decision of the state of new jersey to dismiss the case against our clients, and hope that the appropriate orders will be signed promptly,'' said beldock
carter, now 50, has been living in seclusion since being freed in november 1985 by u.s. district judge h. lee sarokin. his whereabouts could not be determined friday, and beldock declined to give out carter's home phone number
the u.s. supreme court on jan. 11 had let stand sarokin's finding that carter's conviction was tainted because prosecutors withheld information from the defense
sarokin said the convictions were based on ``an appeal to racism rather than reason, and concealment rather than disclosure.''
defense attorneys all along had considered a third trial unlikely because testimony from the only eyewitness, alfred bello, had been discredited during appeals
resultingly, admission of any relevant testimony by him at a new trial must be considered problematical at this point,'' goceljak said in court papers
the case began when two black gunmen entered the lafayette bar and grill in paterson and killed the bartender and two patrons. hours earlier, a black paterson bartender had been shot to death by a white man
carter and artis were arrested three months later and convicted by an all-white jury in may 1967
but bello and another witness later recanted, saying they had been pressured by detectives into giving false testimony at the trial, and the case was reopened in 1974. the new jersey supreme court reversed the convictions march 17, 1976
in a second trial, carter and artis were convicted again dec. 21, 1976, in part with the testimony of bello, who had retracted his claims that he was coerced. this time, the state's highest court upheld the convictions by a 4-3 vote in 1982
from there, the case went to federal court and sarokin's ruling. tampering</head> not attorneys but other agents for the tobacco company. subs 11th pvs, bgng, `at issue... with 4 grafs to update with attorney saying he filed motion to force company to identify all paid agents. picks up 12th graf, `carlton said ....'</note>
an attorney for american brands inc. has admitted that company representatives talked with jurors during the trial of a $16.5 million damage suit against the cigarette manufacturer, but he says the plaintiffs are wrong to call it jury tampering
the family of deceased smoker nathan horton, of durant, had claimed american brands should be held liable for his illness and death. horton, 50, died jan. 29, 1987, of emphysema and lung cancer after 35 years of smoking two packs a day of pall mall unfiltered cigarettes, which are made by american brands
the trial ended jan. 29 with a hung jury
there's no question that it's a serious matter to file a motion of this kind,'' said plaintiff's attorney don barrett. he filed documents thursday alleging improper jury contact by the american brands representatives and seeking a default judgment and other sanctions against the defendant
but ed blackmon, one of several local attorneys hired by american brands, called the allegations of improper jury contact a joke
what you have is a clear attempt by the plaintiff to keep us from getting a fair trial,'' blackmon said
blackmon said the alleged improper contact with jurors was to let jurors know there wouldn't be court that particular day because the judge was ill
when you try to make that into a tampering argument, it's what their case was about: take what amounts to nothing and turn it into something,'' he said
the horton family's motion, filed thursday in holmes county circuit court, is based on information contained in affidavits given to district attorney frank carlton
it seeks a judgment in the hortons' behalf on the basis of american brand's alleged liability for horton's lung cancer and death, as well as attorneys' fees, court costs and expenses in preparation of the case
at issue are allegations that two paid representatives of american brand contacted three jurors during the trial, said carlton
barrett said friday four affidavits filed with the court indicate ``that more than one paid agent of the american tobacco co. illegally and improperly contacted certain members of the jury'' during the trial
this agent was not an attorney, but he was mighty well paid,'' said barrett, declining to name the person
barrett said he had also filed a motion asking the court to force the tobacco company to provide names ``of each person known or suspected by either defendant to have been hired or paid by anybody as a `jury consultant' or otherwise to assist either defendants or their attorneys in trial preparation or at the trial ... and to state the sums of money paid or owing to each person so hired, including all persons paid simply to be present in the courtroom during the trial.''
carlton said he picked up four affidavits tuesday from holmes county circuit judge gray evans, who presided over the monthlong trial
jurors gave two of the sworn statements, in which they said an individual contacted them one day during the trial about a scheduling change in court, carlton said. two other affidavits were made by people who heard an american brands adviser bragging that he had been paid $2,700. one of those people also said the adviser was talking to a juror
you're not supposed to contact jurors,'' carlton said. ``you're not even supposed to say, `good morning.''' anti-intellectualism'</head>
attorney general edwin meese iii says that rejected supreme court nominee robert bork was the target of ``a perverse campaign of anti-intellectualism and politically motivated character assassination.''
meese, in a speech to the republican national lawyers association, also was critical of sen. joseph biden, d-del., saying that the senate confirmation process for bork resulted in ``grave injustices'' being done ``to one of the foremost judicial thinkers of our time.''
the senate judiciary committee that biden chairs conducted the confirmation hearings on bork and recommended rejection of the nomination. the senate on oct. 23 turned aside the nomination on a vote of 58-42
meese, in the speech delivered thursday night, said that bork was unfairly criticized during his confirmation hearings because he declined to take an expansive view of the role of the judiciary and of the ninth amendment dealing with rights not enumerated in the constitution
the attorney general said biden suggested that ``the courts exist to discover and define our inalienable rights and to enforce them and implied that this was so whether or not they are found in the written texts of the supreme laws of our land
such ideas not only represent a gross misunderstanding of the american political process and tradition but also ... if carried into effect would seriously threaten our liberties as a self-governing people,'' meese said
biden is hospitalized while recovering from surgery to correct a blood vessel problem near his brain and is unable to comment, said his press secretary, pat baskette
meese said the courts have a role in protecting rights, but that the rights themselves, to be valid, must be derived from written legal documents
most of us here agree that grave injustices were done to one of the foremost judicial thinkers of our time'' during bork's confirmation process, meese said. ``he was the victim of a perverse campaigan of anti-intellectualism and politically motivated character assassination, that i hope will never bear a repeat performance in the future history of our country.''
another unsuccessful supreme court nominee, douglas ginsburg, was in the audience for meese's speech and the two men spoke briefly after the attorney general's remarks. ginsburg's nomination, which followed bork's, collapsed nov. 7 after ginsburg acknowledged that he had smoked marijuana while he was a law professor
reagan's third nominee for the post, anthony kennedy, won swift senate approval and was sworn in as a justice on thursday
illinois sen. paul simon said friday he would remain in the democratic presidential race until the party convention in july
this is a marathon race for the heart and soul of the democratic party, and i'm in it until the finish line in atlanta,'' simon told the minnehaha county democratic forum. the national convention will be held july 18-21 in the georgia capital
the response i have received here in the past few days, plus the outpouring of encouragement from my home state of illinois and from democrats throughout the land, has convinced me that a great many americans want a clear-cut choice next november,'' simon said
they want a make-no-apologies democratic nominee. i intend to offer that choice, waging a fight for the heart and the soul of the democratic party.''
after placing third among democrats in this week's new hampshire primary, simon had said he would drop out of the race if he did not win south dakota's primary or minnesota's caucuses tuesday
the senator said friday that he initially decided on that path because of financial reality. ``i didn't want to end up with a huge debt,'' he said, adding that he did not make the statement as a ploy to get more money for his campaign
simon said cash pledges have increased dramatically in the last few days, but he would not say who had contributed. simon's staff has said the campaign received at least $300,000 in the past week and $250,000 the week earlier
gene r. carter, superintendent of the norfolk, va., public schools, was named the first national superintendent of the year on friday by the american association of school adminstrators
the award, announced at the educators' convention in las vegas, includes a gold medallion and a $1,000 u.s. savings bond for carter and a $10,000 college scholarship that will go to carter's hometown high school
carter attended booker t. washington high school in staunton, va., which in those days of legal segregation was for blacks only. it no longer exists
the scholarship will go instead to a student from robert e. lee high school, which now serves all the youths of staunton. the rules for deciding who will win the scholarship have not been determined
a panel of business, government and education leaders chose carter from four finalists, who had been selected earlier from a field of 38 state finalists
the runners-up were: jack c. dulaney of the monongalia schools in morgantown, w.va.; scott n. rose of the pinellas county schools in clearwater, fla., and robert d. tschirki of the littleton, colo., schools. each received a silver medallion and $500 u.s. savings bond
carter outlined his educational philosophy in this statement: ``education is power. the belief that knowledge empowers people and nations is the foundation upon which we must build our commitment to education. those of us who lead american public education must safeguard what could be termed an educational bill of rights for each student. we need to guarantee simultaneous equity and excellence for every young person in our nation.''
carter said teachers and students need administrators ``who help them learn. they also need leaders who create a positive and constructive tone, a climate that will support educational excellence.''
the award, sponsored by the servicemaster co. of downers grove, ill., is patterned after the long-established national teacher of the year competition
the editors of the opposition daily extra said friday that the government closed down their publication again, three weeks after it reopened
cristobal sarmiento, extra's publisher, said in an interview that government officials arrived thursday night and sealed the door with an adhesive tape that read ``closed by the attorney general of the nation.''
the paper had reopened in january, six months after it was closed in a general crackdown by the government on opposition news media after protests started against the leadership of gen. manuel antonio noriega
noriega, the nation's military chief, is considered the de facto ruler of panama, nominally governed by civilian president eric arturo delvalle
a document ordering extra to be closed said this was done ``to obtain elements that might serve to prove a punishable deed or to uncover its authors and participants.''
editors said government officials confiscated material ready for publication in friday's editions before sealing the door
extra is printed in the opposition daily la prensa next door, but is a separate publication. la prensa reopened last month and continues to publish
besides extra, the newspaper el siglo and the radio stations kw continente, la exitosa and radio chiriqui have been closed down by the government this year
sarmiento was accused last year of publishing information against the interests of the national economy, but the case was suspended as part of an amnesty ordered by the national legislature
six news media that had been closed last july reopened as part of that amnesty
the national banking commission meanwhile announced friday that nearly 50 percent of the local deposits withdrawn from banks in panama were returned in the past four months
people had withdrawn banking deposits since unrest started last june with allegations that noriega had been involved in a wide range of illicit activities
the banking commission said about $103 million of the $208 million withdrawn up to last october had been recovered by private panamanian banks and that as a result they had ``strengthened their liquidity.''
the commission's statement said about 40 percent of the recovery was registered during the past five weeks
by continuing in this way, or better yet, accelerating this rhythm of recovery, the private panamanian banks surely will be able to reactivate soon their credit lending as much for commercial purposes as for mortgage holders,'' the statement said
there are 20 panamanian and 98 foreign institutions in panama
the marine radio in qatar issued warnings friday to vessels in the persian gulf after a ship reported what appeared to be a mine in the shallows off the sheikdom's west coast
the radio advised ships to stay clear of that area between qatar, which juts north into the gulf from the arabian peninsula, and the island state of bahrain
shipping executives said a ship that did not identify itself reported sighting an object that was ``black, with points,'' at about 4 p.m. there was no confirmation that it was one of the numerous mines sown in the gulf since the iran-iraq war began in september 1980
waters in that stretch are too shallow for major shipping and unlikely to have been mined, but a few mines have been found off bahrain and qatar, apparently after drifting down from the northern gulf
most sightings have turned out to be floating debris ranging from oil drums to dead sheep with their feet sticking out of the water
a french corvette, the montcalm, used gunfire to destroy a floating mine north of bahrain on thursday, according a report by the kuwaiti news agency that quoted french navy officials in paris
the united states and five european countries are decreasing their mine-sweeping forces in the gulf after declaring the threat posed by iranian mines to be under control
iran said its navy intercepted five foreign ships thursday in the strait of hormuz, the gulf's narrow southern gate, but let all of them go when it was found they contained no cargo bound for iraq
iranian frigates and armed speedboats patrol the strait, which leads into the gulf of oman. they stop ships suspected of trading with iraq and sometimes attack neutral vessels in retaliation for iraqi air strikes on iranian coastal shipping
a crowd of 75 people waved signs and released blue balloons friday in support of dallas police, after officers killed two men who threatened them with weapons in separate incidents
minority leaders and the city council have berated the department for the past two years for being too trigger-happy when confronting suspects, especially blacks and hispanics, but others have rallied around police
there have been police casualties, too, including two officers slain last month
police credited new two-person patrols, begun after the second officer's death, with averting officers' death or serious injury in the latest incidents
early friday, police shot and killed a white man who used a hunting knife to cut an officer who had chased the man's car during a robbery investigation
wednesday night, police fatally shot a black man they said pointed a loaded semiautomatic pistol at an officer who had slipped and fallen on a dark residential street and was unable to draw his gun
the department placed the officers on routine administrative leave while it conducts an internal investigation
tension flared last month when police chief billy prince accused council members of fostering anti-police sentiment that led to the jan. 23 death of officer john chase, who was gunned down by a deranged, homeless man. some witnesses said a few youths egged on the gunman, though others said they heard nothing of the kind
since then, however, the city has seen repeated shows of support for the department
at friday's noon rally at the john f. kennedy memorial, the mostly white crowd held signs and released balloons in support of the double-patrol system police say may have saved the life of one officer wednesday and prevented further injury to the other officer friday
we are here today to thank each and every peace officer across this nation for doing the job that no one else is brave enough to do,'' said terri kleinmeier, president of citizens offering police support
e.l. crenshaw, a retired dallas police officer, called the double patrols ``the best thing since flush toilets'' and attacked police critics by saying ``you don't put down these indians until you've walked in their moccasins.''
the two-man element at the scene prevented more injury to the officer. it's very possible that the injury would have escalated to a severe and critical injury,'' homicide investigator don ortega said
dorothy johnson, one of the few blacks to attend the downtown rally, said there has been racial tension in the city, ``but i don't take sides. a tragedy can happen to either side.''
ronnie lewis jones died about an hour after he was shot wednesday by officer brian wolff, who said jones pointed the pistol at his partner, steven johnson
if it had not been a two-man element, johnson could be dead right now,'' said capt. john holt, head of the department's crimes against persons section
early friday, police killed thomas holloway, 35, after stopping him on the southern methodist university campus. the car's license tags were covered with cloth
holloway emerged from his car, carrying a hunting knife, and cut one officer's hand, police said. the officer and his partner fired at the man, ortega said. at least five shots were fired, police said
police were paired as a safety precaution after two officers _ chase, who was white, and james joe, who was black _ were killed in nine days last month
on jan. 14 joe, who was off-duty, was killed as he confronted burglary suspects in a northeast dallas apartment complex's parking lot. nine days later, a mentally ill man took chase's gun and shot him to death before being killed by pursuing officers
arizona's national image is suffering, former rep. john rhodes said friday in announcing he will run against impeached gov. evan mecham, a fellow republican, in the may 17 recall election
if there is an election on may 17, my name will be on the ballot,'' the 71-year-old former u.s. house minority leader said at a news conference. ``i don't like to lose. in fact, i'm not going to lose.''
rhodes will oppose mecham, democrat carolyn warner and a number of lesser-known potential candidates in the winner-take-all recall vote. mrs. warner, a former state school superintendent, lost to mecham in the three-way 1986 gubernatorial race
mecham also faces a march 9 criminal trial on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and a feb. 29 impeachment trial in the state senate
mecham and his staffers did not return phone calls seeking comment on rhodes' entry into the race
rhodes, who served 30 years in the house before retiring in 1982, said that ``because of the current acrimonious climate, the important issues facing the state are not being addressed adequately. ... we cannot afford continued paralysis.''
mecham is guaranteed a spot on the recall ballot. other candidates must submit 3,336 signatures of registered voters by march 18. the secretary of state's office said 86 people, including mrs. warner and rhodes, had picked up packets to collect signatures thus far
attorney general bob corbin has issued a non-binding opinion saying that if mecham resigns or is removed from office before the recall vote, the election still must be held even though the governorship would have been turned over to acting gov. rose mofford
however, a number of lawmakers and others have said the matter is likely to be settled in court
mrs. mofford, a democrat, has declined to say if she will run in a recall election
rhodes declined to criticize mecham or mrs. warner, who has labeled him a candidate of the power brokers because he is backed by people like developer j. fife symington and keith turley, chairman of pinnacle west, the parent firm of arizona public service corp. symington is rhodes' finance chairman, and turley was among the first people to urge rhodes to enter the race
my service in the congress should be adequate proof that i don't wear anyone's collar,'' rhodes said
rhodes said former sen. barry goldwater has promised his support, and current sen. john mccain, a republican, said friday he also backs rhodes. goldwater previously said mecham should resign
state republican chairman burton kruglick said the party has not endorsed either mecham or rhodes in the recall campaign
meanwhile, mrs. mofford on friday disputed mecham's claim that she has been dismantling his administration since she took over as acting governor following his feb. 5 impeachment by the house
i am responsible for acting as the chief executive of this state during that period,'' mrs. mofford said in a letter to mecham. she said she had replaced only one department head and had given mecham everyone he wanted for his personal staff
also on friday, a recall petition was taken out against rep. sterling ridge, a republican who voted to impeach mecham, making him the 10th lawmaker to face a recall drive because of his recall vote
the first of seven memorial services for victims of the rampage at a silicon valley defense plant took place friday while officials maintained a suicide watch on the gunman charged with their deaths
about 600 mourners jammed a funeral home for services for glenda moritz, a 27-year-old planner at esl inc., the top-secret electronics plant where police say richard wade farley shot seven workers to death and wounded three others, including a woman whose rejection of farley's advances apparently sparked the massacre
jeanne pilling, moritz's roommate and best friend, said the two spent the night before tuesday's shooting talking about their destinies
glenda said, `we never know what the future holds for us. don't you wish you knew what the future holds?''' pilling recalled. ``i still don't believe it really happened. she was my very best friend. i've never been that close to a person in my life.''
there was no casket; a private burial is planned. mourners paid their respects before a display of photos surrounded by dozens of bouquets
you've lost that loving feeling,'' by the righteous brothers, was played during the service. friends said it was one of moritz's favorite songs
additional services are planned this weekend for the six others killed before the computer expert surrendered after 5{ hours
medical authorities said three esl employees wounded in the attack, and a fourth who broke her arm trying to escape, are all recovering, including laura black, a 26-year-old technician whom farley had pursued relentlessly for four years
farley, 39, was fired from the company 21 months ago for harassing her, esl officials said
he is being held without bail in solitary confinement in santa clara county jail, where he has requested a telephone and envelopes
he was being held in an isolation cell under a ``welfare watch,'' which allows guards to maintain close supervision in case he attempts to take his life and also protects him from attacks by other inmates, said san jose county sheriff's sgt. cary colla
he has been quiet. he's been polite to staff. as one officer described it, he seemed to be going through a lot of self-thought,'' said colla
the docile and quiet portrait of farley contrasts markedly with the man police say tormented black by following her, phoning her, joining her aerobics class and sending her more than 300 letters
i want to warn you how far i'm willing to go if you continue to push me,'' he wrote in one note. ``i once told you i will do whatever is necessary to see you. let's say you don't back down and pretty soon i crack under the pressure and run amok destroying everything in my path until the police catch me and kill me. ...''
black finally obtained a court order to prevent farley from bothering her further. the order was final on wednesday, 12 hours after farley marched into the esl plant carrying 98 pounds of weaponry and opened fire with a repeating shotgun
rep. newt gingrich, r-ga., said friday he will ask the house ethics committee next month to launch a formal investigation into allegations of corruption that have been leveled against speaker jim wright in published reports over the past 10 years
gingrich, a leader of republican right in the house and a frequent critic of the ethics of house democratic leaders, said the news accounts outline ``clear violations of house rules'' by wright, d-texas, and deserve to be investigated
the problem that this house faces is that they now have a speaker who has real problems,'' he said. ``we're going to have to at least, at a minimum, insist that we find out what the truth is, and on march 3 i intend to create that opportunity.''
neither wright nor his spokesman were immediately available to comment on gingrich's plan to request an investigation
under house rules, any member can ask the ethics committee _ formally called the committee on standards of official conduct _ to investigate another member. the panel, composed of six democrats and six republicans, can reject such a request only by a majority vote
gingrich said it would be ``inconceivable'' that the committee would refuse to investigate the allegations. but if that happens, he said he intends to force the issue on the house floor with a series of privileged votes that could tie up the house for months
gingrich, who lost a house vote last year on his proposal to create an outside commission to investigate ethics complaints against wright and other democratic leaders, said he was announcing his intentions to seek an ethics committee investigation now so other house members could familiarize themselves with the allegations against wright
he said he chose march 3 as the date to file his complaint because he wants the committee to have time to complete at least a preliminary investigation before congress adjourns for the year
gingrich cited two specific published reports which he said provide clear evidence that wright violated house rules. the first involved wrights's failure since 1980 to file the required financial disclosure reports for a company in which he is a partner
the second involved 55 percent royalties wright received for a book published by a friend whose printing company worked for wright's campaign committee. gingrich said house rules prohibit members from receiving royalities in excess of ``the usual and customary value for such services,'' and most authors receive royalties of 6 percent to 8 percent
gingrich and a political action committee he heads were accused last month by the democratic congressional campaign committee of mail fraud for soliciting more than $200,000 in contributions for conservative candidates through the mails and then providing only $3,000 to such candidates
gingrich denied the dccc accusations friday, characterizing them as an attempt to discredit him politically so he could not pursue the ethics complaints against wright. he also denied that his actions against wright were politically motivated. over new hampshire loss; picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng, `at the.' minor editing thruout.</note>
vice president george bush said friday that the rodeo of the political campaign is filled with hard knocks, and suggested that his chief rival bob dole is still smarting from his new hampshire fall
in a thinly disguised barb directed toward the kansas senator, bush suggested to a crowd at the national cowboy hall of fame that his opponent is brooding over his second-place finish in the new hampshire republican primary
you learn that the rodeo is full of hard encounters with the ground and you learn to pick yourself up and dust yourself off and get back on the horse again,'' bush said
and there's a lesson in that for everybody in public life and it's a lesson that the people of iowa reminded me of 10 days ago,'' bush said. ``so you don't get angry and bitter when you get defeated. you pick yourself back up and get back on the horse and go on and win the next election.''
bush said earlier in the day that he is bewildered by dole's refusal to debate him friday night, but said he will ``let them worry'' about the wisdom of that strategy
at the start of a campaign tour in oklahoma city, bush said that despite the pre-super tuesday jockeying by dole and pat robertson, ``all i know is to concentrate on the positive and take my message to the people.''
a senior bush campaign aide, talking to reporters on grounds of anonymity, said there had been talk of bush withdrawing from the dallas debate. but the official said bush killed that idea, telling aides that ``i gave my word'' to take part in the face-off
seeking votes in oklahoma, a state that has suffered from declining u.s. oil production and price drops, bush told reporters at will rogers world airport that if elected president, he would push for ``a newer and more visionary'' energy policy
bush did not elaborate on that point. he told an audience in dallas on thursday that the united states must free itself of dependency on foreign sources of oil. in the new hampshire campaign, he said he was against a $10 per barrel import fee
the vice president's plane landed in oklahoma city in clear, springlike weather under sunny skies. bush strode over to waiting reorters, and he was besieged with questions about dole's refusal to meet him in the dallas republican presidential debate later in the day
i honestly cannot interpret what it's about,'' bush said of the dole campaign strategy. ``i'm simply confused by what it is. ... i'll let them worry about their campaigns and we'll keep on the positive track.''
he emphatically denied allegations from rival campaign camps that his campaign had been given advance notice of the questions to be asked in the debate
i can't believe that somebody would make that kind of accusation,'' he said. ``it's certainly not true. there is no evidence of truth whatsoever in that.''
bush also said ``no way'' when asked whether he was worried about being upset by robertson in the march 5 south carolina primary
but the vice president did acknowledge that ``he's strong there. but we will fight hard.'' bush is scheduled to visit south carolina on monday after campaigning over the weekend in his hometown of houston
bush began his oklahoma city tour by visiting a control data systems computer components manufacturing plant
at one point, the vice president sat down next to a woman, wearing a blue work blouse, and accepted her invitation to try his hand at assembling a component. he manually installed a computer chip into a circuit board
after touring the plant, bush went to the cowboy hall of fame, where he joined in a tribute to the late malcolm baldrige, the reagan administration commerce secretary who was killed in a fall from horse in northern california last year
baldrige, an accomplished rodeo rider, was enshrined in the hall during a private ``hat hanging'' ceremony
colombia's largest leftist guerrilla group said friday it supports president virgilio barco's attempt to combat violence by reforming the constitution so he will have more power
the colombian revolutionary armed forces, known as the farc, said it believes ``a vast majority of the people'' support such a plebiscite
the communique, from the farc's chiefs of staff, was published by colombia's leading daily, el tiempo, of bogota
the supreme court has thwarted barco's attempts to use state of siege powers to move against drug traffickers, leftist guerrillas and right-wing death squads. it found about half of his decrees unconstitutional
barco proposed last month that colombia's 1886 constitution be reformed through a referendum
a 1957 amendment to the constitution prohibits referendums, so there must first be a plebiscite to lift that ban. once the ban was lifted, a constituent assembly would be held to decide how the constitution should be reformed
barco has not spelled out the reforms he wants, but indicated he wants to change colombia's two-chamber congress to one chamber to speed up legislation; to change the overburdened and corrupt court system, and to get more power in issuing decrees under a state of siege
a state of siege is on now in colombia. there has been a state of siege for all but a few months of the last 40 years
barco belongs to the liberal party. the opposition conservative party refused to support a plebiscite. barco has delayed setting a voting date in hope of promoting national unity on the issue
the plebiscite could be as early as march 13, coinciding with the nationwide election of mayors
the farc said barco should ignore the conservatives and see ``if the people want a new constitution or if they want to stay with the anachronistic and feudal one of 1886.''
the farc is the largest of five guerrilla groups in colombia. the army says the farc has about 5,000 members. farc leaders claim to have about 20,000 combatants
by reforming the constitution, barco hopes to have the tools to stop violence which has been wracking the country for four decades
the left has been particularly hurt. more than 400 members of its patriotic union party were killed in the last two years. many of the party's leaders and other members are former farc guerrillas
the party says right-wing death squads run by the military are behind the killings
about 100 members of the liberal and conservative parties also have been killed in the last two years. in many of those cases the military has blamed leftist guerrillas
colombia also has been hit hard by drug trafficker violence
the government says that the traffickers killed a justice minister, an attorney general, several judges, two newspaper editors and many others who opposed them over the last four years
thousands of ford motor co. workers learned friday their share of the automaker's record $4.6 billion in 1987 earnings will average more than $3,700 each when profit-sharing checks are handed out next month
ford will distribute $635 million in profit-sharing to hourly and salaried workers march 8. the no. 2 automaker said it is believed to be the largest one-year payout ever by a major u.s. corporation
ford's chief financial officer, stan seneker, announced the figures to cheering workers at ford's michigan truck plant in wayne, just west of detroit. the announcement was broadcast live to 200 ford facilities nationwide
ford, which earned the highest profits in automotive history in 1987, will know in coming weeks exactly how many of its 180,000 workers will receive a share, said ford spokesman mike moran said
the company's u.s. employees can take pride in their performance as members of the ford team. it is fitting that they will share in the results by receiving their largest profit-sharing checks ever,'' ford chairman donald petersen said
united auto workers vice president stephen yokich, who heads the union's ford department, said the uaw was pleased with the payouts, which were first negotiated in 1982 for 1983 earnings
but he added, ``we would again urge ford motor co. to allocate much more in capital investments from its huge profits into u.s.-based production of vehicles and components
the real `reward' sought by u.s. workers, consumers and communities for their contributions to ford's success should be sizeable additional u.s. investments by ford toward securing jobs for the future,'' yokich said
ford has added no assembly plants of its own in the united states in recent years. instead, it is building some cars in mexico, and its new ford probe sporty coupe is built at a mazda motor corp. plant
ford also imports cars from korea and west germany and plans to build a new lincoln-mercury luxury convertible in australia
in 1987, ford outearned industry-leader general motors corp. for the second straight year, its profits jumping 41 percent over 1986
workers at gm, which earned $3.6 billion, will receive no share of profits for the second straight year. no. 3 chrysler corp. made $1.3 billion in 1987
although the formulas for profit-sharing at ford and gm differ, both are based on the company's u.s. performance. ford improved its u.s. earnings in 1987; gm's fell by nearly half from 1986
the lack of profit-sharing at gm at the same time that the corporation handed out millions of dollars in executive bonuses angered workers. gm has switched to the ford formula for the contract covering 1988-90
but gm said that even under the ford formula, it wouldn't have earned enough in the united states to pay profit-sharing for 1987
more than 160,250 ford workers received record profit-sharing payments averaging $2,100 for 1986, when ford earned $3.29 billion
in 1985, ford profit-sharing averaged $1,200 per worker, $2,000 in 1984 and $400 in 1983. in the past five years, ford said it has given out more than $1.6 billion to its workers
the united nations plans to reconvene the 159-member general assembly in an emergency session to consider the u.s. move to close the palestine liberation organization mission, u.n. officials said friday
the effort by the u.s. congress has placed america on a collision course with the world body. the plo has formidable support at the united nations, which generally votes against the united states and israel on middle east issues
under the u.s. anti-terrorism act of 1987, passed by congress and signed by president reagan on dec. 22, 1987, the plo mission at the united nations was ordered closed by march 22
on thursday, arab nations demanded a resumed session to fight the u.s. action which the united nations and the u.s. state department say violates a legal agreement on the right of missions to operate
in a letter to peter florin of east germany, president of the general assembly, the arab group requested reconvening of the general assembly as soon as possible and no later than feb. 29
the 42nd general assembly completed its agenda in december but technically is still in session. it can be reconvened at any time with a request by members and consent of the president
reconvened sessions are not uncommon, but the plo issue is one of the most controversial and divisive to be considered
secretary-general javier perez de cuellar ``feels the request for a resumed session is both timely and understandable,'' u.n. press spokesman mario zamorano told reporters at a briefing friday
florin will return wednesday from a visit to egypt and will consult with the arab countries on reconvening the world body, his spokeswoman, nadia youssef, told reporters friday
the plo and the arab league previously said they might ask the assembly to leave new york and meet in geneva if the plo mission is closed
after congress passed the anti-terrorism measure, the general assembly overwhelmingly passed a resolution urging the united states to leave the plo mission open
the u.s. government itself is divided on the issue. the state department has said repeatedly that the treaty obliges the united states to allow all u.n. missions, including the plo, to function
it now is up to attorney general edwin meese iii to decide whether the mission can remain open
several members of congress have said meese told them he would close the mission, despite the treaty
the treaty provides for binding arbitration of disputes between the united states and the united nations. perez de cuellar said the united states has so far not agreed to arbitration
plo chairman yasser arafat has said the plo may take the dispute to the international court of justice in the hague. those...''</note>
windhoek, south-west africa (ap) _ a bomb exploded in a crowded bank near a military base during lunch hour friday and killed 14 people. it was the deadliest civilian attack in the territory's 22-year guerrilla war for independence
the blast in the northern town of oshakati killed 10 women, three men and a child and injured 31 people, most of them seriously, said an army spokesman, commandant lieb bester
no one immediately claimed responsibility for the bombing, which destroyed the first national bank building. five people were injured when the same bank was bombed a year ago
all those killed, a white woman and 13 blacks, were civilians, bester said. most were believed to be government workers who had just received their paychecks
a police inspector, keirie du rand, said about 55 pounds of plastic explosives were used in the blast, which occurred shortly before 1 p.m. anfire raged for several hours after the explosion, hampering police access
oshakati is about 25 miles south of the angolan border and is home to the largest military base in the region, a staging point for south africa's military intervention in angola's civil war
guerrillas of the south-west african people's organization (swapo), based in angola, frequently operate in the ovambo region around oshakati
swapo has been fighting since 1966 to gain control of south-west africa, also known as namibia. the territory is administered by south africa in violation of a united nations resolution
a statement received in windhoek, the territorial capital, from a swapo office in luanda, angola, denied involvement. the statement said the blast was part of a south african propaganda campaign to ``smear the name of swapo.''
swapo has claimed responsibility for previous bombings in the territory, including a blast last month at a store at a military base in windhoek. the bombing, which caused no injuries, was intended to protest the visit to namibia of conservative west german politician franz josef strauss
the worst previous bombing in the region occurred in 1986 in the port town of walvis bay, a south african enclave near the center of namibia's atlantic coast. five people were killed and 23 injured in that explosion at a crowded butcher shop. no group claimed responsibility for that blast
swapo has attacked both military and civilian targets during its sabotage and bombing campaign. an estimated 20,000 people have died during the bush war, about half of them guerrillas, about 700 of them security forces, and the rest civilians
south african and south-west african troops have been fighting for about five months in angola on behalf of the unita rebel movement. south african officials say they will not grant independence to namibia until after withdrawal of the 40,000 cuban troops fighting in support of angola's marxist government
only about 70,000 of namibia's 1.3 million people are white, and the south african government has installed a multiracial transitional administration to run the territory's affairs
swapo has refused to negotiate with the transitional government, citing the u.n. resolution demanding free elections
the south african press association said the doors of the bank may have been locked at the time of the explosion. it said guards often locked the doors when the bank was busy in order to keep the office from becoming too crowded
a federal appeals court friday rejected an attempt by america west airlines inc. to block the planned merger of usair and piedmont aviation, saying the phoenix-based airline had no legal standing in the case
in a brief opinion, a three-judge panel of the u.s. circuit court of appeals here refused to grant america west's petition to review the transportation department's approval of the merger
america west contended that the merger will inhibit its ability to expand to eastern cities
but the court said ``america west's generalized allegations about flying eastward are neither causally related to the department's final order nor redressable by reversal of the order.''
even if the merger were overturned by the court, america west would be no better off because it has not identified any interest in serving any identified market actually affected by the merger,'' the court said
in a statement, america west's chairman, edward r. beauvais, said the company was disappointed by the decision
we are in the process of reviewing the decision to determine our future course of action with respect to the case,'' he said
air traffic will increase steadily over the next dozen years with air traffic controllers handling a third more planes in 1999 than they do today, the federal aviation administration forecast friday
the faa forecast also shows that the number of people flying commercial jetliners will grow from about 445 million passengers in 1987 to nearly 765 million in 1999
the commuter aircraft are expected to have an even sharper passenger growth from carrying 27 million people last year to carrying 58 million annually just before the turn of the century, according to the faa's latest aviation forecasts
what we see is a situation of growth, substantial growth, for the industry and the faa,'' john rodgers, the agency's deputy director for aviation policy and plans, told an aviation planning conference
the conference focused on problems stemming from the expected growth in aviation in the coming years. most aviation experts have predicted that either through government regulation or some form of market incentives the nation's aviation system will have to be constrained because of a shortage of airports and air traffic control limitiations
in a speech, however, robert crandall, chairman of american airlines, told the group that more attention should be placed on ``how to avoid (air traffic) constraints rather than using up too many resources talking about how to operate within constraints.''
crandall acknowledged that some limitations on aviation growth might be necessary in the short term, but he said in the long run ``bold action'' is needed to increase airway and airport capacity
we should not become so focused on constraints that we lose sight of the need to build an aviation system capable of operating in the long term ... without the constraints which are increasingly reducing the industry's efficiency, stifling its growth and frustrating its customers,'' said crandall
the faa growth forecast was based on an assumption of an average 3 percent annual economic growth and the absence of intense fare wars among the airlines. the growth likely would be dampened by slower economic growth and likely be greater if the airlines were to engage in a fare battle that would attract more travelers
according to the faa forecast, the number of domestic enplanements will increase 4.6 percent a year through the end of this decade while the number of revenue passenger miles - a figure that reflects a single passenger traveling one mile - will increase 4.8 percent a year
the number of flights, however, are expected to increase at a slower rate, 2.3 percent annually, indicating that airlines will fly with fewer empty seats and likely move somewhat to larger aircraft, said the forecast
during the next dozen years there will be almost no increase in the number of general aviation aircraft, although the number of more sophisticated turbine-powered business aircraft is expected to increase by about 50 percent, the faa said
the demand for faa operational services is anticipated to increase over the forecast period as a result of continued strong growth in aviation activity,'' predicted the faa
the total number of aircraft operations - both commercial and private -handled at faa towers and at enroute air traffic control centers will increase by about 2.4 percent a year, the agency said
faa towers at airports will handle 81.4 million flight operations by 1999, compared to 61 million last year, the forecast predicted. the increase in operations handled by enroute air traffic control centers will stem primarily from increased air carrier and commuter traffic, the faa said
the head of israel's government broadcasting authority has banned a satirical song about alleged israeli indifference to the violence in the occupied arab territories, a spokeswoman said friday
what's burning'' is about members of a family who intently watch the american television show ``dynasty'' while their house goes up in flames
the song is a satirical commentary on the way normal life has continued for many israelis during 10 weeks of violence in the occupied west bank and gaza strip. more than 50 palestinians have been killed by israelis in the unrest, according to u.n. figures
it was to have been performed on the friday night entertainment show ``from me, manny,'' one of the highest-rated shows on state television
spokeswoman sari timerman said the song was banned by uri porat, chief of the israel broadcasting authority, who described it as ``maccabre anti-israeli propaganda in the guise of social satire. it is based on the lying thesis that the israeli public is indifferent ... to what happens here.''
several daily newspapers gave front-page coverage to the ban and published the words of the song in full
four well-known comedians, including tuvia zafir, whose specialty is mimicking israel's political leaders, act out the lyrics
zafir portrays the father in a family of four that includes a wife, a son serving in the army and a younger boy
the father, determined to watch ``dynasty,'' ignores the the warnings of his younger son about the flames outside
father: ``don't worry. it won't last. it will be over in a few minutes.''
verse: ``nothing's burning. nothing's burning. no reason to get up. no reason to hurry.''
father: ``and as the mature, responsible and experienced one my motto is: `sit still and don't do anything.'''
even when his clothes catch fire the father doesn't worry. zafir sings:
you're so silly, fire, so silly. what do you think, that just because you're burning me i will think you're endangering my health? really now! go ahead, spread as much as you like. we'll see which one of us tires faster.''
the house burns down
father: ``the fire, as i said, will finally be extinguished and of course time will be on our side.''
son: ``but father, we have burned the time.''
father: ``shut up!'' (slaps him.) ``and whoever takes a look around''
mother: ``will see that father, as always, is right.''
ms. timerman said porat was especially angered by a passage in which the father tells his elder son to get up and put out the flames, ``but try not to block `dynasty.'''
she quoted porat as saying: ``this is an insult to every israeli family. it portrays them as not caring about their soldier-sons and sending them to do their dirty work.''
premier giovanni goria won a vote of confidence in the senate on friday that completed the resurrection of his shaky coalition government
the senate voted 170 to 91 to back goria. the chamber of deputies, the lower house of parliament, voted 364-208 with four abstentions on thursday to support the return of the premier
although the votes of confidence have supported goria, the problems that led to his resignation have not been resolved
goria, a christian democrat, resigned feb. 10 after defectors in his party helped defeat the government 17 times in the chamber during secret votes on the proposed budget and spending for government ministries
president francesco cossiga rejected the resignation and told goria to remain premier to get the budget passed by parliament before the april 30 deadline
goria's five-party coalition, italy's 47th postwar government, has been shaky since he took office last july. the coalition includes the christian democrats, the socialists and three tiny parties, the social democrats, republicans and liberals
the premier, who at 44 is the youngest to ever hold the post, also resigned in november during a dispute with the liberals. however, cossiga later persuaded him to withdraw his resignation
