i stood with you,'' the democratic candidate said. ``now make me a president.''
the rev. arlene ackerman, pastor of all god's children metropolitan community church, said jackson was the only presidential candidate to join gays and lesbians when they marched on washington, d.c., in october
he's not afraid to dignify us by championing our causes,'' said bill dorn, a former catholic priest who is gay
jackson, who drew a capacity crowd of about 1,000 to the church, said other candidates have avoided making appearances with gay and lesbian groups
they were afraid that being close to you would make them look unpresidential,'' jackson said
jackson said he supports legislation in congress that calls for an end to discrimination based on sexual orientation. he also said he supports a massive, federally funded aids prevention and education campaign
i hope you do consider me to be your friend,'' jackson said. ``i affirm your humanity and your rights under the law.''
jackson urged the crowd to attend minnesota's precinct caucuses on tuesday
don't pull for me and vote for someone else,'' he said. ``put your oath and votes in the same trough.''
