peace talks between the leftist nicaraguan government and contra rebels broke down friday and their mediator indirectly blamed the sandinistas for not accepting a new cease-fire proposal
cardinal miguel obando y bravo, the head of the roman catholic church in nicaragua, abruptly suspended the talks in mid-afternoon, expressing disappointment that his proposal had not been accepted ``in principle'' by both sides
victor hugo tinoco, nicaragua's deputy foreign minister, said the cardinal called off the talks before he could deliver a formal, written response that would have accepted the mediator's five-point plan
the plan, offered by obando y bravo on thursday, called on the contras to accept a cease-fire in exchange for four major concessions by the sandinistas, including a total amnesty for all political prisoners and full freedom of the press
contra negotiators told a news conference thursday night that they accepted the cardinal's proposal ``in principle,'' while tinoco called it ``interesting and constructive'' but said it needed clarification
paul reichler, a washington, d.c., attorney adivising the sandinistas, said earlier friday that president daniel ortega had initially instructed his negotiators not to discuss obando y bravo's proposal at the bargaining table with the contras
reichler said ortega's instructions came by telephone thursday night, shortly after obando y bravo offered his plan to break what he called an impasse in a discussion on defining the objectives of a cease-fire
the attorney said ortega suggested that roger fisher, a harvard professor who heads the institute for conflict resolution in boston, draw up a new cease-fire plan, drawing on the proposals of the government and the contras
in a communique, obando y bravo rejected that suggestion
no new date was set for further negotiations, although both sides expressed their willingness to continue the talks
the cardinal's communique said that ``after all the meetings that they have had, the mediators believe that the acceptance, in principle, of its proposal would favor the rapid advance of the cease-fire negotiations.''
the communique also said the government and the contras should give their negotiators ``enough decision-making ability to resolve problems that present themselves in the negotiations.''
in a news conference after the talks ended, jaime morales, the chief contra negotiator, said his team had the ability to make decisions on the spot, noting that the rebels had accepted obando y bravo's proposal thursday night
we accepted the proposal in principle, and the other side did not,'' morales said
tinoco, on the other hand, blamed the contras for the breakdown in the negotiations
it was our impression that the contras were systematically rejecting all discussion of a cease-fire,'' he told reporters. ``the contras continue to be advised by people in the (reagan) administration who want to continue the war.''
the u.s.-supported rebels expressed reservations friday about the proposal. they said they saw potential danger in the mediator's request for their acceptance of an as yet undefined cease-fire in exchange for concessions
during a break in the talks friday morning, reichler told reporters that ortega felt the guatemala city talks should be confined solely to the mechanics of establishing a cease-fire and not become a forum for political discussions
the attorney quoted the nicaraguan president as saying he was willing to talk personally with obando y bravo about his proposal but did not want his negotiators to discuss it at the talks
later in the day, however, the government apparently switched positions. but by the time it could get its new response to the cardinal, he had already called off the negotiations
tinoco said the government's formal response accepted the cardinal's five-point proposal in principle but said it was ``indispensable to arrive at a definition and agreement'' on his cease-fire plan
under the cardinal's plan, the rebels would be confined to certain ``enclaves or zones'' during a 30-day cease-fire, while talks on a permanent truce continued
in exchange for the cease-fire, the government would:
_ grant a ``full, general amnesty'' to several thousand political prisoners in nicaraguan jails, including members of the national guard of former dictator gen. anastasio somoza, whom the sandinistas overthrew in 1979
_ permit unrestricted freedom of the press, a right now granted only to some media
_ ``reconsider'' a mandatory military draft law, which has provoked violent protests in several nicaraguan cities
_ reopen talks with the internal opposition, represented by 14 political parties and a coalition of business, labor and political groups known as the democratic coordinate. those talks broke off late last year
the first round of direct peace talks between the two sides took place in san jose, costa rica, in late january, a week before the u.s. house rejected president reagan's latest request for $36.2 million in contra aid
participants characterized that meeting as cordial but lacking in progress
the sandinistas and the contras came to guatemala city stating that they were still far apart on the question of which should come first, a cease-fire or democratic reforms in nicaragua
the negotiations are being held in accordance with a central american peace plan signed by five of the region's presidents last august
the reagan administration was accused in court papers friday of continuing to force employees to sign agreements not to disclose classified information despite a one-year moratorium imposed by congress
the american foreign service association filed a motion in u.s. district court for a preliminary injunction to force secretary of state george schultz to stop ordering state department employees to sign one of the non-disclosure forms
the injunction sought by the plaintiffs would also direct cia director william webster and steven garfinkel, head of the information security oversight office, to order other federal agencies to stop forcing employees to sign the forms
one of the forms, sf 189, binds federal employees never to divulge classified or classifiable information without permission. more than 1.7 million federal employees in sensitive jobs have signed the form
the other form, sf 4193, also requires employees to seek ``prepublication review of contemplated disclosures.''
critics in congress contend the forms violate the first amendment rights of government employees. these critics argue that inclusion of ``classifiable information'' give agencies the power to punish whistleblowers by classifying information after it has already been disclosed
when it passed the continuing resolution for the 1988 fiscal year, congress said no money could be used during the fiscal year to force employees to sign the agreements or other nondisclosure forms
the brief charged that ``numerous employees have been required to sign forms sf 189 and sf 4193 since the passage of the continuing resolution.''
the plaintiffs charged that a division of the navy last month ordered its employees to sign one of the forms and the air force issued a directive last month saying ``that signing sf 189 is a prerequisite to access to classified information.''
foreign service officers, who are members of the american foreign service association, are still being required to sign sf 4193, the court papers charged
the administration has continued to implement the standard forms at issue in this case, despite congress' explicit direction in the continuing resolution that all such implementation efforts must cease. such illegal conduct should not be allowed to continue,'' the lawsuit said
sikh separatists set off bombs near courthouses in four major cities in punjab state friday, killing nine people and injuring more than 60, police said
three other people were shot to death in separate attacks in the northern state, where militant sikhs are waging a war for an independent homeland. more than 230 people have been killed this year in violence blamed on sikhs
police in new delhi issued a ``red alert'' after the explosions and asked people not to touch abandoned objects such as boxes, bags and briefcases
ravi pawar, a police spokesman, said intelligence information indicated that sikh terrorists may be planning to explode bombs in busy areas in the capital
the bombs in punjab blew up in or near courthouse compounds in the cities of gurdaspur, amritsar, patiala and hoshiarpur, killing nine people. fifty people were detained in the sikh holy city of amritsar for questioning in connection with one explosion, police reports said
in patiala, a powerful bomb blew up in a soda water factory in front of the district court building, killing three hindus and injuring one
the blast at a courthouse in hoshiarpur killed three people, including a woman, police said. two others were injured
j.p. birdhi, senior superintendent of police in gurdaspur, said two people died and 33 people were injured, six of them seriously, in a blast there
in amritsar, assailants lobbed a bomb over a wall into a crowd outside the court. one person was killed and 19 others were wounded, said izhar alam, the city police chief
he said a homemade bomb was discovered inside a liquor bottle left in a cinema hall filled with 200 people. it was turned over to bomb experts and no one was injured
also friday, four sikh extremists gunned down a security guard at a bank in patiala, police said
sikhs are a religious minority in india, representing 2 percent of the 780 million population, but they are a majority in punjab state
the state has been under direct federal rule since prime minister rajiv gandhi dismissed the moderate sikh state government last year for failing to curb terrorism
more than 1,000 people were killed last year in attacks blamed on sikhs. from pentagon officials</note>
the pentagon acknowledged late friday that the marine officer kidnapped in lebanon earlier this week was a former military aide to the secretary of defense
a spokesman dismissed suggestions, however, that the capture of lt. col. william ``rich'' higgins posed any type of major security risk to the united states
higgins was the junior military assistant to defense secretary caspar w. weinberger for two years, said dan howard, the pentagon's chief spokesman. weinberger resigned nov. 5 and was succeeded by frank carlucci
as weinberger's assistant from june 1985 to june 1987, higgins had access to and handled a variety of classified documents, but was only one of 36 individuals ``who worked in the immediate office of the secretary handling administrative work,'' howard said
higgins was kidnapped on wednesday in lebanon, where he was assigned to temporary duty with the united nations heading a group of observers attached to the u.n. truce supervision organization
howard provided a statement to reporters late friday after radio free lebanon broadcast a story in arabic quoting unnamed amal shiite moslems as saying higgins had ``an association with weinberger.''
the spokesman said the pentagon had played down higgins' background over the past two days because it did not want to aggravate the situation surrounding his kidnapping
but the united states does not believe he was kidnapped because he once worked for weinberger, howard said, nor were any restrictions violated in allowing him to leave a post in the defense secretary's office for another assignment in a country like lebanon
there was no restriction that was broken by his accepting this assignment,'' howard said. ``he (previously) handled paperwork and other administrative duties
there are no restrictions on where middle-grade officers like lt. col. higgins can be assigned following pentagon duty. his understanding of political-military affairs and his administrative abilities made him well suited for the (u.n.) position
howard said that ``for the moment, we prefer to focus our attention on his prompt and safe return, rather than on unproductive speculation on how and why this particular individual found himself in this predicament.''
asked then if the administration equated higgins' disappearance to the kidnapping of william buckley several years ago, howard replied: ``no.''
buckley was the cia station chief in lebanon and was later tortured and murdered by his kidnappers
higgins, 43, is a native of danville, ky., whose wife and daughter now live in northern virginia. his wife, robin, is a major in the marine corps
a decorated combat veteran of vietnam, higgins has alternated between field positions and staff jobs in washington through most of his career. after graduating from the air force command and staff college in 1980, higgins assumed a post in the plans division at marine corps headquarters
in june 1981, he was transferred to the pentagon and to the second-level staff serving the secretary and deputy secretary of defense. in 1982, he became the military assistant for interagency matters under the pentagon's executive secretary, meaning he was responsible for coordinating weinberger's meetings with other cabinet officials and the national security council
after leaving that post and graduating from the national war college in 1985, higgins became the junior military assistant on weinberger's personal staff
the secretary of defense normally has two such personal military aides _ one an admiral or general and the other a lower-ranking officer such as higgins
higgins remained in the job with weinberger until june 1987, when he assumed the u.n. assigment. update with pentagon statement saying higgins had worked for weinberger. picks up 5th graf pvs bgng: fewer than ...</note>
president reagan said friday that americans will not be pulled out of the u.n. observer group in lebanon despite the threat of terrorism and the kidnapping of marine lt. col. william r. higgins
reagan made his statement after defense secretary frank c. carlucci said in a television interview that u.s. officials were studying whether americans should be withdrawn from lebanon because of the abduction of higgins by gunmen in southern lebanon
the president said he was reluctant to answer questions during a photo-taking session in the oval office, but that ``on this particular subject, i feel i must straighten it out.''
denying that americans would be pulled out, reagan said, ``we are going to meet our obligations to the united nations.''
meanwhile, the pentagon acknowledged friday evening that higgins had been a military aide to the secretary of defense. a spokesman dismissed suggestions that higgins' capture posed a major security risk to the united states, and said he did not believe higgins' capture had anything to do with the fact that he had been a junior military assistant to defense secretary caspar weinberger
dan howard, the pentagon spokesman, said higgins ``handled paperwork and other administrative duties'' for weinberger from june 1985 to june 1987. he said the administration did not equate higgins' capture to that of william buckley several years ago. buckley was the cia station chief in lebanon when he was captured, tortured and murdered by his kidnappers
the pentagon provided a statement on higgins' background after radio free lebanon broadcast a story quoting unnamed amal shiite moslems as saying higgins had ``an association with weinberger.''
fewer than 20 americans are assigned to u.n. duties along the lebanese-israeli border, according to the state department
reagan said u.n. forces had been in lebanon since 1949. ``we're very definitely a part of the united nations.''
speaking about the threat of terrorism, the president said, ``of course we worry because we know that terrorists around the world targeted us as one of their targets.''
as reporters left the room, reagan turned to his guest, west german chancellor helmut kohl, and said, ``they didn't ask the question i wanted them to ask.'' reagan indicated he wanted to elaborate on his comment thursday that he wanted to ``rescue'' higgins
however, when reporters shouted a question about the ``rescue'' remark as the president left for a weekend at camp david, he did not respond
administration officials already had clarified reagan's remark, saying he was referring to diplomatic efforts through the united nations and governments in the region. reagan's comment to kohl was picked up by a boom microphone
