rene char, called ``the greatest french poet of the 20th century'' by premier jacques chirac, died in paris friday, according to the publishing company gallimard. he was 80
gallimard said he died at the military hospital of val-de-grace. it did not disclose the cause of death
among char's most famous poems are ``hammer without a master,'' written in 1934, and ``return uphill,'' written in 1966
hammer without a master'' was later set to music by pierre boulez
char also wrote criticism and plays for nearly half a century
rene char was without doubt the greatest french poet of the 20th century,'' chirac said in a statement
char is to be buried tuesday in isle-sur-la-sorgue, the provencal village where he was born on june 14, 1907
his poetry borrowed imagery from nature and from his childhood in southern france
after completing his education at the university in aix-en-provence, he moved to paris where he became friendly with the surrealists andre breton and paul eluard
char also was friends with the artists pablo picasso, georges braque and nicolas de stael
he fought against the forces of rebel general francisco franco in the spanish civil war and led a resistance unit in the french alps during world war ii under the nom de guerre ``captain alexander.''
he was later awarded the medal of the resistance and the croix de guerre and was named to the legion of honor
in 1945, char moved to the luberon mountains, not far from his birthplace
in our darkness, there is not a place for beauty,'' he once said. ``every place is for beauty.'' to update with debates; inserts 6 grafs after 17th graf pvs bgng: the democrats ... and subs grafs 18-20th pvs bgng: on the ... with 5 grafs to update. picks up 21st graf pvs bgng: dole, campaigning ..., editing to tighten. ^by rita beamish</note>
vice president george bush suggested friday that gop presidential rival bob dole was ``angry and bitter'' over his loss in new hampshire but dole countered ``we'll see who's dispirited'' after tuesday's midwestern contests. democratic national chairman paul kirk told his squabbling presidential candidates to cool it
the democratic candidates save sen. albert gore jr. debated in st. paul, minn., ahead of the south dakota primary and minnesota caucuses, while the republicans debated over a debate that dwindled to just two candidates
rep. richard gephardt and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis drew fire from their democratic presidential rivals in the free-wheeling debate that indicated their status following wins in iowa and new hampshire
at the republican debate in dallas, reduced to a one-on-one event by the refusal of dole and pat robertson to participate, both bush and rep. jack kemp said they regretted the boycott and said it would hurt their opponents
