if president reagan's proposed budget actually becomes america's budget for 1989, it will mean that the federal government will collect $1,687 in individual income taxes for every man, woman and child in the country
that's an increase of $65 from the budget he presented a year ago, due almost entirely to economic growth
the mathematics are straightforward. divide the $412.4 billion expected through individual income taxes during the year by 244.4 million people, the u.s. population as of jan. 1. last year, when the total population was 242.1 million, the assumption was that individual income taxes would bring in $392.8 billion
according to the budget proposal reagan sent to capitol hill on thursday, the federal government expects its total receipts in 1989 to be $964.7 billion. besides the personal income tax, the sum includes corporate income taxes of $117.7 billion and social security taxes of $354.6 billion. the rest will come from estate and gift taxes, customs duties, excise taxes and the like
using the same population formula for this year, the total receipts represent $3,947 for everyone from the tiniest to the oldest centenarian
the source of money flowing in to the government has changed greatly in the reagan years, the administration points out. the individual and corporate income tax share of total receipts in 1989 is expected to be 4.7 percentage points less than 1980 when three out of every five dollars came from income taxes
the administration tagged two displaced worker programs for extinction because they have not ``operated efficiently to help workers adjust.''
one provides unemployment benefit payments when unemployment insurance runs out. the administration feels those additional weeks of payments ``encourage workers to delay efforts to seek new opportunities in the hope that somehow their old jobs will reappear.'' in the current year, the program cost $48 million in federal money
the second program, costing $287 million in 1988, pays states for helping dislocated workers find new occupations that use their skills, get training in new skills or meet the cost of looking for jobs. that money, says the budget, should go into a new worker readjustment program
the administration also wants to drop a work incentive program that provided job services, training and public service employment to welfare recipients
although its aim is to help curb welfare dependency, it has not proved successful or cost-effective,'' the proposal said. the government budgeted $93 million for the program this year
reagan's budget proposal for 1988 asked congress to tack on $1 for every ticket for international travel to and from the united states to be used for a government program that encourages foreign travel to the united states
congress did not pass the legislation last year and the administration wants it brought up again
money for recreation is to be cut back under the proposal from $1.7 billion this year to $1.4 billion
to make that cut, the administration wants to reduce the amount spent for buying land from $232 million to $51 million. and it proposes a halt in buying some land for park and refuge purposes through 1993 _ except for wetlands acquired with revenue from sale of duck hunting stamps and the like
the budget also makes clear that pardons are on the increase. last year, there were only 23 pardons granted by the president. that number is estimated to increase to 50 this fiscal year and 50 again in the next. there was no explanation. the number of ``denials and no actions,'' _ 290 in 1987 _ is expected to increase slightly to 300 this year and next
coniston partners indicated today it would try to place four representatives on the gillette co. board of directors, escalating its strategy of pressuring the company into a merger or restructuring
a group led by the investment partnership, which holds a 6 percent stake in gillette, said it intended to solicit proxies from gillette shareholders to place candidates on the board of directors
in disclosing its gillette stake last thursday, coniston indicated it might seek representation on the board as part of a strategy to force an increase in gillette's share value
coniston would be unable to take control of gillette's board, because only a third of the seats are up for election in any year. but analysts say a coniston victory in the proxy fight could pressure the board to accede to the group's demands that it meet with potential merger partners
gillette stock rose 37{ cents to $39 a share in early trading today on the new york stock exchange
a spokesman at the boston-based consumer products company said gillette had not yet seen the securities and exchange commission filing outlining coniston's plan, and would not comment until it had
coniston also has said it was attempting to meet with potential acquirers of gillette, which long has been a takeover target. gillette has resisted takeover overtures, and reiterated a desire to remain independent last week after coniston made its disclosures
the moves by coniston, which successfully waged a similar strategy against allegis corp. last year, were seen widely as an attempt to force gillette's board to meet with potential merger partners such as revlon group inc., which has had several buyout offers rebuffed by gillette over the past 18 months
keith gollust, a principal in the partnership, said gillette's takeover defenses essentially gave its board of directors unilateral power to accept or reject any merger offers
our position is that shareholders, who really own the company, ought to have the right to make that decision,'' he said
gollust said the group had a telephone conversation with gillette chairman colman m. mockler jr. last week, but mockler did not change the company's prior statements that it wished to remain independent. pvs, the spending; minor editing thruout.</note>
the democratic chairman of the senate budget committee today praised parts of the $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget president reagan submitted to congress, but warned that the proposal left tough deficit fighting for future administrations
sen. lawton chiles, d-fla., said that domestic spending increases proposed by the president in programs he has tried cutting in the past showed a white house shift toward congressional priorities
after eight years, it looks like you've finally seen the light on education, drug enforcement, health and the environment,'' chiles told white house budget director james c. miller iii, who was appearing before the senate budget panel
but chiles also warned that the national debt, now about $2.5 trillion, was rapidly growing and would have to be dealt with soon. he said efforts to control the deficit would have to go beyond the so-called budget summit agreement reached last november between reagan and congressional leaders
the job facing the next president will make last year look like a walk down primrose lane,'' chiles said
the house budget committee chairman, rep. william h. gray iii, speaking on ``cbs this morning,'' gave the spending plan ``a passing grade in that sense that it's closer to congressional priorities.''
the pennsylvania democrat cited the budget's slowed increases in defense spending and relaxed restraints on domestic spending as factors in its favor
the spending plan contains a deficit of $129.5 billion, less than the $136 billion target required by the gramm-rudman balanced budget law. the government would spend $1.094 trillion, while taking in $965 billion in receipts
if the budget were enacted intact, the government would have to collect $1,687 in individual income taxes for every person in the country _ $65 more would have been required under reagan's 1988 budget. such an increase, however, is attributable almost entirely to economic growth
appearing with gray, miller attributed the mild capitol hill reaction to the budget summit agreement
we had 20 days and 20 nights of real hard negotiating,'' he said. ``that's half the time noah spent on the ark.''
under that agreement, drawn in the aftermath of the october stock market crash, legislators and the administration set this budget's overall spending ceilings for military, domestic and foreign aid spending. in addition, reagan already has signed $14 billion in new 1989 taxes called for in the pact
with 1988 an election year, lawmakers are unlikely to insist on revisiting those painful subjects
it's like tying two cats by the tail and throwing them over the clothesline,'' sen. ernest hollings, d-s.c., a member of the senate budget committee, told reporters. ``there'll be a lot of small intramurals, but nothing really's going to happen.''
house minority leader bob michel, r-ill., added, ``although i have always felt that more could be cut from the budget through a (spending) freeze, i think our first responsibility is to affirm the summit agreement.''
others, however, predicted that although the budget's overall shape appears settled, skirmishes will be fought over how that money is divided up
it's a little like looking at a trojan horse,'' said chiles. ``it's an attractive horse, but you've got to look on the inside.''
reagan's budget contains proposals that pleased many lawmakers:
_spending to combat aids is increased by more than one-third to $1.3 billion
_education gets a $1.5 billion boost to $20.3 billion
_the national aeronautics and space administration's budget grows nearly 20 percent to $11 billion
_$2.5 billion is provided for a five-year fight against acid rain
but there are spending slashes in other programs that congress has rejected before and is likely to ignore again
the president would:
_end $600 million in federal subsidies for amtrak, the passenger railroad
_reduce mass transit aid from $3.3 billion to $1.4 billion
_eliminate the $200 million urban development action grants program
_sell government assets such as loan portfolios, the alaska power administration and the naval petroleum reserve
the battle will be fought on domestic differences,'' said gray
the budget is also the first submitted by reagan that does not allow pentagon spending to keep abreast of inflation. thus, it allows a military spending increase from $285.4 billion to $294 billion in fiscal 1989, and contains a reduction in the size of active-duty forces and drops the goal of a 600-ship navy
it does, however, grant servicemen and women 4.3 percent pay raise, well above the 2 percent granted other federal employees
the performance of the economy will be a weighty factor in determining how docile the 1989 budget wars will be
the budget's expected $129.5 billion deficit is based on projections by the white house office of management and budget. it projects healthy economic growth, along with continuing low interest rates, inflation and unemployment, which taken together mean lower government spending and higher government revenues
the congressional budget office, which studies the budget for congress, expects a weaker economic performance this year and has projected a $176 billion deficit
chiles said he expected congress to be able to adhere to the budget summit agreement unless ``the economy totally goes south.''
others, however, were critical of omb's projections, but conceded that lawmakers had little taste this year for tackling the massive deficit slashing that would be needed if cbo's forecast is accurate
this is the year of the big wink, the high art of blue smoke and mirrors,'' said rep. dan rostenkowski, d-ill., chairman of the tax-writing ways and means committee
if the lower deficit projection proves accurate, it could be the third consecutive drop in federal red ink. since reaching a record $221 billion in 1986, the deficit fell to $150 billion last year and is expected to fall to $146 billion this year
one possible bone of contention is the promise reagan has made to try to cancel spending for fiscal 1988 _ which began oct. 1 _ on several spending projects that lawmakers obtained for their home districts. the president is expected to raise the issue next week
