grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower today on the chicago board of trade
most of the markets were down only slightly, but wheat was off as much as 5\ cents a bushel within a few minutes of the opening bell
demand for wheat typically weakens in late winter and early spring, and the futures market is anticipating a corresponding drop in prices, said walter spilka, an analyst in new york for smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
people are expecting the seasonal downturn in wheat,'' spilka said. ``they're looking for it and looking for it and when they see signs of weakening, you get a kind of bandwagon effect.''
wheat futures prices have mostly advanced for the past eight months. a down day today would mark the fourth straight day of steady or lower wheat prices
in early trading, wheat was 3} cents to 5\ cents lower with the contract for delivery in march at $3.16{ a bushel; corn was { cent lower to \ cent higher with march at $2.00{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1\ cents lower with march at $1.90} a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with march at $6.27{ a bushel
