livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on thursday
stock market investors face a quandary these days when they look for ways to profit from the revival of american manufacturing
practically no one disputes that ``smokestack america'' _ makers of steel, paper, chemicals, machinery and so forth _ has made an impressive comeback from its woes of the early to mid-1980s
the dollar's decline in currency markets has improved the competitive position of american manufacturers in world markets and given a needed boost to u.s. exports
furthermore, in the lean years many companies in this sector of the economy cut costs, increased productivity and ``restructured'' themselves to concentrate on operations with the most promising potential
while business was bad, there was little incentive to expand capacity. so now that business is better, manufacturers often find the facilities they have running at full tilt with order backlogs growing
this, in turn, creates a climate in which a company can enjoy what wall street analysts call ``pricing flexibility'' _ the opportunity to increase prices and profits
all this adds up to what any experienced investor would regard as a classic opportunity
while falling inflation and lower interest rates provided the dominant themes of the 1982-87 bull market, many analysts say the story today and for the future is manufacturing
there's one problem with that view, however. manufacturing is by long-standing tradition closely tied to the ups and downs of the business cycle. and if there is going to be a recession, as so many people are predicting right now, manufacturing would appear to be standing directly in its path
in january, notes rao chalasani, an analyst at prescott, ball &amp; turben inc., a cleveland-based investment firm, an index he maintains of 31 manufacturing stocks fell 5.8 percent while the dow jones industrial average gained about 1 percent
that action came amid other signs that recession fears were increasing in the securities markets _ among them a drop in interest rates and in the price of gold
nevertheless, putting aside the question of where the economical cycle stands, many analysts argue that there is a strong ``secular,'' or long-term, case for being bullish on american manufacturing
investment strategy decisions frequently key off of the business cycle,'' said robert salomon at salomon brothers in a commentary on the subject. ``occasionally, however, a secular trend takes hold
we believe that the revival of the u.s. manufacturing sector represents the beginning of a secular trend of a proportion similar to the disinflation trend experienced earlier in this decade.''
maintains chalasani on a similar note: ``the fundamental secular trend will remain for many years. numerous factors can temporarily check it, but it can be derailed only by cascading financial accidents.''
salomon says that a recession is likely next year, but that the forces in the economy emphasizing production and deemphasizing consumption could shape it into something considerably different from the typical down phase of the business cycle
if export growth partly offsets weakness in the domestic economy, as we believe is likely, areas of the economy that are typically weak during an economic contraction _ notably the cyclical sectors _ may show surprising strength,'' he reasons
at the same time, he says, ``some consumption-oriented industries _ traditionally perceived as defensive investments _ may not be the safe havens that they have been in other times
on balance, the positive secular trend evident in the manufacturing sector will, to some extent, offset (or at least dampen) the near-term cyclical weakness.''
