bond prices barely budged friday in light trading that brokers attributed to lack of significant news and reluctance to buy or sell until more economic statistics are revealed later this month
the treasury's key 30-year issue rose about $1.25 per $1,000 in face amount. its yield, which moves inversely to price, eased to 8.43 percent from 8.44 percent late thursday
it seemed pretty quiet around here today,'' said carol stone, senior economist at nomura securities inc. in new york. ``i think people are waiting for some news they might learn next week.''
the commerce department is scheduled to report january factory orders tuesday, revised fourth-quarter gross national product thursday, and january consumer price index friday
those statistics could provide further insight into whether the economy is heading into a recession, as some analysts fear, or is growing vigorously and possibly inciting inflation
an economic slowdown would imply lower interest rates and likely help bond prices. conversely, signs of inflation would imply higher interest rates and tend to depress bond prices
in the secondary market for treasury bonds, prices of short-term governments were unchanged, while intermediate and long-term maturities rose [ point, the financial information service telerate inc. reported
the movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a bond with a $1,000 face value
the merrill lynch daily treasury index, which measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities of a year or longer, rose 0.04 to 113.31. the shearson lehman daily treasury bond index, which makes a similar measurement, rose 0.42 to 1,184.74
among corporate bonds, industrials and utilities were unchanged to slightly higher in light trading
moody's investment grade corporate bond index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.59 to 282.87
among tax-exempt municipal bonds, general obligations and dollar bonds both rose about \ point in extremely light trading
yields on three-month treasury bills fell 1 point to 5.67 percent. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. six-month bills fell 4 basis points to 5.95 percent and year bills fell 1 basis point to 6.24 percent
the federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 611-16 percent, up from 6| percent late thursday
an ``extremely upset'' wall street trader was charged with weapons possession and witness intimidation friday after authorities alleged he plotted an attack on convicted financier ivan f. boesky with a loaded semi-automatic rifle
the arrest of john a. mulheren marked the first public indication of potential violence in a financial scandal surrounding boesky and suggested that government investigators are closer to making new arrests
mulheren, a general partner in the firm jamie securities co., was seized near his rumson, n.j. home thursday in possession of an israeli-made semi-automatic rifle, said monmouth county assistant prosecutor alton kenney
mulheren was ordered held in lieu of $17,500 bail after a hearing friday
a complaint filed against mulheren in freehold alleged the weapon was to be used ``unlawfully against the person or property'' of boesky, a former financier whose downfall more than a year ago shook the financial world
the complaint also mentioned a possible attack against michael davidoff, a former head trader for boesky who is cooperating in a government investigation of the financial scandal
authorities declined to say why they believed mulheren was plotting against boesky and davidoff, but mulheren once was a close associate of boesky and reportedly has been implicated in the government's investigation
meanwhile in manhattan, federal prosecutors charged mulheren in a two-count criminal complaint with attempting to intimidate a cooperating witness, who was identified only as witness x, formerly employed by boesky. they refused to confirm or deny that witness x is davidoff
the federal complaint quoted mulheren's wife as telling police he had been ``extremely upset by the boesky situation'' and ``was armed and was going to get'' witness x
the complaint said when police seized mulheren, they found the loaded rifle as well as army fatigue-type clothing in a bag in his car
boesky's whereabouts weren't immediately clear and he could not be reached for comment. his attorney harvey l. pitt did not return two telephone calls seeking comment. a secretary said he was out of the office
in november 1986 boesky paid a record $100 million to settle a securities and exchange commission complaint of insider trading, the misuse of private information to profit in securities transactions. he was banished from the securities business for life
last april, boesky pleaded guilty to a criminal charge of conspiracy to lie to the sec, for which he was sentenced to a three-year prison term in december. he's scheduled to start serving the sentence next month
boesky has been the government's chief source of information in a probe of other wall street professionals
last september, the wall street journal quoted unidentified people it said were familiar with the investigation as saying mulheren was cooperating with the government as a result of boesky's disclosures
the newspaper also said without attribution that the investigation could lead to civil and criminal charges against mulheren
fred m. stone, a lawyer for jamie, said the company's partners are discussing a course of action in the wake of mulheren's arrest. stone declined to say how many partners were involved in jamie
stone also released a statement from mulheren's new york attorney otto obermaier
it is known that john mulheren has been upset by the investigation by regulatory authorities of securities activities and by the rumors and publicity which developed which he felt unfairly impugned his honesty and integrity,'' obermaier said
the important thing now is for him to get help and support to permit him to resume a normal and constructive life. he is in the process of seeking required medical assistance,'' said obermaier's statement
the new jersey complaint named mulheren on charges of unlawful possession of weapon and intent to use the weapon unlawfully, said kenney
the possession charge carries a maximum sentence of five years in prison and $7,500 in fines, while the other charge carries a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and $100,000 in fines upon conviction, the prosecutor said
kenny said federal authorities in manhattan had filed papers to arrest mulheren if he posted the local bail
kenney said rumson police went to mulheren's home thursday and received permission from his wife to search the family car, where police seized a 9mm pistol, a .357-caliber magnum revolver and a shotgun. but mulheren was not arrested then because he was licensed for the weapons
police began watching mulheren afterward and later thursday stopped him in his car after he left home
kenney said police found a satchel in the car containing the semi-automatic rifle
the prosecutor said mulheren was then arrested because the rifle was ``clearly not a sportsmen's weapon'' and, although such firearms can be owned in new jersey, a permit is needed to carry them off private property
eastman kodak co. said friday its innovative 9-volt lithium batteries, which were supposed to have a shelf life of 10 years, don't last that long
until the problem is corrected, they won't have a storage life of 10 years,'' said kodak spokesman henry kaska. ``but i don't think the average consumer is going to run into any difficulty.''
the company said the problem does not affect the use life of the batteries, only the amount of time they can sit on store shelves
the news prompted black &amp; decker corp. to announce immediate plans friday to stop selling mini-flashlights that were designed to exclusively use kodak's 9-volt lithium batteries
we're very concerned with selling the best possible product and we relied on kodak's word,'' said barbara lucas, a spokeswoman for the baltimore-based company. ``we can't very well continue to be associated with something like this.''
she said the company planned to notify dealers and ask them to pull the lite years flashlights, introduced last year, and the recently-announced just-for-me line off the shelves immediately
she didn't know how many products would have to be pulled off the shelves, but said the lite years line had been selling well
when the unique batteries were introduced last year, kodak touted them as lasting twice as long as 9-volt alkaline batterie and having a 10-year shelf life
however, routine testing last week by kodak determined the batteries don't last that long on store shelves or in car glove compartments, especially when they're used in ``high-drain'' products such as flashlights, kaska said
kodak officials, who told black &amp; decker about the problem, said the shortened shelf life is caused by a buildup of resistance inside the battery that prevents full current from being transmitted
the problem is much more noticeable in products where a great deal of current is needed, rather than ``medium drain'' products, like smoke detectors or calculators
kaska said the problem would be corrected, however, within a few weeks, and the claim of 10 years of shelf life would be accurate once again
we understand the problem. we know how to fix it and will do so quickly,'' said james moxley, president of ultra technologies, the kodak subsidiary that makes and sells batteries
he said the problem, which was discovered last week in ongoing storage-life tests, does not affect how long the batteries can be used, only the amount of time they can be stored
the less-than-predicted storage life will be corrected by changing the electrolytic chemical used in the batteries, moxley said
as a matter of good business ethics, we reported the results of our tests to black &amp; decker,'' he said. ``obviously, we are disappointed by the company's action.''
